Follicular lymphoma with marginal zone differentiation. The tumor follicles are back-to-back, poorly circumscribed and surrounded by a band of marginal zone differentiation.

The distal duodenal aspect of the total gastrectomy reveals normal duodenum with Brunner glands at the base of the duodenal mucosa and normal antrum, with the typical antral 50/50 ratio of surface foveolar epithelium to deeper mucinous glands. The proximal margin of the gastrectomy demonstrates massive foveolar hyperplasia extending to the squamocolumnar gastroesophageal junction.

Histopathology of kidney mass showing clear cell carcinoma.
A biopsy of the stomach showed moderately to poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma and signet-ring cell carcinoma.

Metastatic follicular thyroid carcinoma (FTC) in the femur.
Malignant mesotheliomas in the pleural/mediastinal cavity showing invasion of the myocardium.
Histopathology section showing squamous mucosa infiltrated by a high-grade lymphoma.

Scanning view of the thyroid mass showing tumor cells forming varied-sized follicles with densely eosinophilic colloid within the follicle lumen, consistent with follicular variant papillary thyroid carcinoma.
Rectal adenocarcinoma microscopic sections show foci of comedonecrosis.
Carcinosarcoma.
Representative section revealed basophile hyaline chondroid matrix, typical lobulated architecture, increased cellularity, and mild cellular atypia, consistent with low-grade chondrosarcoma.
Photomicrograph demonstrating lung adenocarcinoma cells with hyperchromatic nuclei and eosinophilic cytoplasm.
The recurrent metastatic cervical lymph node was diagnosed of papillary thyroid carcinoma, follicular variant (PTC-FV). Pathologic section showed few papillae formation.
Histopathological findings of lung adenocarcinoma.
Histological appearance of MALT lymphoma in HCV-seropositive cases using hematoxylin and eosin staining.
Histopathology of ovarian high-grade serous carcinoma showing nuclear pleomorphism and frequent mitotic figures. Nuclear atypia is characteristic of high-grade tumors. 40× magnification.
Normal colon mucosa on the left with the margin of tumor on the right containing large, atypical cells consistent with adenocarcinoma.
Cancellous bone and malignant, lace-like osteoid formation by the spindled sarcomatous cells and in between these cells chondroid matrix (HE, × 100) .

Spleen: Nodular hyperplasia (lymphoid follicle). Nodular hyperplasia is essentially focal proliferation of various types of splenic components compressing slightly normal splenic tissues, although a large aggregation of lymphocytes is the main feature. The nodule takes an appearance like a giant follicle without the normal structures of a lymph follicle such as a central artery, periarterial lymphoid sheath (PALS) or germinal center. The follicles out of the nodule are normal. There is no evidence to support that this lesion progresses to lymphoma.
Histology of the endometrial carcinoma shows an endometrioid pattern with an open chromatin pattern and prominent nucleoli.

Histology of the biopsy taken from an endobronchial tumor shows atypical cell clusters with oval and polygonal cells mixed with blood. Cells contain enlarged, hyperchromatic, pleomorphic nuclei and eosinophilic cytoplasm, and prominent nucleoli, compatible with adenocarcinoma of the lung.
Microphotography showing angiosarcomatous proliferation made of endothelial cells.
Follicular T-cell lymphoma. Lymph nodes show a nodular/follicular growth pattern.
Photographs of malignant epithelioid mesothelioma showing large tubular and dyscohesive patterns.
Photomicrograph showing metastatic cholangiocarcinoma composed of duct-like structures lined by cuboidal or columnar cells with high pleomorphism, surrounded by dense stromal reaction.
Adenocarcinoma with adjacent normal colonic tissue.
Histology slide showing a region of glioblastoma exhibiting hypercellularity, cytologic pleomorphism, intratumoral hemorrhage, and occasional mitotic activity.
Histology of myxoid liposarcoma showing a variable number of adipocytes and a prominent capillary pattern.
In situ miR-4653-3p hybridization. Pancreatic ductal adenocarcinomas were diffusely and strongly positive for miR-4653-3p expression.
Lymphoblastic lymphoma showing intermediate-sized immature lymphocytes, dense chromatin, and scant cytoplasm.

The Pathological image of the well differentiated liposarcoma.

Histology from tumor tissue in the lumbar column confirmed a pleomorphic biphasic glial tumor as diagnosed earlier, compatible with metastases from gliosarcoma, WHO grade IV.

Dedifferentiated chondrosarcoma is characterized by the coexistence of low-grade chondrosarcoma components and high-grade dedifferentiated components with features of undifferentiated sarcoma, with a distinct border.
Pigmented melanoma metastasis constituted from pleomorphic epithelioid cells.

Esophageal squamous epithelium with lymphocytic infiltrate in the basal layer and scattered apoptotic keratinocytes (Civatte bodies).

(A) The macroscopic specimen obtained by endoscopic mucosal resection revealed that the tumors were composed of a great proliferation of lymph follicles whose germinal center was in the  lamina propria . (B) A large lymph follicle squeezed the normal ducts, but no findings of malignant lymphoma with destruction of normal duct structure or lymphoepithelial lesions were seen

Histological patterns of splenic marginal zone lymphoma (SMZL). Biphasic pattern: small lymphocytes surround and replace the white pulp follicles and merge with a peripheral zone of larger marginal zone (MZ)-like cells, including scattered transformed blasts, giving the characteristic biphasic pattern.
Para-common iliac lymph node metastasis of prostate cancer: localized adenocarcinoma with a cribriform growth pattern.
Biopsy of the esophagus showing cells with hyperchromatic nuclei, scanty cytoplasm, pleomorphic cells, and bizarre cells suggestive of poorly differentiated carcinoma.
Hematoxylin and Eosin (H&E) stain of sarcoma.

Tall cell variant of papillary thyroid carcinoma exhibits elongated follicular and closely packed papillary growth patterns. Tall cells display prominent cell membranes, dense eosinophilic cytoplasm, and nuclear features typical of papillary carcinoma.

Low-power view reveals typical periosteal osteosarcoma features, which consisted of lobules of neoplastic cartilage and myxoid matrix, surrounded by a fibrous membrane; the cartilage composed of atypical chondroblastic cells.

Histological findings of the non-small cell lung cancer and renal cell carcinoma. (A) Lung: sheets or islands of large polygonal malignant cells with pink cytoplasm and distinct cell borders consistent with squamous cell carcinoma are observed (H&E staining, ×200). (B) Kidney: biopsy specimen of the renal mass showed alveolar growth of large polygonal cells with clear cytoplasm, uniform round nuclei, and inconspicuous nucleoli (H&E staining, ×200). Neoplastic cells have clear cytoplasm and are arranged in nests with intervening blood vessels, consistent with clear cell carcinoma.
Microscopic findings of a biopsied hepatic specimen showed primary hepatocellular carcinoma.

Melanoma in situ. Atypical melanocytes are seen predominantly in the basal portion of the epithelium (arrow) and will stain for melanocytic markers, which helps distinguish this lesion from Paget’s disease, which can be architecturally similar. This lesion did show pigmentation (hematoxylin and eosin, x 40 magnification).
Pleomorphic liposarcoma showing Floret cells and malignant lipocytes (Histo., H and E, ×400).

Histopathology from a liver tumor demonstrates hepatocellular carcinoma. Hematoxylin and eosin staining shows tumor cells in a trabecular pattern. The cell plates are three cells thick or wider in most of this tumor.

Histological findings of the amputated specimen show an abrupt transition between the low-grade chondrosarcoma and high-grade dedifferentiated sarcoma components. The cartilaginous portion of the tumor shows a grade 1 or grade 2 chondrosarcoma with bone destruction. The lesion is composed of spindle cells arranged in a fascicular growth pattern, resembling a high-grade undifferentiated pleomorphic sarcoma.
Concordant PD-L1 reactivity in paired histological and cytological specimens from a lung squamous cell carcinoma. Bronchial biopsy, H&E staining, >500–1000 cells.

Hematoxylin and eosin-stained section demonstrates papillary thyroid carcinoma with follicular pattern and nuclear features including grooves, clearing, overlapping, and enlargement, consistent with papillary thyroid carcinoma arising in a solid variant.

Histologic differences between benign giant cell tumor of bone (GCTB), giant cell-rich osteosarcoma, and malignant GCTB. Benign GCTB consists of two cell types: stromal mononuclear spindle cells and multinucleated giant cells (GCs). Arrow shows a GC.

Extranodal marginal zone B-cell lymphoma of mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue (MALT lymphoma): the lymphoma cells infiltrate around reactive B-cell follicles, external to a preserved follicle mantle, in a marginal zone distribution. Marginal zone B cells have characteristics of small and medium size. The majority of patients present with stage I or II disease. The MALT lymphoma and its natural course is indolent and is slow to disseminate; recurrence may involve other extranodal sites.

Histopathological findings showed a high cellularity tumor and prostate adenocarcinoma with a Gleason score of 10 (5 + 5). The resected tissue showed that the tumor cell nuclei are deep stained and characterized by heteromorphism and caryocinesia.

Histopathologic findings of malignant melanoma after repeated recurrent dysplastic nevi. Tumor cell: round to oval nuclei showing mild nuclear pleomorphism with small nucleoli and irregular nuclear membrane. The cytoplasm contains melanin pigmentation. No mitosis is evident (H&E, ×400).

Photomicrography of the esophageal ulcerated lesion showing positivity for synaptophysin. (400X).

High power view of parathyroid carcinoma highlighting marked nuclear pleomorphism with atypical cells, prominent nucleoli, multinucleation, and abundant droplet filled cytoplasm. The chromatin varies from coarse and clumped in overtly malignant cells with marked pleomorphism to finely stippled (“salt and pepper”) in smaller more typical parathyroid tissue.

Distribution of gold nanoparticles (GNPs) after intratumoral injection in a human eye enucleated for uveal melanoma. Note rather diffuse infiltration of orange-colored GNPs within the sheets of tumor cells. The image is stained with hematoxylin and eosin and has a magnification of ×200.
Tubuli seminiferi contorti (testis) and nuclei of rhabdomyoblasts and parts of myxoid stroma (rhabdomyosarcoma) appear green.

Histolological appearance of the anal melanoma.  A bulky, polypoid mass predominantly involving lamina propria and submucosa was seen. The tumor showed focal intraepithelial lentiginous component, best interpreted as melanoma in situ (H & E, 4×).

Nanoparticles may be detected through light microscopy by using chemical staining protocols that are conventionally employed in histopathology. For example, clusters of iron oxide nanoparticles can be visualized in HE-stained tissue sections as a finely granular brown material within the cells of a glioblastoma tumor.
Histopathologic findings of various durations of esophageal cryotherapy show necrosis and edema involving the layers of the submucosa and the mucularis propria.
Left renal cell carcinoma showing typical clear cell carcinoma.
Nodular melanoma with nodular growth and a prominent vertical component to the invasion of the tumor.
Nevoid melanoma has the architecture of a banal compound nevus. Diagnostic clues included.

H&E staining of Adenocarcinoma of the prostate, Gleason grade 6, showing small glands, single layers of nuclei, and lack of polarity of nuclei within the cells.

Photomicrograph of the specimen shows sheets of large cells adjacent to an area of coagulation necrosis, a common finding in biopsies of primary central nervous system post-transplant lymphoproliferative disorder. This monomorphic case could also be called diffuse large B cell lymphoma.
Photomicrograph showing histology of mesothelioma with broad papillae, edematous fibrous cores, and lined by uniform cuboidal cells with vascular invasion.

Primary mediastinal B cell lymphoma - tumor cells are round to ovoid with abundant clear cytoplasm.
The primary axillary tumor was cytologically compatible with undifferentiated pleomorphic sarcoma that focally showed discohesive and relatively monotonous round cell components.

Haematoxylin and Eosin staining showing melanosis and not melanoma: this shows light brown powdery pigments to dark brown globules which are mainly present in the cytoplasm, partially or completely obscuring the nuclei. There is no evidence of any pigment deposit in the lamina propria.

Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma (DLBCL) in the pleural cavity with aggregates of large atypical lymphocytes having irregular nuclei with uneven chromatin and small to large nucleoli in a necrotic background. Some cells show multilobulated nuclei.

Histopathologic examination of the primary and metastatic duodenal adenocarcinoma by hematoxylin–eosin staining reveals a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma penetrating the visceral peritoneum and invading the pancreas.

Well differentiated papillary mesothelioma of the peritoneum. Multiple coarse papillae are present with varying fibrovascular cores and minimal cellular atypia.

Examination reveals scattered cells with clearing of the nuclear cytoplasm, typical of papillary thyroid carcinoma. The striking nuclear pleomorphism is unusual for papillary carcinoma.

Histology of papillary thyroid carcinoma (PTC) showing nuclear changes: chromatin clearing known as 'Orphan Annie eye' nuclei, grooves, intranuclear pseudoinclusions, nucleoli, powdery chromatin, crowding, and overlapping.
At the periphery of the lesion, pagetoid spread of single atypical melanocytes was seen. The diagnosis was changed from SAMPUS to in situ melanoma.
Bronchoscopic biopsy showing classical Hodgkin lymphoma.

Histopathologic examination of the melanoma on the nose shows irregular proliferation of melanocytes in the epidermis and in the dermis, arranged in nests of varying size and shape. Single melanocytes are seen at the dermal epidermal junction and down a hair follicle. The melanocytes are pleomorphic, with some displaying hyperchromatic nuclei, prominent nucleoli, and melanin pigment in their cytoplasm. A mitotic figure is shown.
Hodgkin's lymphoma showing Reed Sternberg cell.
Photomicrograph showing the spindle cells of leiomyosarcoma with multiple abnormal mitosis.
Bronchoalveolar lavage from right lung showing clusters of poorly differentiated carcinoma cells favoring the histology of squamous cell carcinoma.
A group of microphotographs of pulmonary adenocarcinoma showing a cluster of tumor cells.
Low-grade fibromyoid sarcomas are characterized by bland looking spindle cells set in an alternating fibromyxoid matrix.
Histologic section showing large malignant lymphocytes in a T-cell lymphoma. H and E stain at 40 × magnification.

Histopathological features of the sentinel lymph node. Metastatic malignant melanoma was identified. Specific tumor cells showed signet-ring cell appearance as observed in the inset (magnification, ×400) (hematoxylin and eosin stain; magnification, ×100).

Hematoxylin and eosin stain of the retroperitoneal mass (20×). Malignant mesothelioma that is somewhat pleomorphic but mostly epithelioid. Polygonal cells with some spindling are seen. Cells have pleomorphic nuclei, occasionally multinucleated with moderate amount of eosinophilic cytoplasm. Nuclei have a vesicular chromatin pattern with distinct nucleoli. There is no obvious glandular or squamous differentiation.
Hematoxylin and eosin stain demonstrating mucinous adenocarcinoma within prostatic needle core biopsy.
Adenosarcomatous overgrowth area in adenosarcoma: Stromal cells are large and pleomorphic.
Primary cardiac undifferentiated pleomorphic sarcoma with a hypercellular lesion.
Micrograph of the hepatocellular carcinoma on the left, with normal congested hepatic parenchyma on the right.
Upper esophagus, lined by squamous epithelium. Lamina propria is severely infiltrated by mixed inflammatory population (neutrophils, lymphocytes, plasma cells).
Mixed histological type of gastric cancer in WHO classification, showing high differentiated tubular adenocarcinoma mixed with mucinous adenocarcinoma.

Colloid carcinoma or mucinous noncystic carcinoma arising from an IPMN. Large mucin “lakes” representing invasive adenocarcinoma replacing normal pancreatic parenchyma. Clusters of tumor epithelial cells are seen “floated” in the mucin.
A small focus of high-grade prostatic adenocarcinoma with a cribriform pattern.
5 Foxp3 + T regs /high-power field in a primary melanoma with no MMP-23 expression.
Breast core biopsy showed grade 3 breast invasive ductal carcinoma.
Pathological examination of a specimen from the breast showed scirrhous carcinoma, a grade II invasive ductal carcinoma.
Infiltration of malignant looking lymphoid cells in the lamina propria suggestive of malt lymphoma
Adenocarcinoma with neoplastic pneumocytes having large hyperchromatic nuclei growing along the alveolar walls.
Histological features of angiosarcoma of the bladder: Morphological features including spindle and epithelioid pleomorphic cells.
The configuration of a lesion with tumor budding in T1 esophageal cancer. Many tumor budding foci are present.
Histopathological features of pediatric-type follicular lymphoma include large and irregular lymphoid follicles densely distributed with a starry-sky pattern.

Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma with scattered atypical lymphoid large cells in the background of necrosis. The nuclei are large and darkly stained, round or oval, with rough nuclear chromatin and nuclear debris.
Histopathology showing features of malignant melanoma.
The lymphoid follicles and lymphoid cells infiltrate epidural fat tissue. The histologic diagnosis was non-Hodgkin's follicular lymphoma.
Bone marrow biopsy section showing decreased marrow cellularity with no evidence of lymphoma cell infiltration.
Histological comparison between DLBCL in the patient.
Spitzoid melanoma with effacement of the epidermis and asymmetric pigmentation.
Histological sections of hematoxylin-eosin-stained breast tumor tissue showing invasive ductal carcinoma with tumor grade III and tumor percentage 50%.
Excision of mass showing regions with typical myxoid liposarcoma.
Hematoxylin and eosin staining of omental synovial sarcoma, showing diffuse proliferation of spindle-shaped and small round tumor cells.
Oncocytic Poorly Differentiated Thyroid Carcinoma. These aggressive tumors are characterized by loss of thyroglobulin expression.
Details from a locally advanced thyroid carcinoma with a columnar cell variant of PTC component.
Variability of morphologic details in different examples of peripheral T-cell lymphoma, not otherwise specified (PTCL_NOS).
Photomicrograph showing childhood anaplastic thyroid carcinoma with area of necrosis.
Pathological examination of a specimen from the right axillary lymph node showed metastatic cells from the invasive ductal carcinoma of the breast.
Representative histological slides of mucinous colorectal adenocarcinoma displaying abundant extracellular mucin in a mucinous rectal tumor.
Histologic appearance of the clear cell adenocarcinoma of the colon showing intervillous histiocytic aggregates.
Photomicrograph showing diffuse lymphomatous infiltrate destroying the hair follicles.
The microscopic appearance of glioblastoma multiforme.
Histology of the biopsied mass showing moderately differentiated gastric adenocarcinoma.

Light microscopy image of a glioblastoma multiforme grade IV showing a highly porous neuropil with most of the polymorphous tumor cells surrounded by large cavities. Two isolated blood vessels are apparent by erythrocytes and atypical endothelial cells.

Histological image of osteosarcoma showing nests of tumor cells with a lace-like architecture separated from the rest of the tissue, along with areas of mitosis indicating the aggressive nature of the tumor.
Arrows indicate melanocytes and keratinocytes in melanoma.
High-grade conventional osteosarcoma is observed.
Prostatic stroma with fibrosis and no adenocarcinoma.
Histopathological image showing features suggestive of rhabdomyosarcoma.
Lung squamous cell carcinoma with scattered squamous cells showing abundant cytoplasm, enlarged and darkly stained nuclei, and irregular morphology.
Histologic examination of the lung shows well-differentiated adenocarcinoma with a bronchioloalveolar carcinoma growth pattern in the right upper lobe.
Photomicrographs from representative cases showing Leiomyosarcoma and Epstein-Barr virus-associated smooth muscle tumor (EBV-SMT) stained with Hematoxylin and Eosin (H&E).
Distal esophageal squamous epithelium is replaced by specialized columnar epithelium with goblet cells.

A 29-year-old woman with swelling and stiffness of the left distal radius. Pathological section shows giant cell tumor of the bone with malignant transformation consisting of well-differentiated osteosarcoma (HE 200X).
Abdominal mass biopsy showing mesothelioma.
Poorly differentiated gastric adenocarcinoma with hepatoid features, composed mainly of trabecular and focal glandular formations.
Papillary thyroid cancer cells with typical nuclear changes.
Histopathological findings of resected specimen of the pancreas show moderately to poorly differentiated ductal adenocarcinoma.
Histological findings of the tumor show poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma with dense lymphocytic infiltration, similar to gastric carcinoma with lymphoid stroma.
Kaposi's sarcoma consisting of angiomatoid vascular spaces and abundant spindle-shaped cells.
Focus of prostatic adenocarcinoma within a pelvic lymph node.

Pathological findings of the peritoneal malignant mesothelioma. Higher magnification of the tumor cells showing oval shaped mesothelioma cells, with indistinct border, moderate cytoplasm, and prominent nuclei with inconspicuous nucleoli.

Histopathological features of myxoid liposarcoma: High-grade MLPS with more than 5% cellular overlap, diminished myxoid matrix, less apparent capillary vasculature, a higher nuclear grade, and increased mitotic activity.
There was a prominent granulomatous reaction, comprising epithelioid histiocytes and fibroblasts surrounding Burkitt lymphoma cells.
Well differentiated adenocarcinoma centered by the common bile duct with very discrete infiltration of the surrounding pancreatic parenchyma.  At the upper left of the image, morphology of the tumor.

Sheet-like growth pattern, high-grade cytological atypia, and numerous mitotic figures are depicted in this radiation-associated angiosarcoma of the oral cavity. 7/9 cases (77.8%) of radiation-associated tumors in this study were high grade.
A cross section of an arteriole is shown with the lumen, the tunica media containing smooth muscle, the tunica adventitia containing stroma, and surrounded by a thin layer of glioblastoma cells.
A histopathological exam confirms papillary renal cell carcinoma.

Histopathological examination reveals mature lobulated sebaceous glands that overlie the esophageal squamous epithelium without hair follicles or malignancy. Inflammatory infiltration is present around the sebaceous glands located in the deep portion of lamina propria (H&E, ×40).
Pathology of the resected soft tissue of the neck showing the presence of papillary thyroid carcinoma in the background of necrotic tissue.
Histopathology of the breast carcinoma and lymph nodes. Invasive ductal carcinoma of the left breast infiltrating surrounding fat and stroma.
Histology (H&E staining) of tissues fixed either in GAF or in PBF. A colorectal adenocarcinoma fixed in PBF, where the similarity in preservation of structural and cell components can be appreciated.
A representative routine H&E section showing spindled and undifferentiated histomorphology classically seen in carcinosarcoma.
Low power view of the coexisting Kaposi sarcoma and Molluscum contagiosum.
Detection of FcaGHV1 by in situ hybridization in an intestinal large, granular lymphocyte lymphoma.
Ocular-adnexal MALT lymphoma with uniform and similar lymphoma cells to those in SLL.
A photomicrograph of the tumor shows small proliferating spindle cells and lipoblasts in the myxoid stroma, findings consistent with myxoid liposarcoma. Hematoxylin and eosin stain.
Nodular melanoma with nodular growth and a prominent vertical component to the invasion of the tumor.
Gastric adenocarcinoma–GC.
GFAP staining of glioblastoma tumor cells.
Adenocarcinoma of the lung with prevalent lepidic growth and invasive features focally present in the neoplasia.
Shave biopsy of mid-back shows usual features of hyperkeratotic seborrheic keratosis with co-existing melanoma in-situ.
Histological features of angiosarcoma of the bladder: Morphological features including spindle and epithelioid pleomorphic cells.
In some areas, mucinous changes were prominent, which could be mistaken for myxoma or myxoid liposarcoma.
Hematoxylin-eosin staining showed that epithelioid angiosarcoma had abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm and vesicular nuclei, with prominent nucleoli.

Microscopic view of the specimen shows sarcomatous MNCs that are less atypical, with many bland, ovoid-shaped, benign-looking OGCs having normochromatic nuclei. Some OGCs have hyperchromatic, mildly pleomorphic nuclei. A pleomorphic giant cell with pleomorphic and hyperchromatic nuclei and prominent nucleoli is observed.

Left hemicolectomy of the sigmoid colon mass demonstrated moderately differentiated infiltrating neoplastic glands within ulcerated colonic mucosa consistent with primary colonic adenocarcinoma with associated calcifications.
Histology of a high grade adrenocortical carcinoma showing confluent areas of necrosis.
Mixed cellularity Hodgkin lymphoma with positive LMP1 expression noted in Reed–Sternberg cells.
Uterine cervix biopsy showing a biphasic malignant neoplasm consistent with a homologous MMMTU. Haematoxylin & eosin stain of an undifferentiated malignant uterine neoplasm.
GalNAc-T14 expression in different breast cancer type. Invasive lobular carcinoma.
Typical histology of pancreatic ITPN with an associated invasive adenocarcinoma.

Clear cell sarcoma tissue section: compact nests and fascicles with large rounded and spindle-shaped cells separated by connective tissue septa. Mitoses are numerous. The cells had large amounts of clear cytoplasm.
Histopathological findings of needle biopsy specimen of the prostate show adenocarcinoma of the prostate, Gleason grade 3+4 = score of 7.
Histopathological lesions in spleen with activation of melanomacrophages and lymphocytic depletion.
Histopathological image of the right-sided cystic parathyroid carcinoma showing cyst formation.
A possible transition zone between osteogenic sarcoma and cemento-osseous dysplasia.

Histopathologic stud with microphotograph (2×) of excised angiosarcoma showing numerous anaestomotic vascular spaces and foci of malignant cells at the periphery of the tumor and hematoma at the center correlated the MRI features. MRI = magnetic resonance imaging.
Intraosseous rhabdomyosarcoma with an epithelioid atypical neoplastic cell population predominating.
The subsequent cervical lymph node biopsy shows large Reed–Sternberg cells and variants in a background of mixed inflammation, diagnostic of classical Hodgkin lymphoma.
Perineural invasion from high-grade pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma with desmoplastic and lymphocytic reaction into the surrounding stromal tissue.
H&E section showing infiltrates of adenocarcinoma of the prostate.
Histological patterns of splenic marginal zone lymphoma (SMZL). Monophasic pattern: cases lack a central core of smaller lymphocytes and have a monophasic pattern.
Histology of a lipoma-like well-differentiated liposarcoma.

Melanoma in situ: Tumoral cells with clear/pale eosinophilic cytoplasm; the nuclei present hyperchromasia and enlargement; some of the cells show prominent nucleoli; Tumoral cells reaching the upper side of the squamous layer of the epidermis; inflammatory cells are observed in the papillary dermis.
H&E stain of the patient’s left testicular tumor shows a mixed germ cell tumor composed of post pubertal teratoma, embryonal carcinoma, and yolk sac tumor.
Malignant melanoma. Necrotic melanocytic nests in the reticular dermis (HE, 100x)
Microscopic findings of the mixed adenocarcinoma-NET of the stomach. The adenocarcinoma was located in the superficial part of the mucosa, while the NET was in the basal part.
Adrenocortical carcinoma with pleomorphic tumor cells and prominent nucleoli.
Adrenocortical carcinoma: Sheet of pleomorphic tumor cells showing necrosis.

Microscopic findings of the precursor T-cell lymphoblastic lymphoma from the axillary lymph node show most tumor cells with immature nuclei, fine chromatin, convoluted nuclear contours, and frequent mitotic figures.
Capsulated follicular neoplasm with areas of questionable nuclear changes of papillary thyroid carcinoma.
Histological images with malignant cells from the papillary thyroid carcinoma. Histological examination of the thyroid gland (hematoxylin and eosin stain).

Left thigh tumor pathology: They continued with well-differentiated liposarcoma cells, with desmoplastic stroma, abundant lipoblastic cells, and hyperchromatic and pleomorphic nuclei and presence of numerous mitoses.
Typical cytological features of well-differentiated papillary thyroid carcinoma are visible: nuclear pseudoinclusions, grooving, and clearing are present.
Hematoxylin and eosin-stained section demonstrating lentigo maligna melanoma.
Infiltration of the right nasal cavity wall with a melanoma arriving in depth to the cartilage without invading it. Abbreviation:  hematoxylin-eosin-saffron.
Histopathologic section of caudate nucleus mass: Sheets of packed, pleomorphic large cells with high nucleus to cytoplasm ratio, consistent with a diffuse large cell lymphoma.

A microscopic image of repeated prostatic needle biopsy (hematoxylin and eosin stain), showing adenocarcinoma components after treatment with ADT (therapeutic effect was judged to be Grade 1), together with squamous carcinoma components.  Abbreviation: ADT, androgen deprivation therapy.
Abdominal computed tomography of the liver and pathologic findings from the primary tumor. Abdominal computed tomography demonstrated papillary renal cell carcinoma, G2, INF-α, T2a, N0, M0, v (-)
Histological section showing fusiform sarcomatous cells.

Polypoid nodule invading the perimuscular connective tissue of the pancreas with acinar structure of the pancreas beneath the nodule. Moderately to poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma surrounded by desmoplastic reaction.

Bone marrow aspirate smear shows melanoma cells with nuclear pleomorphism and intracytoplasmic pigment.
Case 3 showing pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma involving the bile duct.
Section of the rectal specimen showing metastatic gastric adenocarcinoma.

Histological features of pancreatic adenocarcinoma and pancreatic intraepithelial neoplasias (PanINs). PanIN 1.
Synovial sarcoma with round to spindle nuclei and a hemorrhagic background.
Histological morphology of colorectal cancer subtypes showing serrated adenocarcinoma (SAC) with serrated glands, large, rounded nuclei, prominent nucleoli, and ample eosinophilic cytoplasm.
Histology showing appearance of sarcoma: tumour cells arranged in characteristic storiform, interlacing fascicular and diffuse patterns.
Paired cytological sample and surgical sample of pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma (PDAC) showing PDAC cells with Papanicolaou stain in cytological sample.
Proximal-type epithelioid sarcoma of perineum with a 'pseudoangiosarcomatous' pattern and tumor cells arranged in a disintegrating perivascular pattern.

Histopathology picture showing grade 1 chondrosarcoma with lobules of cartilage separated by fibrous tissue.
Malignant Melanoma Showing Positive SCF Expression in Malignant Tumor Cells (X400).
Representative histopathological images of low-grade myxofibrosarcoma showing myxoid stroma, pleomorphic cells, and curvilinear vessels.

Clear cell carcinoma versus serous carcinoma. High-grade endometrial carcinoma displaying morphologic features overlapping those of clear cell carcinoma and serous carcinoma. The high mitotic index and nuclear pleomorphism are most characteristic of serous carcinoma.

Histopathological examination revealing the mass to be myxoid pleomorphic liposarcoma with lymphangioma-like myxoid pools within the tumor.
Intense reactivity with 14F7 Mab was observed in glioblastoma cells. The staining was located on both cell membrane and cytoplasm of malignant cells.
Choroidal melanoma with ciliary body infiltration.

Classic papillary thyroid carcinomas with tall cell features contain 10% to 50% of cells with tall cell characteristics. Dotted lines show the area containing tall cells. Myxoinflammatory fibroblastic sarcoma with a myxoid background containing spindle-shaped and epithelioid cells, inflammatory cells, and pseudolipoblasts.
Microphotograph showing papillary thyroid carcinoma.
Expression of P16(INK4A) in classical Hodgkin lymphoma. P16(INK4A) expression in HRS cells.

The diagnosis of leiomyosarcoma was originally considered in this leiomyoma. However, the tumor was reclassified as STUMP upon review. It is hypercellular and shows nuclear atypia but lacks significant mitotic activity or coagulative necrosis.
Pheochromocytoma arising from the medulla in relation to the surrounding cortex.
Endometrial carcinoma with T2 signal isointense to myometrium. On the post-contrast T1W imaging, there is better tumour to myometrium contrast.
Malignant melanoma. Pleomorphic melanocytes arranged in confluent nests. Mitotic figures are present (HE, 400x)

Microscopic slides of sections of the lungs showing intravascular collections of fibrin and markedly anaplastic tumour cells consistent with poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma. A slide showing recanalization of a thrombosed pulmonary blood vessel. Note the individual tumour cells. Haematoxylin and eosin stain.

histology revealed bone with a fibrocartilaginous cap in continuity with trabecular bone and bone marrow that is replaced by fat. Microscopic appearance of parathyroid carcinoma.
Glioblastoma with typical pseudopalisading necrosis.
A case of pulmonary adenocarcinoma showing mainly solid pattern with few acinar pattern.

Microscopic slides of sections of the lungs showing intravascular collections of fibrin and markedly anaplastic tumour cells consistent with poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma. A slide showing tumour cells with associated thrombus in the pulmonary vessels. Haematoxylin and eosin stain.

H&E staining of lung adenocarcinoma showing variation in nucleus size and shape, deep staining, and increased nucleoplasm index.

Gastric ulcer biopsy: Section shows fragments of gastric mucosa. The lamina propria shows moderate increase in the inflammatory cell content composed of lymphocytes and plasma cells. One of the fragments shows sheets and clusters of neoplastic cells with high N:C, peripherally pushed pleomorphic and hyperchromatic nucleus with abundant eosinophilic granular cytoplasm. These cells are infiltrating the muscularis mucosa. Stomach biopsy consistent with moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma with signet ring cells.
Histopathologic features of the histiocytic sarcoma show a diffuse, noncohesive growth pattern and various admixed inflammatory components using hematoxylin-eosin stain.
Osteosarcoma – Smear shows an osteoid matrix with few tumor cells.

A photomicrograph showing irregular woven bone with osteoblastic rimming. Specific histomorphological patterns of diffuse invasion, so-called “secondary structures of Scherer” in glioblastoma. As a rule, glioma cells migrate along existing brain structures such as brain parenchyma, blood vessels, white matter tracts, and subpial spaces. The secondary structures of Scherer are referred to four criteria as subpial spread.
Rhabdomyosarcoma arising in a giant congenital naevus. This view shows the naevus and its abrupt transition to a more cellular neoplasm, which infiltrates the subcutis.

Hematoxylin and eosin stain shows pathological findings.  Purple  (cartilage) and  pink  (bone)  components, plus partially gray areas outside the  pink areas, are typical for a cartilaginous cap. The chondrocyte component is enriched with cellular components but lacks nuclear atypicality, which points to osteochondroma and away from chondrosarcoma.  Bar = 100 μm.
Histological features of pancreatic adenocarcinoma and pancreatic intraepithelial neoplasias (PanINs). PanIN 3.
Microscopic examination demonstrating glioblastoma with neovascularization and a classic pseudopalisading pattern of necrosis characteristic of glioblastoma.
Pathological diagnosis of tissue from right proximal femur: metastatic pleomorphic liposarcoma, with the presence of vascular invasion. 60x magnification.

Anterior gingival biopsy of an ovoid nodule lined on the surface by squamous epithelium. A Kaposi's sarcoma tumor takes up the rest of the tissue. The tumor consists of spindled cells forming slit-like spaces. There are numerous extravasated red blood cells. The individual cells show mitotic activity, have poor defined cell borders, and ovoid, small to medium-sized nuclei with occasional pinpoint nuclei.
Cytological picture of a high-grade spindle cell sarcoma.
Photomicrograph of the esophagus showing neovascularization, reactive stromal and endothelial cells with enlarged nuclei in the ulcer bed.

Chondrosarcoma: Paraffin-embedded section displaying a tumor arranged in short fascicles with anaplastic spindle shaped cells. Right lower corner shows malignant chondroid differentiation (H&E, ×100).

Clear cell papillary renal cell carcinoma in native kidneys of a renal transplant recipient. Single layers of clear cells with moderate amount of clear cytoplasm and pyknotic nuclei oriented toward the apical surfaces.

NK/T-cell lymphoma with angiocentric infiltrate of small lymphocytes and atypical cells.
CT diagnosis and biopsy of cholangiocarcinoma and hepatocellular carcinoma. Liver biopsy of hepatocellular carcinoma (magnification ×400).

Histopathological examination of nodule of resected thyroid reveals a capsulated nodule formed of microfollicles lined by follicular epithelial cells, which had enlarged pale crowded nuclei together with nuclear grooves and inclusions, indicative of papillary thyroid carcinoma.
Esophageal biopsy showing focal ulceration and patchy acute and chronic esophagitis suggestive of Crohn's disease.
Hematoxylin and eosin staining of mesothelioma.
Primary mediastinal B cell lymphoma.
A representative case of diffuse large B-cell lymphoma (DLBCL) morphology.
Photomicrograph showing invasive carcinoma of the breast.
Metastatic endometrial carcinoma.
Histologic features of small biopsy samples of mesothelioma. The presence of necrosis favors the diagnosis of malignant mesothelioma.
Histological appearance of Grade III follicular lymphoma with more than 15 centroblasts per high power field.

Histologic features of a millimetric MFT focus close to the outer surface of the thyroid gland mimicking at low magnification so-called occult sclerosing papillary thyroid carcinoma. MFT was an incidental diagnosis in a thyroid gland removed for other thyroid pathology.
Histological picture of the histiocytic sarcoma showing large atypical cells with large atypical nuclei and phagocytosis of a neutrophilic granulocyte.
Histology of small cell carcinoma element of the esophageal carcinoma. The tumor cells show characteristic morphologies of small cell carcinoma.
Papillary thyroid carcinoma (PTC) shows desmoplastic tumor stroma mainly composed of caner-associated fibroblasts (CAF).
Slide showing pancreatic adenocarcinoma, malignant cells with high nucleus to cytoplasm ratio (red arrow).
Rectal mass showing submucosa and deep mucosa with metastatic adenocarcinoma.
KAI1 in uveal melanoma. Strong and diffuse cytoplasmic positivity in mixed (spindle-epithelioid) malignant melanoma.
Histology of the rejected tumor with HE stain, showing moderately differentiated gastric adenocarcinoma, with complete pathological rejection (R0, T1a(M), UL (-), v(-), Ly (-), pHM0, PVM0).

Representative images of hematoxylin and eosin staining for classic and isolated forms of intraductal carcinoma of the prostate (IDC-P) from the cases of the authors′ institution. Cribriform tumor spreads into a non-neoplastic gland lined by a layer of basal cells in a 50 year old patient with pT3b prostate cancer. Intraductal proliferation shows epithelial atypia surpassing that of high-grade prostatic intraepithelial neoplasia (HGPIN) not accompanied by invasive adenocarcinoma elsewhere in an 80 year old patient.
Histopathology in a patient with pancreatic tumor shows glandular adenocarcinoma foci and nests of squamous cell carcinoma, consistent with adenosquamous carcinoma.
1.2 cm focus of papillary thyroid carcinoma.
Ductal adenocarcinoma of the prostate.
Details from a case of locally advanced thyroid carcinoma with tall cell variant of PTC component.

In the superficial esophagus biopsy fragments obtained in the upper digestive tract endoscopy, there was a light inflammatory infiltrate composed mainly by eosinophils, recognizable by their cytoplasmic granules that appear brick-red after eosin staining. A maximum of five eosinophils per high-power field was observed.
Areas of well-differentiated liposarcoma.
Histopathological features of both the glial and the mesenchymal components of gliosarcoma. H&E stain of the glial compartment of a gliosarcoma with prominent vessels.
Prostate adenocarcinoma from biopsy.
Histopathological findings of the esophageal mass revealed large polygonal cells with an intermediate amount of pale oncophilic cytoplasm and extensive nuclear crushing artifact.
Hematoxylin and eosin staining of primary gliosarcoma lesions.
Primary cardiac extraskeletal osteosarcoma with neoplastic osteoid matrix.  H&E staining.
Well-differentiated liposarcoma. Adipocytes show variation in size and shape. Enlarged bizarre hyperchromatic stromal cells are present.

Area adjacent to the dysplastic nevus with melanoma in situ. An irregular lentiginous and nested melanocytic proliferation with scattered lymphocytes and melanophages with papillary dermal fibrosis is observed extending to the peripheral margin.
High-grade conventional osteosarcoma is observed.

The green arrow shows nodules composed of sheets, pseudoacinar structures, and cords of cells with abundant cytoplasm and vesicular nuclei and prominent nucleoli suggestive of well-differentiated hepatocellular carcinoma. The background liver shows features of giant cell hepatitis with cholestasis in keeping with progressive familial intrahepatic cholestasis (PFIC) type 2.
Closer view of the traditional serrated adenoma (TSA) of Barrett’s esophagus showing unlocked serrated configurations with low-grade dysplasia.
A section of a glioblastoma multiforme tumor indicates a rich spatial composition in terms of nuclear size, cellularity, and presence of lymphocytes.
Foci of well-differentiated prostatic acinar adenocarcinoma with a single layer of neoplastic cells arranged into separate glands of variable size and shape, with one focus of perineural invasion.
Histopathological analysis by hematoxylin and eosin (H&E) staining shows squamous cell carcinoma of the lung with a high mixed density of tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes (TILs).
Histological findings of cervical lymph nodes show lymph nodes almost replaced by angiosarcoma, forming an anastomosing network of sinusoids lined by hyperchromatic, nucleated endothelial cells.
Leiomyosarcomatous and liposarcomatous components in the spinal metastasis.
Representative hematoxylin-eosin stainings of the pheochromocytoma.

Tubular adenocarcinoma from the stomach with poorly-cohesive lesions containing signet-ring cells. Discohesive and highly atypical tumor cells with signet-ring cells of intracytoplasmic mucin or eosinophilic cytoplasm can be observed.
Plasmablastic lymphoma: cells with a plasmacytoid appearance and a clock-face condensation of the chromatin.
Sclerosing variant of well-differentiated liposarcoma/atypical lipomatous tumor, highlighting the scattered lipoblasts in a sclerotic background.
Histological findings of epithelioid angiosarcoma.

Detail of Figure 4  for the appearance of pleomorphic sarcoma: the tumor component has large tachychromatic nuclei, monstrous or with atypical mitoses in the atmosphere of lipoblasts; the vessels are newly-formed with prominent cores. HE staining.
Fibrosarcoma of corpus cavernosum.
Histological images of sarcoma using hematoxylin and eosin stain show a chondrosarcomatous area.
Microscopic findings in low grade chondrosarcoma show hypocellular chondroid lobules.
Representative metastases in cirrhotic livers. Metastatic colorectal adenocarcinoma.
Urethral tumor showed moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma consistent with sigmoid colon cancer.

Histologic section of prostate core needle rebiopsy showing moderately differentiated squamous cell carcinoma characterized by presence of keratinization and abundant eosinophilic glassy cytoplasm. There was no evidence of adenocarcinoma component in the prostate specimen.
Histopathology image in a proven case of diffuse large B-cell lymphoma of the duodenum demonstrating cells with vesicular chromatin, prominent nucleoli, and moderate-to-abundant amount of cytoplasm.

Histological examination of the mandible tissue by hematoxylin and eosin staining shows atypical squamous cells and cancer pearls in the alveolar bone of the mandible, with intercellular bridges, which are characteristic of well-differentiated squamous cell carcinoma.
The diagnosis of squamous cell carcinoma of the lung was pathologically verified.
Undifferentiated sarcomatoid cells.
Fine needle biopsy specimen obtained from a pancreatic body mass. The final diagnosis was pancreatic adenocarcinoma.
Cervical lymph node showing lymphomatous infiltrate and necrotizing granulomatous inflammation comprised of epithelial cells, giant cells, and necrosis.
Histopathology of Sarcoma 180 tumor cells shows the presence of mitosis.
Histology of prostate adenocarcinoma showing an abnormal gland with an irregular, thick wall, made up of cells with abnormally large nuclei.

Pathological examination revealing the mass to be a well-differentiated liposarcoma (lipoma-like subtype), characterized by fat cells with different sizes, univacuolated (signet-ring cells) and multivacuolated (lipoblast) lipoblasts.
Endometrial carcinoma in cell block preparation.
The sarcomatous component was composed of spindle cell proliferation.
Well-differentiated component of the liposarcoma, showing atypical cells with nucleomegaly and hyperchromasia scattered within mature adipocytes and intervening fibrous septae.
Histological biopsy of a pulmonary adenocarcinoma with metastasis from gastrointestinal neoplasm. Tumor cells are grouped in clusters.  Metastasis from gastrointestinal neoplasm.

Esophageal biopsies showing eosinophilic infiltration of squamous mucosa and intestinal metaplasia within glandular mucosa, with intestinal metaplasia confirmed by presence of goblet cells in biopsy taken from abnormal colored mucosa.
Images of haematoxylin and eosin (H&E) stained sarcomatoid mesothelioma subtypes, indicating the presence of spindle cells and abundant stroma.
Pathology showed a well-moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma with invasion through the muscularis propria into pericolorectal tissues.
Prostate adenocarcinoma from biopsy.
Representative microphotographs showing an ectopic papillary thyroid carcinoma.
H&E histological slide of the patient's papillary renal cell carcinoma, Fuhrman grade III, showing characteristic papillary architecture and non neoplastic renal parenchyma on the left.
Representative histology of papillary thyroid carcinoma (PTC) subtypes. Tumor cells showed distinct nuclear features, such as grooves and ground-glass appearance.
Microscopic findings of the lung nodule biopsy show that the majority of the specimen is involved by squamous cell carcinoma.
Basal aspect of the traditional serrated adenoma (TSA) of Barrett’s esophagus with high-grade dysplasia.

Both the testicular tumor and inguinal lymph node presented with irregular cobblestone proliferations of germ cell-like atypical cells with clear nucleoli and no vascular proliferation. Spermatic cord stump was negative, showing that this tumor was a classical seminoma.
Regressed Kaposi sarcoma lesion showing a perivascular infiltrate comprised mainly of plasma cells.
Photomicrograph showing poorly differentiated squamous cell carcinoma of the lung.
This recurrent Ewing sarcoma displays epithelioid features, such as increased eosinophilic cytoplasm and cohesive nests.

Large lymphoma cells in the pericardial effusion. Lymphoma cells vary in size, from 5 to 15 times that of normal erythrocytes. Nuclei are pleomorphic, with some coarse nuclear chromatins and distinct nucleoli. Cytoplasm is faint blue to basophilic with frequent vacuoles.
Clear cell carcinoma of the left kidney.  HE staining.  Image in the centre 0.5× and on the lower-right corner 40× magnification.
Invasive ductal carcinoma of the breast showing invasive tumor cells with high nuclear grade.
Clear cell sarcoma of soft tissue: uniform clear cells in fascicles.
Histological features of carcinosarcoma in the enterectomy specimen, with tumor implant in the mesenteric adipose tissue.

Representative histology of papillary thyroid carcinoma (PTC) subtypes. Poorly differentiated PTC with poorly differentiated components, including solid and insular proliferations. The solid and insular components comprised about 20% of the tumor.
Monophasic poorly differentiated synovial sarcoma.
Section showing respiratory epithelium lined tissue with subepithelium infiltrated by an adenocarcinoma arranged in tubulo-acinar and micropapillary pattern.
Large lymphoma cells in the biopsied right supraclavicular lymph node with large, atypical cells having some retracted pale cytoplasm scattered among the inflammatory cells.
Representative pathology slides from the primary excision of the exophytic clitoral mass demonstrating melanoma.
Rectal adenocarcinoma showing extensive tumor necrosis.
Histopathological findings. Hematoxylin and eosin staining showing that lung adenocarcinoma has a papillary‐predominant pattern.
Papillary thyroid carcinoma (PTC).

The cholangiocarcinoma-like tumour is located adjacent to the metastatic lesion. The positional relationship between the neuroendocrine tumour (NET) and microscopic cholangiocarcinoma-like tumour is shown.
Microscopic evaluation of the tumor showing sheets of cells with hypersarcomatic nuclei and moderate cytoplasm. Intervening blood vessels were seen. Frequent mitosis is seen.
Representative case of plasmablastic lymphoma. Neoplastic cells have plasmablastic morphology, with a prominent nucleolus and moderate amount of cytoplasm.
Glandular arrangement of tumor cells with surrounding desmoplastic reaction in bone marrow biopsy in case with metastasis from gastric adenocarcinoma.  )
DAM showing unusual vascular features: capillary-like microvascular proliferation, as seen in glioblastoma.
Lung adenocarcinoma metastasis.  Hematoxylin and eosin.
Prostatic ductal adenocarcinoma tumor cells showing a papillary histological pattern.
Histopathology of the excised melanoma of left sole.
Fine needle aspiration biopsy shows papillary thyroid carcinoma.
H&E staining of the synovial sarcoma shows numerous small round cells with a high nucleocytoplasmic ratio.
Pathology of tumour specimen shows intermediate size homogenous basophilic cells with hyperchromatic nuclei containing nucleoli: Burkitt's lymphoma.
Normal-appearing bone with sarcomatous transformation.

35-year-old man with cardiac angiosarcoma. Photomicrograph of histologic specimen shows markedly infiltrative tumour extensively permeating cardiac tissue, with dissection of the cardiac myocytes. The minimally atypical spindle and ovoid malignant endothelial cells are seen to line ill-defined, angulated vascular channels insinuating between individual cardiac muscle cells (H and E, × 400).
Chest computed tomography and histopathological findings of the primary lung tumor. Note: a diagnosis of pathological lung adenocarcinoma was considered using H&E stain.
Right axillary node biopsy demonstrating diffuse large B-cell lymphoma.
Histopathology of mesenchymal chondrosarcoma showing cells with high NC ratio and scanty cytoplasm admixed with lobules of hyaline cartilage showing increased cellularity and mitotic figures.
Fine needle aspiration of the renal tumor revealed a tubulo-papillary architecture with prominent nucleoli.

Histological features of mucinous colon adenocarcinoma and gastric carcinoma – intestinal type. Strips of atypical tumor cells and part of abortive glands floating in large extracellular mucin lakes comprising at least 50% of tumor area.

Histological features of germ-cell tumor (seminoma) with somatic malignant transformation. In situ germ cell neoplasia (upper right corner) admixed with somatic spindle cell sarcoma (lower left corner), (H&E 200x).
Papillary thyroid carcinoma with intranuclear cytoplasmic pseudoinclusions and nuclear grooves. The remaining nuclei show variation in size and shape.
Histological images with malignant cells from the papillary thyroid carcinoma. Biopsy of the pericardium (hematoxylin and eosin stain).
Microscopic appearance of lymphoma infiltrate in the heart shows lymphoid cells infiltrating the myocardium.

Invasive colorectal adenocarcinoma demonstrating a micropapillary growth pattern. A micropapillary pattern is characterized by small and tight clusters of tumor cells with surrounding cleft-like spaces. This histologic feature is associated with lymphovascular invasion and nodal metastasis.

Haematoxylin and eosin stained sections showing adenocarcinoma. (a) Intestinal type gastric adenocarcinoma showing invasion of the muscularis propria by moderately differentiated malignant glands. (b) Diffuse type gastric adenocarcinoma showing monomorphic tumour cells with an Indian-file pattern of infiltration (magnification ×200).
Histopathological features of myoinvasive primary endometrial carcinoma showing glandular and cribriform patterns with moderate nuclear atypia using Hematoxylin and eosin staining.

Histopathology of the Endoscopic Colonic Biopsy Hematoxylin and eosin stained, medium power, magnification ×250. Metastatic colonic adenocarcinoma in the lesser curvature of the stomach as seen by * – malignant epithelium recapitulating colonic glands associated with ↑ – benign gastric glands.
A metastasis from the papillary thyroid carcinoma is present in this lymph node.

Photomicrograph showing cytomorphological findings of endoscopic ultrasound guided fine needle aspirate of pancreatic adenocarcinoma. The cells are markedly pleomorphic with enlarged irregular nuclei, macronucleoli, and moderate lacy cytoplasm.
Histopathological examination of the biopsy specimen showing melanoma cells containing melanin granules.

Nodular sclerosis Hodgkin's lymphoma: Reed Sternberg cells with a pale abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm. The nuclei are bilobed with owl‐eye inclusion‐like nucleoli. These cells are present in a rich inflammatory reactive background.
Histopathological appearance of undifferentiated pleomorphic sarcoma showing tumor cells with marked nuclear pleomorphism and mitotic forms.
Cellular variant of myxoid liposarcoma.

Specific histomorphological patterns of diffuse invasion, so-called “secondary structures of Scherer” in glioblastoma. As a rule, glioma cells migrate along existing brain structures such as brain parenchyma, blood vessels, white matter tracts, and subpial spaces. The secondary structures of Scherer are referred to four criteria as perineuronal satellitosis.
Photomicrograph showing carcinomatous and sarcomatous elements infiltrating the myometrium indicating a carcinosarcoma.
Histopathological examination of the rectal tumor showing moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma.
Detail of Figure 3  for the appearance of pleomorphic sarcoma: sarcomatous tumor component in the atmosphere of lipoblasts has large tachychromatic nuclei, with atypical mitoses. HE staining.
Invasive ductal carcinoma of the breast reveals irregular infiltrative nests of tumor cells using H&E staining.
The lesion shows monomorphic and dense proliferation of atypical large lymphoid cells resembling diffuse large B-cell lymphoma (DLBCL).
Hematoxylin- and eosin-stained section of tissue from the initial surgical excision shows a high-grade spindle-cell sarcoma with nuclear pleomorphism.
Paucicellular myxoid liposarcoma with obvious lipoblastic differentiation.

Pathology: Skull metastases. Skull mets: H&E stained image displays numerous atypical spindle and
epithelioid cells with mitosis and malignant osteoid, invading the bone.

Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma in the cervical lymph node reveals diffuse infiltration of the medium and large lymphocytes.
Examples of malignant pleural mesothelioma (MPM): sarcomatoid MPM.
Biopsy taken from the mid esophagus showing no pathological findings.
Immature cells in CSF from patients with lymphoma.
Photomicrographs of non-metastatic pheochromocytoma cases with elevated PASS scores showing large and irregular nests in a pheochromocytoma with a PASS score of 7.
Microphotographs showing the appearance of anaplastic large cell lymphoma in the capsule surrounding an implant. Most cases are of a B-cell phenotype.
Macroscopic and histologic findings of lung adenocarcinoma. Right lungs showing multiple solid nodules (arrowheads).
Gliosarcoma spindle cells in short fascicles with fibrillar background.
Histopathology image of the excised parotid gland carcinosarcoma.
Gastric adenocarcinoma (Hematoxylin-eosin staining). Abbreviations: HE, Hematoxylin-eosin; GC, Gastric cancer.
The extent of heat denaturation was determined in the excised porcine esophagus stained with hematoxylin and eosin.
Hematoxylin-eosin staining of lung adenocarcinoma sample.
Pancreatic adenocarcinoma at the pancreatic body. Hematoxylin–eosin (H&E) staining of biopsy samples.
Hematoxylin and eosin-stained slide of cryobiopsy of lung showing adenocarcinoma.
Tumor spread through air spaces (STAS) in lung adenocarcinoma (ADC) shown with H&E staining.
Colon adenocarcinoma.
Intraluminal tumor growth of a Leiomyosarcoma originating from the subclavian vein.
Histopathological evaluation of esophageal mucosal biopsies: (a) benign squamous esophageal mucosa with profuse inflammatory cells; (b) extensive necrotic slough.
Histopathological findings of the thyroid carcinoma show tumor cells arranged in microcysts of varying sizes, with a metastatic lesion in the lymph node.
Hematoxylin and eosin staining shows the hypercontraction of sarcomeres with contraction band necrosis and lymphocytic infiltration due to catecholamine overproduction from pheochromocytoma.
Acinar adenocarcinoma of the prostate.
Centrally located angiosarcoma high grade with fusiform tumor component.
Histopathological findings of lung adenocarcinoma show papillary structures and alveolar epithelial replacement growths.

The tumor shows minimal typical ductal features of phyllodes tumor (see photomicrograph, top panel), a minority of the remainder low-grade malignant (see other photomicrograph, left half) and majority high-grade malignant ‘overgrown stroma’. Mature squamous ‘pearls’ (see photomicrograph, lower panel) and chondroid areas (see photomicrograph, middle panel) are obvious divergent differentiation. Foci of geographic necrosis, and broad zones of undifferentiated sarcoma with marked atypia (see other photomicrograph, right half), tumor giant cells, and numerous mitoses and karyorrhectic cells, constitute the most malignant-appearing areas.
Typical histological findings of dermatofibrosarcoma protuberans show fibroblastic neoplasm with uniform appearance of storiform pattern, minimal cellular pleomorphism, and low mitotic activity.
The esophageal epithelium exhibits fewer cells and recovered stratification, with basal cells occupying not more than 15% of esophageal thickness, and no eosinophilic infiltration.
EBV-positive DLBCL, NOS composed of sheets of large-sized cells admixed with necrotic foci.
H&E stained breast histopathological microscopy image of invasive carcinoma grade 2.
Surgical biopsy of the lymph node confirmed anaplastic large cell lymphoma.
Postoperative pathology of material from the endometrium shows a high-grade endometrial carcinoma invading into less than half of the myometrium.
Papillary thyroid carcinoma with optically clear nuclei and visible nucleoli.  Identified using hematoxylin and eosin.
Mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue (MALT) lymphoma. The lymphoma cells show a strong and uniform expression of CD20.
The pathological diagnosis of the resected specimens was lung adenocarcinoma.
Metastatic nodal infiltration by a colon adenocarcinoma.
The splenic tissue has a relatively normal structure with increased melanomacrophages.
The histopathological figure of RCC with sarcomatoid differentiation, showing clear cell carcinoma together with leiomyosarcoma-like cells using H&E stain.
Bone marrow biopsy histopathology revealed diffuse involvement with small lymphocytic lymphoma.

a. Stain of prostatic ductal adenocarcinoma; In the microscopic examination of the prostatectomy material, among the areas of classical prostatic acinar adenocarcinoma, there were adenocarcinoma cells composed of malignant neoplastic proliferation with papillary and cribriform architecture. Numerous lymphoma cells with irregular nuclear contours and large nucleoli clustered are seen in small vessel lumens.
Sigmoid colon biopsy demonstrating features of ovarian-type adenocarcinoma.
Malignant epithelial (carcinoma) and stromal (sarcoma) components of MC observed using H&E staining at 200x magnification.
Examples of pathological tissue sections of head and neck squamous cell carcinomas stained with hematoxylin and eosin. Sample shows strong staining involving >70% of the tumor cells.
Primary lung squamous cell carcinoma. Tumor cells demonstrate pleomorphic nuclei with few dyskeratotic cells.

Photomicrograph of the thoracoscopic pleural biopsy specimen taken from a patient with extraskeletal myxoid chondrosarcoma. Nests of polygonal tumor cells with abundant myxoid stroma and small vessels.
Images of haematoxylin and eosin (H&E) stained epithelioid mesothelioma subtypes, indicating the presence of flat, cuboidal cells.
Patient 8 biopsy specimen with non-keratinizing oropharyngeal carcinoma compared with concurrent non-neoplastic mucosa. H&E stained sections of non-keratinizing squamous cell carcinoma.
“Crush”artifacts of esophageal small cell carcinoma (upper right) [hematoxylinand eosin (H and E) stain] .
The tumor shows a bimorphic pattern consisting of low-grade chondrosarcoma and high-grade spindle cell sarcoma using hematoxylin and eosin stain.

Pathologic findings of lymph node metastasis in papillary thyroid carcinoma. Metastatic tumor foci with intact lymph node capsule. Metastatic tumor foci extend to the surrounding perinodal fat tissue beyond the fibrous capsule of the lymph node.

The submucosa of the esophagus contains mitotically active spindle cells and pleomorphic spindle cells with eosinophilic cytoplasm and focal areas containing eosinophilic stromal hyaline-like material, likely osteoid.
Histological findings showing a cellular area revealing bland spindle cells, resembling Kaposi sarcoma.
Photomicrograph of H&E stained primary nodular melanoma at low magnification showing nests of atypical melanocyte proliferationsmalignant melanoma tumor cells.
Section of esophagus showing hyperkeratosis and candida organism.

Histopathologic examination of the esophageal mucosa biopsy shows fragments of ulcer slough and granulation tissue, with few cells exhibiting cytopathic changes suggestive of herpetic viral etiology, including multinucleation, chromatin margination, and vague nuclear inclusions. Histological examination shows pathological characteristics of glioblastoma.
Histopathological examination of mixed-type liposarcoma tissue shows a myxoid component.

Dilated lymphatics with multifocal areas resembling early Kaposi's sarcoma.
Papillary thyroid carcinoma showing finger-like projections lined by neoplastic cells.

Round blue cell sarcoma arising in AFH with atypical round to oval cells with vesicular nuclei and brisk mitotic activity. 40x magnification.
Circumscribed neoplastic papilliferous thyroid carcinoma with inflammatory cells, especially lymphocytes (lymphocytic thyroiditis).

Morphologic spectrum of post-transplant plasmablastic lymphomas. Representative hematoxylin and eosin (H&E)-stained sections of post-transplant plasmablastic lymphomas showing a monotonous infiltrate of plasmablasts, with areas of plasmablastic morphology and focal areas of plasmacytic differentiation.
A view of clear cell chondrosarcoma showing large tumour cells, round to oval in shape, abundant clear cytoplasm, and centrally located round nucleus.
Microscopic findings of cholangiocarcinoma. The Ki-67 labeling index is higher in the solid cholangiocarcinoma area than in the VMC and transitional areas.
Histology of the stomach shows a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma in the lesion.

Histopathological imaging of esophageal lesions.

Expression of miR-92a in colorectal adenocarcinoma (CA) and its precancerous lesions, revealed by  in situ  hybridization (magnification, ×200). CA. Numerous cells within the epidermis in a case of in situ melanoma.
Histology at the time of the recurrence. Epithelial Malignant Mesothelioma recurrence in a more acinar pattern (arrow) (HES).
Tumor stroma in thyroid cancer. Fibrous stroma composed of CAF is noted in anaplastic thyroid carcinoma.

Photomicrography of lymph node biopsy showing diffuse solid lymphomatous growth, monomorphic cells with irregularly folded nuclei and granular chromatin, focal angiocentric pattern, and many apoptotic bodies with inconspicuous nucleoli.
Lung biopsy showing adenocarcinoma with a necrotic component and surrounding edema. Bronchopneumonia and emphysema are observed.

Histopathology of fat pad biopsy showing intravascular large B cell lymphoma cells mainly located in the lumina of small vessels.

Characteristic neoplastic invasion of parathyroid carcinoma cells into adjacent vessels and gross invasion of the surrounding thyroid tissue.

Histopathology demonstrating pleomorphic glial cells, nuclear atypia, palisading necrosis, mitoses, and vascular proliferation consistent with a diagnosis of glioblastoma.
Histopathology of the most common malignant renal neoplasms. Papillary type 1.

Chondrosarcoma grade 2.
Photomicrography of the lacrimal sac melanoma showing solid growth of malignant cells characterized by production of melanin pigments, hyperchromic nuclei and prominent nucleoli (H&E, ×400).
Histopathological examination showed that the tumor was composed of a mixture of well-differentiated lipoblast and pleomorphic liposarcoma with both atypical nuclear and multinuclear spindle cells.

Diffuse high grade Burkitt's like lymphoma.
Papillary renal cell carcinoma with micropapillary features with lymphovascular invasion, tumor cells showing eosinophilic cytoplasm with atypical nuclei with prominent nucleoli.

The tumor consisted of monotonous, small atypical astroglial cells. Glomeruloid microvascular proliferation was observed, consistent with the diagnosis of small cell glioblastoma.
Morphological descriptions of Kaposi’s sarcoma and Kaposi’s sarcoma-like cases. Microscopic identification by hematoxylin and eosin staining shows nodular structures.

Bone marrow biopsy showing hypercellular marrow with trilineage hyperplasia, mild eosinophilia, focal mild reticulin fibrosis, mild increase in iron, and positive for a monoclonal B cell population, consistent with splenic marginal zone lymphoma.
Aspiration smear showing a typical dual population of lymphoid cells in a case of intermediate grade non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.
Clear cell sarcoma: Spindled to epithelioid cells with pale eosinophilic cytoplasm and vesicular nuclei with prominent nucleoli.

Melanoma. Occupation of the central area of the epidermis and superior dermis by proliferation of anaplastic melanocytic cells, with irregular distribution of melanin pigment. Melanoma, superficial spreading type, Breslow 0.62 mm and Clark level III.
The esophageal adenoid cystic carcinoma (AdCC) is composed of impacted cells with scant cytoplasm, forming solid and cribriform structures.
Microscopic image of osteogenic sarcoma with area of tumour necrosis.

Histopathology demonstrating pleomorphic glial cells, nuclear atypia, palisading necrosis, mitoses, and vascular proliferation consistent with a diagnosis of glioblastoma.
Lymph node showing follicular lymphoma, grade 3A.

Histopathology slide showing angiomatous meningioma. Histopathology slide showing small round nuclei with chondroid elements, consistent with chondrosarcoma. Histopathology slide showing chondroid elements.

Malignant phyllodes tumor with ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) in surrounding tissue. Hematoxylin and eosin stain of intraocular hemangiosarcoma demonstrating neoplastic spindle cells lining blood-filled vascular channels. Arrows indicate neoplastic cells lining vascular, blood-filled channels.

Histologic features of αβ T-cell lymphoma involving the spinal cord. Monomorphic medium-to-large atypical lymphoid cells diffusely infiltrating the spinal cord parenchyma with occasional perivascular arrangement.
Microscopic findings of the lung nodule biopsy show squamous cell carcinoma with marked cytologic atypia, keratinization, and invasive growth pattern.
H&E staining showing the histopathological appearance of the rectal carcinoma with ossification in the stroma. Serrated adenocarcinoma with ossification in the stroma.
Prostatic adenocarcinoma Gleason grade 3 + 3 observed under 10× objective. Prostatic adenocarcinoma Gleason grade 3 + 3 observed under 40× objective.
Histopathology showing monomorphic epithelioid peritoneal mesothelioma.
Lymphoplasmacytic lymphoma with uniform lymphoma cells and Dutcher bodies.
5B14 mAb reactivity in small round blue cell tumours, including rhabdomyosarcomas, medulloblastomas, and neuroblastomas.
Morphologically, the cells showed strong polymorphism, such as having a spindle shape or polynuclear formation, and proliferated densely; cancer and sarcoma components were mixed.
Microphotograph showing invasive ductal carcinoma with dense intratumoral lymphoplasmacytic infiltrate. Normal breast parenchyma can be seen at the lower right corner of the image.

The pheochromocytoma component of the tumor shows polygonal, oval-shaped, and spindle cells with amphophilic cytoplasm. The nuclei are round to spindle-shaped with inconspicuous nucleoli. A bizarre cell is seen with pseudoinclusion.
Incidental focal acantholytic dyskeratosis associated with prominent solar elastosis. This occurred in association with an excision of a melanoma in situ.
Nodal grey-zone lymphoma showing features of both classical Hodgkin lymphoma and diffuse large B-cell lymphoma.
Microscopic images showing detail of follicular growth areas of a papillary thyroid carcinoma.

Type I/low grade serous ovarian carcinoma characterized by a significantly higher degree of nuclear atypia and higher number of mitosis compared to high grade serous carcinoma. The papillae are less well preserved in high grade compared to low grade serous carcinomas.
Hematoxylin and eosin staining of a glioblastoma multiforme showing palisading cells around the necrotic area.
Histologic features of small biopsy samples of mesothelioma show tumor cells invading the fibrous stroma.
Cartilage ring and mucous glands in the esophageal wall.
Hodgkin's lymphoma showing heterogenous expression of CD20.
The glial tumor shows biphasic tumor tissue with a mesenchymal component and a more obvious glial component, compatible with gliosarcoma, WHO grade IV.
Melanoma in situ with large melanocytes spreading upwards into the epidermis.
Histological findings show adenocarcinoma arising from ectopic pancreatic tissue and ectopic pancreatic tissue.
Biopsies of the esophageal lesions showed nonspecific inflammation with marked neutrophil infiltration.
High power view of extraskeletal Ewing’s sarcoma characterized by small round cell tumor of striking uniformity.
Histological examination of mucosal esophageal biopsy demonstrated numerous intraepithelial eosinophils and eosinophilic microabscesses consistent with eosinophilic esophagitis.
The tumor was constituted by blastomatous areas, containing epithelioid cells, and sarcomatous areas, containing fusiform cells.
Pathology slide showing bladder wall with colonic adenocarcinoma tumor deposits.

Lung biopsy showed moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma with two fragments of fibrocollagenous tissue and alveolar tissue displaying infiltration by tumour cells in small clusters, glandular, and single cell patterns.

Pathologic finding of tumor specimen. There were two parts, dura and scalp. B was removed from the epidural layer including dura mater. The features shown are compatible with osteoblastic osteosarcoma.
Diffuse infiltration of gastric mucosa from a poorly differentiated poorly cohesive gastric adenocarcinoma, including mixed adenocarcinoma with > 50% signet ring cells features.
Lymphoma cells infiltrate decidua in between chorionic villi.  CV  chorionic villi,  L  lymphoma cells.
Chondrosarcoma
Spindle cell carcinoma-malignant epithelial cells showing spindling/sarcomatoid appearance (H&E stain, ×100)
Histological examination of the biopsy specimens confirmed the diagnosis of diffuse large B-cell lymphoma (DLBCL).
Invasive ductal breast carcinoma with infiltrating margins. Low-power photomicrograph showing invasive ductal carcinoma.
Histopathologic aspects of myxoid and round cell liposarcoma.
Histopathology of esophagus biopsy shows ulceration of the mucosa with granulation tissue.
Appearance of atypical cells in leiomyosarcoma.
Abnormal lymphomatous cells in the duodenal bulb.
Glioblastoma.
Histopathology of the right ureter represented a lesion of a metastatic prostate adenocarcinoma.
Left breast: invasive ductal carcinoma. Arrow shows focal area of mucin between sheets of malignant cells.

A case of lung adenocarcinoma in which the results of ROSE were negative and undiagnosed by EBUS-GS, but diagnosed by additional conventional TBB: B. the specimen obtained by EBUS-GS did not show malignant findings (hematoxylin and eosin staining).
H&E stain of the initial prostate biopsy of case 4 when he was diagnosed with prostatic adenocarcinoma ten years prior to this presentation.
Invasive lobular carcinoma of the breast with extra cellular mucin shows the classic pattern of lobular carcinoma with single cell infiltration and discohesive pattern.
Representative histologic images of follicular lymphoma showing partial involvement of regional lymph nodes.

Histologic section of plantar skin shows hyperparakeratosis with melanocytic
atypia in the basal layer of epidermal ridges with pleomorphism and oriented
upwards, characterizing malignant melanocytic lesion/acral melanoma. White
arrow shows the intermediate ridge. Black arrow shows the limiting ridges.
