Hematoxylin and eosin stain of lung adenocarcinoma.
Well-differentiated cartilage nodules surrounded by sarcoma components.

Presentation of UC with sarcomatoid changes (magnification, x10). Microscopically, the conventional urothelial component was mixed with the predominantly sarcomatous areas, which consisted of elongated spindled cells with vesicular, pleomorphic nuclei and conspicuous mitotic figures on a myxomatous background exhibiting a vaguely fascicular growth pattern. In this figure, obtained by hematoxolin-eosin staining, the nuclei appear colored as violet while the cytoplasm takes on a pink color.
Well-differentiated thyroid carcinoma with high-grade features showing necrosis using H&E stain.
Invasive adenocarcinoma of the pancreatic head.
Lymph node showing follicular lymphoma, sclerosing variant.
Pathologic examination confirmed the diagnosis of papillary thyroid carcinoma.
Oesophageal biopsy showing squamous mucosa with chronic inflammation concentrated around basal epithelium and Civatte body formation consistent with lichen planus.
Streptococcus agalactiae  infected section showing increased melanomacrophage cells and inflammatory cell infiltration.

Primary CNS peripheral T-cell lymphoma, not otherwise specified (PTCL, NOS). This example shows enlarged lymphoid cells with convoluted nuclei with scant to moderate cytoplasm embedded within swaths of associated necrosis.
Bronchial brush smear of squamous cell carcinoma showed pleomorphic and hyperchromatic cells in sheets.
Higher power view showing melanoma cells some of which are producing brown melanin pigment.
Follicular thyroid carcinoma (FTC) with a focus of vascular invasion found in an encapsulated angioinvasive FTC.
The follicular thyroid carcinoma with minimally invasive capsular infiltration.
Photomicrographs show multiple fragments of leiomyosarcoma tissue displaying perivascular hyalinization.
Histopathological sections showing a hobnail-like appearance of tumor cells with irregular and hyperchromatic nuclei resembling malignant mesothelioma.
Type 2 endometrial carcinoma: clear cell carcinoma of the endometrium. H&E sections showing tumor glands lined by clear cells.
Histopathology of the excised melanoma of the left sole.
Biopsied mass showing poorly-differentiated gastric adenocarcinoma.

Gastric cancer detected after Helicobacter pylori eradication: A case of type 0-IIc early gastric cancer in which the lesion measures 7 mm and has a typical irregular microvascular pattern and irregular microsurface pattern. Histopathological findings. The lesion consists of a well-differentiated adenocarcinoma.
Osteoid (pink) from osteosarcoma metastasis seen in a lymph node. Note the blue lymphoid cuff on the rim of the lymph node just under the capsule, identifying it as a largely replaced lymph node.
Histologic examination showed atypical, hyperchromatic spindle cells and osteoid formation, consistent with osteosarcoma.
Microscopic images of the tumor from the histopathologic specimen show normal small bowel mucosa and invasive adenocarcinoma.
The pathology of patients with PENL and DLBCL, with the primary site from the central nervous system.
2.5 cm angiosarcoma with positive surgical margins. Tumor cells with vesicular nuclei and abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm.
Biopsy of the ulcer with hematoxylin and eosin stain, depicting infiltration in a nesting fashion on the left side consistent with metastatic melanoma. Normal mucosa evident on the right.
Histopathology of left eye: conjunctival melanoma with free margins and evident melanocytes with nuclear pleomorphism.
Adrenocortical carcinoma with diffuse architecture and capsular invasion.
Sarcomatous pattern with neoplastic spindle cells in fascicles.

Histopathological examination by H&E staining shows a biphasic pattern with the benign odontogenic epithelium resembling a cord or island, and sarcomatous mesenchymal elements combined with dentine matrix formation.

Photomicrograph of the lung of an adult alpaca with bronchioalveolar adenocarcinoma. H & E stained section of the lung shows a predominantly lepidic growth pattern along pre-existing alveolar walls and abundant fibrous stroma. Note an area of squamous epithelial cells differentiation (arrow). Bar, 100 μm
Core needle biopsy of Kaposi sarcoma shows fascicles comprised of spindled tumor cells.
Examples of PARP-1 staining in uveal melanoma cells: example of high expression (100×).
Pathologic evaluation of the patient’s splenic tissue confirms the presumptive diagnosis of splenic marginal zone lymphoma.
Histological features of germ-cell tumor (seminoma) with somatic malignant transformation. Metastatic spindle cell sarcoma within the spermatic cord (H&E 200x).
Photomicrograph shows histopathological features of spindle cell sarcoma.
Pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma, poorly differentiated: three-dimensional clusters in mitosis and hyperchromatic nuclei in cell block.
Histological findings of a patient with DLBCL OIIA show diffuse infiltration of lymphoma cells.

Oral malignant melanoma (OMM), hematoxylin and eosin staining.  (A)  OMM with junctional activity and composed predominantly of subepithelial spindloid cells with <5% containing pigment. Magnification, ×4.  (B)  Higher magnification of  (A)  highlighting junctional activity (intraepithelial nests within the basal layer of the epithelium). Magnification, ×40.
Hematoxylin and eosin stain showing small intestine submucosa attacked by Kaposi sarcoma.
Interdigitating dendritic cell sarcoma with spindle cells showing mild to moderate nuclear atypia, hyperchromatism, and mild pleomorphism with sheets of small lymphocytes.
Adenocarcinoma with extensive mucin dissecting into the prostatic stroma.
Microscopic slides of recurred mass show osteoid tissue, indicating the transformation to osteosarcoma, with foci of necrosis.

Histology images of FFPE slides from a long survival PDAC case with histological grade 2 showing irregular gland formation located in rich stroma. Abnormal epithelium imitating normal duct epithelium. Adenocarcinoma is situated in the upper right part of the picture and infiltrates an atrophied pancreas parenchyma.
Infiltration of the cardiac muscle by angiosarcoma.
Bone marrow biopsy of a T-cell-rich/diffuse large B-cell lymphoma.
Glandular proliferation lined with cylindrical epithelial cells with atypical and hyperchromatic nuclei that are compatible with microfoci of invasive gastric adenocarcinoma of the intestinal type.
Desmoglein 2 staining is lower in pancreatic cancer cell membranes compared to normal and chronic pancreatitis tissue. Membrane staining was much weaker in pancreatic adenocarcinoma (PaC) samples.
Biopsy specimen of the proximal left femur of a 76-year-old Caucasian female with diagnosis of dedifferentiated chondrosarcoma using Hematoxylin and Eosin stain.
Lung: high power view of aggregate of primary lung adenocarcinoma cells.
Malignant mesothelioma, epithelioid variant . The tumor exhibits papillary and tubular pattern (H&E, original magnification × 200)
Clear-cell sarcoma comprises of nests of epithelioid cells separated by fibrous septa. There are uniform round nuclei and eosinophilic to clear cytoplasm.
Esophageal biopsy reveals eosinophilic infiltration.

Histological section after hindquarter amputation demonstrating large dilated vascular spaces lined by a dense population of atypical plump endothelial-like cells, which are surrounded by disorganized small diameter vascular channels. These features are consistent with angiosarcoma.
Photomicrograph showing a hypercellular tumor with spindle-shaped melanocytes suggestive of malignant melanoma
Metastatic pulmonary adenocarcinoma showing pseudopapillary cluster with nuclear enlargement and cellular crowding.

Photomicrograph from fine needle aspiration biopsy of the thyroid nodule reveals cytologic features of papillary thyroid cancer characterized by groups of follicular cells with nuclear enlargement and intranuclear pseudo-inclusions.
Representative haematoxylin and eosin-stained mediastinal lymph node tissue sections showing diffuse large B-cell lymphoma cells with non-germinal centre type.
Invasive lobular carcinoma of the breast with extra cellular mucin shows the classic pattern of lobular carcinoma with single cell infiltration and discohesive pattern.

Plaque stage Kaposi sarcoma with large numbers of intracellular and extracellular eosinophilic hyaline globules. The arrows indicate so-called 'autolumination' with paranuclear vacuoles containing erythrocytes.
Epithelioid mesothelioma presenting as metastatic lymph node of the mediastinum.
FNAC of Thyroid Nodule Showing Features of Papillary Thyroid Carcinoma.
Lipoma-like variant of well-differentiated liposarcoma/atypical lipomatous tumor, showing variation in adipocyte size, hyperchromatic nuclei, and lipoblasts.
Lymphoma. Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma with large atypical discohesive cells and distinct nucleoli.
Adenocarcinoma of pancreas; hematoxylin and eosin.

The intestinal type of periampullary adenocarcinoma typically resembles colon cancer, consisting of solid nests with cribriform areas, and having tall and often pseudostratified columnar epithelium with oval nuclei located in the more basal aspects of the cytoplasm. There may also be the presence of mucin.

Typical morphological features of mesenchymal chondrosarcomas showing a biphasic pattern of cartilage islands distributed among spindle cells, mainly located in the periphery. Chondrocytes showed moderate nuclear atypia, while spindle cells exhibited nuclear hyperchromatism and pleomorphism.
The histology of leiomyosarcoma shows spindle cells with cigar-shaped nuclei, mitotic activity, and pleomorphic nuclei.
Papillary adenoma is characterized by an encapsulated papillary proliferation arising in the renal cortex.
Papillary thyroid carcinoma: the neoplastic cells show overlapping clear nuclei and abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm (tall cell variant).
Rectal biopsy showing adenocarcinoma displaying nuclear stratification and crowding with frequent atypical mitotic figures.
Histopathological variants of colorectal cancer. Mucinous adenocarcinoma characterized by abundant extracellular mucin production.
Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma (DLBCL): the tumor composed of diffuse infiltration of large lymphoid cells in all wall layers of the affected terminal ileum.
Histologic image showing a cholangiocarcinoma.

H&E stained sections demonstrate a sarcomatoid solid tumor comprised of round to oval cells with hyperchromatic nuclei of variable size, numerous scattered mitotic figures including atypical forms, and multiple foci with osteoid and calcifications. Presence of osteoid is a diagnostic requirement for osteosarcoma.
Examples of homologous carcinosarcoma.
Papillary renal cell carcinoma (type 2) with fibrovascular cores covered by pseudostratified eosinophilic neoplastic epithelium.
Histopathology of the tumor shows microvascular proliferation, confirming the diagnosis of glioblastoma.
Histopathological findings of the primary and recurrent hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) in the right lobe of cirrhotic liver. Both tumors were confirmed by pathology as poorly differentiated HCC.
Microscopical features of extraskeletal myxoid chondrosarcoma: Detail of lipoblast-like cells presenting eosinophilic, vacuolated cytoplasm and round displaced nuclei.
Microscopic finding for the rectum shows a mucinous adenocarcinoma.
H&E staining of bile duct epithelium in cholangiocarcinoma (CCA) tissue.
Surgical specimen showing papillary thyroid carcinoma: complex and branching papillae, with overlapping and grooved nuclei.
Biopsy of this lesion confirmed an EBV positive B-cell lymphoma. Histology showed large atypical lymphocytes.
H and E stained slide. Sarcomatoid carcinoma showing a predominant spindle cell population with pleomorphic cells arranged in interlacing fascicles.

Hematoxylin and eosin (H&E)-stained sections demonstrated a glial neoplasm with a fibrillary background and moderate-to-severe cellularity and nuclear atypia, as well as scattered mitoses. The histology was within the spectrum of that seen in IDH-wildtype glioblastoma, with no obvious unusual features.
Sarcomatoid carcinoma presenting round cells, giant pleomorphic cells, and spindle-shaped anisokaryocytic cells.
Microscopic view of angiosarcoma using hematoxylin and eosin stain.
DFSP with fibrosarcomatous change shows long, sweeping fascicles of spindle cells intersecting at varied angles in a 'herringbone' pattern.
Testicular tumor shows a diffuse infiltrate of round clear cells with central nuclei and prominent nucleoli, consistent with classical Seminoma.
Histological findings of the surgical specimen of the left breast tumor show invasive ductal carcinoma.
Microscopic findings of the tumor show fused and cribriform glands infiltrating into the stroma. The nuclei are atypical and show brisk mitotic activity, consistent with cholangiocarcinoma.
The spleen was infiltrated by low-grade B-cell lymphoma with the proliferation of small-to-medium-sized cells.  Hematoxylin and eosin.
Photomicrograph showing colonic brushings in a case of adenocarcinoma with pleomorphic tumor cells and Langhans giant cell.
H&E stained slide demonstrating atrial myxoma tissue and B cell lymphoma with B cell lymphocytic infiltrates into atrial myxoma.

A, Before treatment, a representative biopsy result shows numerous compact nests of pleomorphic melanoma cells in the upper dermis. A few scattered melanophages filled with brown melanin pigment are also present.  B, After treatment, a clinically darkly pigmented lesion is composed of large clusters of melanophages only. No viable melanoma cells are present.
Adenocarcinoma infiltrating the colon with tumour cells forming irregular glands.
H/E image caption: High grade sarcoma with an infiltrating malignant spindle cell proliferation, pleomorphic multinucleated giant cells and atypical mitoses (left of center) (H and E, ×100)
Histopathologic findings show a combined sarcoma with liposarcoma and osteosarcoma zones.
Prostate adenocarcinoma, predominant Gleason 4 pattern and secondary Gleason 3 pattern (Gleason 4 + 3 = 7), H&E stain image, 400× magnification
The sarcomatous component showed scattered mitotic figures.
Hematoxylin and eosin staining for specimens obtained by CT-guided PCNB shows lung squamous cell carcinoma (SQC).
Hematoxylin and eosin staining of the specimens obtained by hemicolectomy showed infiltration of monomorphic and small- to medium-sized lymphoma cells in the mucosa and submucosa.
Oesophageal mucosa with erosive areas, presenting acanthosis, areas of spongiosis, and marked intraepithelial eosinophilic exocytosis with intraepithelial eosinophilic abscesses.
Endometrial carcinoma.
Histology of cervical angiosarcoma, showing endothelial cells with nuclear atypia, hobnailing, and scattered mitotic figures.  Fig. 2.
Histologic section of the primary tumor in the extremity showing a liposarcoma.
Tumor infiltration image of gastric metastasis of invasive lobular carcinoma of the breast seen in hematoxylin and eosin staining in resected gastric specimen.
The conventional types in multifocal papillary thyroid carcinoma reveal typical complex and branching papillae with characteristic nuclear features.
Human liver showing a hepatocellular carcinoma with a mixed acinar and trabecular growth pattern.
Postoperative histopathological photos confirmed that the lesion originated from renal clear cell carcinoma.
Images of a giant cell glioblastoma. Tumor sections were stained with HES.
Perineural invasion of prostatic adenocarcinoma with circumferential cancer growth around large nerves and cancer growing along a small nerve.
The poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma of the stomach characterized by signet-ring cell carcinoma and mucinous adenocarcinoma.
Bone marrow involvement by NK/T cell lymphoma is identified by H&E stain.
Hematoxylin and eosin staining showed proliferation of tumor cells with extensive pleomorphism and mitoses, consistent with osteosarcoma.
Hematoxylin–eosin staining of the prostate biopsy shows adenocarcinoma with collapsed ductal structure. Gleason score cannot be determined due to post‐androgen deprivation therapy.
Mantle zone lymphoma. The germinal center was surrounded by a thickened lymphocyte sleeve.
H&E staining of the original tumor and tumor from a patient-derived xenograft indicates moderately differentiated cholangiocarcinoma.

Hematoxylin and eosin stained sections of the gastric adenocarcinoma resected from our patient show irregular glands formed by tumor cells of varying sizes and orientation, with prominent nucleoli. The large clear spaces are fat cells.
Primary diffuse large B cell lymphoma of CNS with proliferation of tumor cells as solid and some accumulation in the perivascular space.
Histopathological picture of the lymphoma: nodular lymphoid infiltrates arranged in a follicular pattern in the dermis.
Histopathological examination revealed perivascular and diffuse distribution of relatively large lymphoma cells and smaller reactive lymphocytes.
Typical calcified osteoid in conventional osteosarcoma.

Histological findings of the vaginal malignant melanoma biopsied on the first day (before itraconazole treatment). Haematoxylin and eosin staining. Nested tumour cells can be observed under the normal squamous epithelium lining; the tumour cells show pleomorphism, multinuclei, bizarre nuclei, prominent nucleoli, and mitosis (inset).
Photomicrograph showing histology of mesothelioma with broad papillae and edematous fibrous cores.
Lung adenocarcinoma.

Lung adenocarcinoma: Glandular structures are visible in the cancer tissue and cancer cells are comparatively large with abundant cytoplasm and large nuclei containing secretory granules or mucocysts.
Histological examination of the pancreatectomy specimen showing medium-sized glands with haphazard growth embedded in dense desmoplastic stroma, characteristic findings of pancreatic adenocarcinoma.
Histopathological examination shows spindle cells in DFSP without fibrosarcomatous change.  DFSP: Dermatofibrosarcoma Protruberans.
The cells were rich in polymorphisms, and strong heteromorphic tumor cells forming osteoids were observed. The definitive diagnosis was osteoblastic osteosarcoma.

Light-microscopic images of liver from the early hepatocellular carcinoma group depicting details of the liver microstructure. Feature of low grade nodule showing a slight increase in cellularity, compared with the control tissue without architectural atypia.
Histopathological features of both the glial and the mesenchymal components of gliosarcoma. Mesenchymal compartment of the same tumour with collagenous fibres and spindle-cell-type nuclei.
Pathological changes in melanoma observed in the normal and model groups by H&E staining.
Histopathological analysis of lung tissues of adenocarcinoma in urethane-injected lung tissues.
Tissue morphology in the follicular lymphoma group.
The pictures show typical papillary growth pattern of glandular epithelial cells, which is usually seen in papillary thyroid carcinoma.
Composite histology of Follicular lymphoma transformation to large cell lymphoma. The inset shows high power view of the large cell lymphoma component.
This case was diagnosed as follicular variant of papillary thyroid carcinoma. Biopsy specimens were retrieved from surrounding normal parenchyma.
High power magnification showing atypical tumor cells with larger, irregular nuclei and intracytoplasmic hyaline globule commonly found in well and moderately differentiated chondrosarcoma.
Higher power view illustrating the invasive melanoma component and the atypical fibroxanthoma component.  AFX - atypical fibroxanthoma.
Round blue cell sarcoma arising in AFH with atypical round to oval cells with vesicular nuclei and brisk mitotic activity. 20x magnification.
Initial trans rectal prostate biopsies showing Gleason 4 + 5 = 9 adenocarcinoma of the prostate.

Skin biopsy showing pancreatic adenocarcinoma with dermal involvement of irregularly shaped aggregates of epithelium arranged as glandular structures lined by cells characterized by enlarged vesicular and hyperchromatic nuclei with conspicuous nucleoli.

H&E histological slide of the patient's papillary renal cell carcinoma, Fuhrman grade III, showing neoplastic papillary structures lined by eosinophilic cuboidal epithelial cells with ovoid nuclei and conspicuous nucleoli.
Biopsy demonstrating metastatic prostatic adenocarcinoma.
Fibrosarcomatous areas with a fascicular pattern of spindle-shaped cells.

Hematoxylin and eosin stained sections of the gastric adenocarcinoma resected from our patient. Cytological features of malignant glands; the cells are irregularly shaped with high nucleus to cytoplasm ratio and loss of nuclear polarity. The small dark cells are inflammatory cells.

The resection specimen shows areas of necrosis as well as microvascular hyperplasia. The cellularity is also higher than in the previously resected specimen. Presence of necrosis and microvascular hyperplasia are features supporting glioblastoma.
Hematoxylin and eosin section showing monomorphic population of neoplastic lymphoid cells and large pale macrophages forming the'stars' in the'starry sky' typical of Burkitt Lymphoma.

A 29-yr-old female patient has a small papillary carcinoma at the left lobe of the thyroid gland, the size is approximately 0.7 × 0.6 cm. bFGF × 100, the cytoplasm is strongly positive (+++) in papillary thyroid carcinomas and negative in the surrounding normal thyroid tissue.
Composite image showing cellularity, intact cell morphology, and different architectural patterns of lung adenocarcinoma in cell block preparation, including a cribriform pattern.
Light Microscopic Appearance of Ewing’s Sarcoma demonstrating areas of mixed solid and trabecular areas.
Grade I chondrosarcoma shows mild positive cytoplasmic and nuclear reaction to MMP-13 (ABC DAB).
Hobnail variant of papillary thyroid carcinoma (PTC) and mimicker. Hobnail-like morphology is often seen in classic PTC with cystic changes.
Hematoxylin and eosin staining of the same organoid line reveals nucleolar prominence and cell adhesions, confirming pancreatic duct adenocarcinoma origin.
Interspersed throughout the tumor are more cellular regions composed of spindle cells reminiscent of Kaposi sarcoma but without significant cytologic atypia, mitotic activity, or necrosis.
Invasive prostatic adenocarcinoma infiltrating into skeletal muscle.
Photomicrograph showing metaplastic bone formation and necrosis in sarcoma-like area.
Glioblastoma with extensive areas of coagulative tumour necrosis.
Hematoxylin and eosin staining of lung adenocarcinomas shows a low abundance of tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes and atypical cancer cells with atypical nuclei.
Representative images of typical morphological features of renal cell carcinomas showing a papillary pattern with voluminous clear cells and psammoma bodies.
Some unusual morphological features of papillary renal neoplasm with reverse polarity and hemosiderin deposits in the cytoplasm of tumor cells, especially in the edge of tumors.
Moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of the lung associated with desmoplastic reaction.
Entire stomach wall infiltrated with solid nests of tumor tissue, with occasional central necrosis. Tumor is adenocarcinoma grade III. Notes:  Hematoxylin and eosin stain.
Abnormal blasts in B-cell non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.
Surgery of brain tumor showed adenocarcinoma lung cancer (HE × 40).
Shows the histology of coexisting medullary thyroid carcinoma and Hashimoto's thyroiditis.
Typical histological photomicrograph of KHE showing nodules of spindle-shaped endothelial cells resembling Kaposi sarcoma.
Histologic findings of primary lung adenocarcinoma showing tumor cells arranged in fascicles with elongated nuclei showing palisading.
Adenocarcinoma of the large intestine.
Invasive adenocarcinoma of lung showing acinar type with some glands containing intraluminal and intracellular mucin.
Prostatic ductal adenocarcinoma tumor cells are high columnar and amphophilic, surrounded by abundant cytoplasm. Tumor cells are arranged in single or pseudostratified layers.
Histopathological examination of mixed-type liposarcoma tissue shows a well-differentiated component.

Helicobacter pylori-positive gastric cancer: A case of type 0-IIc early gastric cancer in which the lesion measures 14 mm and has a typical irregular microvascular pattern and irregular microsurface pattern. Histopathological findings. The tumor consists of a well-differentiated adenocarcinoma.
H&E staining of lung adenocarcinoma.
Central part of the pheochromocytoma with irregular, diffuse hemorrhages between tumour nests.
Muscle specimen of the upper part of the esophagus showing wave-like deformation of the myocytes and myocytes of different thicknesses.

Histopathologic findings of the biopsy specimens of gastric cancer show well-differentiated adenocarcinoma.
Histomorphological features of pleomorphic liposarcoma with sporadic, pleomorphic lipoblasts.
Growth of well-differentiated liposarcoma.
A poorly-differentiated malignant mesothelioma consisting of monomorphic small-sized epithelioid cells.
Photomicrograph of right lung mass biopsy showing features of adenocarcinoma lung.

Histological features of mucinous colon adenocarcinoma and gastric carcinoma – intestinal type. Gastric cancer, intestinal type. Tumor is composed of confluent tubular structures consisting of atypical cells with hyperchromatic nuclei similar to intestinal adenocarcinoma, which invade the submucosal gastric area. In the upper part is antral mucosa with reactive mucinous foveolar hyperplasia.
Tumor cells originate from the esophagus.  Hematoxylin and eosin staining.
Histologically, the tumor is composed of lymphoma cells.
Pathological biopsy revealed left lung moderately-differentiated adenocarcinoma.

The effect of IRE on uveal melanoma tumor in primary eye enucleated eye from a 45-year-old woman presented with an extra-large choroidal melanoma. An area far away from the electrodes that were applied to the sclera was seemingly unaffected by treatment, probably because the electric field was lower than ablation thresholds. Note that lymphocytes are not affected by treatment at the area where tumor cells were ablated.
Section from a liver nodule shows hepatocellular carcinoma with many acinar structures.
Biphasic tumor composed of poorly differentiated carcinoma nests and sarcomatous elements.
Histopathology images of cardiac intimal sarcoma showing cells arranged in spindles with high mitotic activity and abundant blood vessels.
Trans urethral resection of the prostate showing new moderate to poorly differentiated keratinising squamous cell carcinoma with no evidence of adenocarcinoma.
Carcinosarcoma with heterologous elements, showing rhabdomyoblastic differentiation.

In this image, we can observe an infiltrate consisting of atypical spindled endothelial cells forming vascular channels intersecting between collagen bundles. Promontory sign (normal vessel enveloped in atypical vascular space) is present. This characteristic is not specific for KS and can also be seen in other vascular neoplasms such as angiosarcoma.
Histopathology of rectal mass at autopsy showing mucinous features of the adenocarcinoma.
Esophageal biopsy showing a single nest of tumor cells in a background of intestinalized metaplastic epithelium.
Metastasis of melanoma and carcinoma to a single regional lymph node, the upper part shows melanoma while the lower part of the image shows carcinoma.
The pheochromocytoma pattern of the composite tumor.
Segmentation of round cell liposarcoma without cell and nucleus outlines.
Variable dominant cell morphology in advanced acral melanoma. Spindle cells.
Haematoxylin & Eosin stain of biopsy sample showing a chondroblastic osteosarcoma.
Pathology of lacrimal sac melanoma: Large epithelioid cells with abnormal nuclei arranged in irregular strands and foci.
Representative images of esophageal ulcerative lesions (H&E stain). Superficial ulcer.
Postoperative microscopic pathology of the inflammatory myofibroblastic tumors. C: Intense positivity of the spindel cells for anaplastic lymphoma kinase.
An unusual case of epithelioid mesothelioma with bland-looking adenomatoid-like spaces diffusely expressing calretinin.
Microscopic images of primary pulmonary mucoepidermoid carcinoma showing solid nests and a cystic component with hyalinization stroma, foci of calcification, and mucus in the cystic component.
Fine-needle aspiration from thyroid nodule showing follicular variant of thyroid carcinoma.

Photomicrographs of metastatic pheochromocytoma cases with elevated PASS scores previously diagnosed at our institution. This tumor was resected from a 61-year old female who developed metastatic disease 9 years after initial diagnosis.
Colorectal adenocarcinoma with intraluminal necrosis.
Pathological findings from the small nodular mass in the mesentery of the small bowel revealed adenocarcinoma in fibrofatty tissue.
Histopathologic findings of acral lentiginous melanoma show melanoma cells proliferating along the dermo-epidermal junction and invading into the dermis.
Histologic features of glioblastoma with PNET-like components and small round blue cell component.
Primary melanoma of the biliary tract. At high magnification, some malignant melanocytes revealed finely granular cytoplasmic melanin.
Primary cardiac extraskeletal osteosarcoma with osteoclast-like giant cells.  H&E staining.
Haematoxylin and eosin stain showing the epithelioid component of pleural mesothelioma.

showing Barrett’s mucosa with high-grade dysplasia (arrows), but no

Superficial spreading melanoma on the abdomen of an 82-year-old man. The atypical network correlates with the hyperpigmented rete ridges with atypical melanocytes in single units and irregular nests mostly arranged at the dermoepidermal junction.
On the esophagus and trachea, there is a densely cellular, unencapsulated, highly invasive neoplasm.

Prostate cancer displaying universal neuroendocrine differentiation . Universal NED is synonymous to SCCP. This cancer type is rarer than conventional prostatic adenocarcinoma (fewer than 1% of total PCa cases) and prognosis is dismal. Histologically, cells display scarce cytoplasm, hyperchromatic nuclei with finely dispersed chromatin and inconspicuous nucleoli, and nuclear molding. Mitotic index is high and necrosis often is present. In about half of the cases, the small cell carcinoma is admixed with areas of conventional prostatic adenocarcinoma. The Gleason scale cannot be used for pure SCCP, but in mixed cases it should be used to grade the adenocarcinoma regions. H&E stain. Courtesy and with permission of Dharam M. The patient underwent excisional biopsy of the inguinal lymph node, and the pathologic diagnosis was consistent with metastatic MM (hematoxylin and eosin staining, x200) (A). HMB45 positivity in atypical melanocytes that metastasized to the lymph node (HMB45, x200) (B). The patient underwent a combined wide local excision with negative margins and inguinal and parailiac lymph node dissection. The skin defect in the hip was reconstructed with a split skin graft. Pathologic examination demonstrated that the MM infiltrated into the entire dermis and metastasize into the lymph node. Two months later, magnetic resonance imaging showed soft tissue mass of 5x3.5x3 cm in size in the right pelvic region, considered conglomerate lymph nodes. The patient underwent surgery for this mass, and pathological examination revealed melanoma metastasis to the lymph node with extranodal soft tissue involvement. The patient was treated with chemotherapy, interferon, and radiotherapy. The patient died 12 months after the diagnosis of MM. Childhood MM is extremely uncommon, representing only 0.3%-0.4% of all melanomas in prepubertal children aged <15 years ( 1 ). Depending on the size of the lesion, CMN carries an increased risk for the development of childhood melanoma. Giant CMNs (>20 cm) have been reported to have increased risk of developing melanomas, particularly during the first and second decades of life ( 2 ). However, cutaneous melanomas rarely arise from small (≤1 cm) and medium (1.5-20 cm) CMNs. Risk factors for developing melanoma from a CMN include irregular borders, increased diameter, color change, surface ulceration, and bleeding. Cutaneous MM poses a high risk of dissemination to regional lymph nodes and visceral organs. Childhood MM is a potentially fatal disease. Accurate staging of patients with melanoma is especially important if clinically occult systemic metastasis is present, which may preclude them the benefit of a complex lymph node dissection for locoregional control ( 1 ). The most appropriate imaging approach for diagnosing and following pediatric patients with MM has been adopted usually from adult guidelines because of its rarity ( 3 ). In staging melanoma,  18 F-FDG PET/CT is often employed to evaluate distant metastatic disease, as melanoma is very  18 F-FDG avid ( 3 ). In addition to staging, PET/CT plays an important role in patient management, such as deciding on the extent of surgery, determination of radiation field, and evaluation of treatment response. The current case also underlines the importance of whole-body oncologic assessment by  18 F-FDG PET scan in pediatric MM, which is a rare but a serious clinical entity.

Conventional osteosarcoma within a preexisting histological confirmed giant cell tumour, suggesting primary malignant transformation.
Small round cell osteosarcoma. The tumor is composed of a uniform population of round cells with focal production of osteoid matrix.

Biopsy of the ileum shows a submucosal lymphoid neoplasm composed of a polymorphous population of cells consisting of centrocytes, centroblasts, atypical lymphoid cells with an intended nucleus, basophilic cytoplasm, and perinuclear clear Golgi zone seen. Hallmark cells with an eccentric horseshoe-shaped nucleus and occasional doughnut cells were noted.
Histopathology of ovarian high-grade serous carcinoma showing nuclear pleomorphism and frequent mitotic figures. Nuclear atypia is characteristic of high-grade tumors. 200× magnification.
Photomicrographs of H & E stained right parietal lobe mass excision demonstrating metastatic melanoma with non-brisk TILs and areas of mild to moderate hemorrhage.
Pheochromocytoma: nests and sheets of amphophilic polygonal cells are separated by vascular spaces.
Aspiration smear showing monomorphic population of atypical lymphoid cells in a case of high grade non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.
Carcinomatous component and sarcomatous component are completely separated by fibrous septae.

Lung adenocarcinoma metastasis to the left second toe. The H&E section shows the dermal infiltration of adenocarcinoma; the tumor cells are arranged in a glandular growth pattern. No involvement of epidermis.
A histological examination of the pancreas shows well-differentiated tubular adenocarcinoma similar to the cancer seen in the leptomeninges in the pancreatic tail.
Image of rhabdomyosarcoma cells.
Photomicrograph of the primary thyroid carcinoma illustrating papillary carcinoma with tall cell features.
Plasmablastic lymphoma. The tumor cell is large with prominent nucleoli.
Hematoxylin/eosin (HE) staining of lung squamous carcinoma tissues.
Sarcomatous component shows undifferentiated spindle cells.
Mesenchymal component appeared as fibrosarcoma.
Malignant mesotheliomas in the pleural/mediastinal cavity showing invasion of the pericardium.
Photomicrograph showing childhood papillary thyroid carcinoma (follicular variant).

Analysis of a cellblock obtained via brushing revealing an exon 19 deletion in a 63‐year‐old male patient with left lower lobe lung adenocarcinoma whose transbronchial needle aspiration cellblock was positive for malignancy but inadequate for analysis. Hematoxylin and eosin staining.
Adenocarcinoma of human lung was stained by hematoxylin and eosin.
Tissue of pituitary gland with cell-rich infiltrate of lymphoma. Large cells with nuclei display prominent nucleoli. On red square adjacent area of lymphocytic hypophysitis.
High-grade osteosarcoma component.
Histopathological examination revealed perivascular and diffuse distribution of relatively large lymphoma cells and smaller reactive lymphocytes.
Prostate adenocarcinoma with a mixed pattern.

An 81-year-old male with invasive lung adenocarcinoma (Acinar 88.3%, MP 5.6%, Scar 6.1%). Surgical pathology demonstrates a focal micropapillary pattern on the anteromedial side of the tumor with background of an acinar pattern.
Small bowel mucosa infiltrated by cords of metastatic lobular adenocarcinoma cells.

MEITL H&E (×40): There is a predominantly diffuse, infiltrate of atypical medium-sized cells with scattered mitosis and apoptosis. MEITL, monomorphic epitheliotropic intestinal T-cell lymphoma; H&E, hematoxylin and eosin.
Tumor in the liver showed Edmondson grade II hepatocellular carcinoma.
Right breast biopsy positive for invasive ductal carcinoma.
Gastric adenocarcinoma with good tubular and secretory differentiation.
Sarcomatous-appearing tumor with multinucleated giant cells.
Histopathological examination of the breast tumor revealed invasive ductal carcinoma of the breast, histological grade III.

A section from breast tissue shows infiltrating atypical cells lying singly in nests and cords. These cells show marked anisonucleosis having pleomorphic hyperchromatic nuclei, prominent nucleoli, coarse chromatin surrounded by pale amphophilic cytoplasm. A few congested blood vessels are also seen. The above findings are suggestive of invasive ductal carcinoma of the breast.
Arrow (1) shows the normal colonic mucosa which is in direct continuity with the transformed colonic adenocarcinoma in the center (arrow 2) which infiltrate downwards in the submucosa.  Fig. 2.
Microscopically, two types of adenocarcinoma cells with dissimilar differentiation types were observed on the serosal surface of the rectum using Hematoxylin and Eosin staining.
Spindle vasoformative growth areas of angiosarcoma.
Histology image of spread through air space (STAS)-positive acinar-pattern lung adenocarcinoma showing a distinct border between the solid tumor and lung parenchyma.
The microscopic findings of the mass show diffuse proliferation and infiltration of atypical large lymphocytes, and lymphoma cells are distributed along the vascular channels as perivascular cuffs.
Extensive necrotic cells with occasional lymphoma cells.
Esophageal histology showing eosinophils organized in micro-abscesses.

Microphotographs of haematoxylin and eosin (H&E)-stained histological section of a core biopsy of a classical bone lymphoma show the focal preservation of the characteristic cellular and nuclear detail with clear cytoplasm and polylobated nuclei with somewhat coarser chromatin, leading to the correct diagnosis of diffuse large cell lymphoma.
Histopathological aspects of interdigitating dendritic cell sarcoma revealing a vaguely whorled growth pattern with abundant cytoplasm and empty nuclei.

Histopathological specimen showing nuclear pseudopalisading, aggregation of tumor cells around the periphery of the necrotic areas, increased mitotic activity, and vascular proliferation, which are the two important hallmarks of glioblastoma.
Image shows microscopic appearance of the nonseminomatous germ cell tumor with sarcomatous changes.

Expression of miR-92a in colorectal adenocarcinoma (CA) and its precancerous lesions, revealed by  in situ  hybridization (magnification, ×200). Low-grade intraepithelial neoplasia. Positive expression of miR-92a is represented by nitro blue tetrazolium/5-bromo-4-chloro-3-indolyl phosphate, with the nuclei counterstained by methylgreen. Scale bar, 100 μm.

Cell-block showing thyroid follicular cells with cribriform architecture in a case of cribriform/morular variant of papillary thyroid carcinoma. Note the presence of elongated nuclei with focal nuclear grooves and intranuclear pseudoinclusions.

Microscopic examination of the hematoxylin and eosin stained nail bed biopsy from a subungual amelanotic melanoma. Distant (top) and closer (lower) views show nests of malignant tumor cells that fill the dermis (short arrows). The neoplasm does not demonstrate any pigment. Individual tumor cells extend into the overlying epidermis (longer arrows in the bottom image) (Hematoxylin and eosin: top x4; middle upper x10; middle lower x10; bottom x40).
Histological images of CAP grading showing almost complete response to tumor treatment with residual adenocarcinoma in the submucosa of the gastric wall and extensive fibrous tissue hyperplasia.
Parathyroid carcinoma × 100 .
Napsin A positive stain for the lung adenocarcinoma metastasis to the pancreas. Magnifying power ×100.
Histological features of pancreatic adenocarcinoma and pancreatic intraepithelial neoplasias (PanINs). Pancreatic adenocarcinoma without PanIN (non-PanIN).
Malignant melanoma. Sheet of atypical melanocytes throughout papillary and reticular dermis (HE, 40x)
Tumor has an epitheloid and sarcomatoid areas.
Hematoxylin-eosin stain showing tumor cells. Diffuse large cell lymphoma.
Glomerulus with segmental and focal sclerosis in a patient with melanoma.
Histomorphological variation of pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma (PDAC) on hematoxylin and eosin staining.

Immature teratoma shows primitive neuroepithelial component, in addition to immature epithelial and mesenchymal tissues including immature cartilage (A), whereas carcinosarcoma is composed of carcinomatous (B, left) and sarcomatous components with malignant-looking cartilage (B, right).
Histopathological view of the specimen showing papillary excrescences typical of papillary thyroid carcinoma.
Histopathological features of SpSCC: Dysplastic epithelium and overt pleomorphism of the spindle cells in the sarcomatoid component.
The pathological diagnosis was moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma in a 4.7 cm × 4.6 cm-sized type 2 tumor in the rectosigmoid colon using HE staining.
Pathologic findings of primary breast carcinoma showing invasive ductal carcinoma growing within a desmoplastic stroma.
Lymphomatoid granulomatosis showing angiocentric proliferation of atypical lymphoid cells associated with Epstein-Barr virus.
Histology of chronic pancreatitis, pancreatic adenocarcinoma, and normal pancreas. Non-disease pancreas.
Initial diagnosis of liposarcoma.
Microscopic images of primary pulmonary mucoepidermoid carcinoma show the tumor is composed of mucous, intermediate, and epidermoid cells without keratinization.
Angiosarcoma comprising pleomorphic tumor cells, which form subtle lumina.
Hematoxylin/eosin staining for clear-cell RCC with sarcomatoid features, considered as grade 4 according to the International Society of Urologic Pathologists (ISUP).
Endoscopic biopsy specimen from the stomach, showing moderately differentiated tubular adenocarcinoma.

Microscopically, the neoplastic mass consists of round to polyhedral cells with round, often eccentric nuclei and abundant eosinophilic granular and microvacuolated cytoplasm, suggesting a histological diagnosis of a retroperitoneal myxoid liposarcoma.
The cartilaginous metaplasia seen in parosteal osteosarcoma can simulate the appearance of an osteochondroma due to the columnar arrangement of chondrocytes and the enchondral ossification.
Hematoxylin and eosin stain of endometrial endometrioid carcinoma showing the glandular pattern of neoplastic cells.

The histopathologic examination showed that the resected mass of lateral neck appeared as a cystic structure overlapped by lymphoid tissue with an internal surface lined by squamous cell carcinoma epithelium.
Detail of the Kaposi sarcoma proliferation replacing the subepithelial stroma.
Esophageal biopsies show granulomatous changes.
Pathological results confirmed cardiac spindle cell sarcomas.
Langerhans cell sarcoma. The tumor cells are highly pleomorphic and many tumor cells have hyperchromatic nuclei. There are infiltrations of neutrophils and eosinophils around the tumor cells.
Hodgkin lymphoma – smear shows classical Reed Sternberg cells with a background of reactive lymphoid cells.
Histologic features of the left atrial pleomorphic liposarcoma.
Microscopic findings: the mucinous adenocarcinoma in the rectal diverticulum. More than 50% of the lesion is composed of a mucin-containing malignant epithelium (H&E, ×100).
Synovial sarcoma.

Histologic features of combined hepatocellular-cholangiocarcinoma. Satellite nodule showing intermediate differentiation. Tumor cells show more abundant cytoplasm, structural pattern of trabeculae or nest, and scant fibrous stroma.
Histological features of germ-cell tumor (seminoma) with somatic malignant transformation. Classic seminoma (upper right corner) associated with spindle cell sarcoma (lower left corner), (H&E 200x).

Photomicrograph of metastatic malignant melanoma to gall bladder mucosa showing large cells with round to oval nuclei, prominent nucleoli, and intracytoplasmic pigment: Hematoxylin and Eosin stain, × 100 magnification.
Inflammatory variant of well-differentiated liposarcoma/atypical lipomatous tumor, dominated by a prominent lymphoplasmocytic infiltration. Note the atypical fat cells as well.
The example of lung adenocarcinoma from the raw dataset.
Asymmetric, not well-circumscribed melanocytic proliferation revealing a melanoma with a Breslow index of 0.45mm.
Histopathological examination revealed a large number of lymphoma cells.
Photomicrograph of the histology of the tumor mass showing sarcomatous spindle cell tumor, consistent with a diagnosis of gastrointestinal stromal tumor (GIST).

Histopathology of dedifferentiated liposarcoma showing dedifferentiated zones resembling undifferentiated pleomorphic sarcoma. The tumor is comprised of spindle cells with numerous mitotic figures; the cells are arranged in interlacing or storiform patterns.
Clusters of morulae comprised of mesothelioma cells.
Anal melanoma. Cross-section of the tumor region.
The heppar-1 stain marked the preserved isolated atypical hepatocytes and tubules in the sarcomatoid stroma.
Histopathologic findings of LP showing squamous epithelium in the middle and distal esophagus.

Section of an involved cervical lymph node showing the interface between an area of conventional papillary thyroid carcinoma (black arrow) with remnants of papillary structures and nuclear features, and an area of dedifferentiation towards anaplastic carcinoma (white arrow) with higher-grade nuclear atypia and sheet-like architecture. The lymph node metastasis of papillary thyroid carcinoma (PTC) showed compact squamous cell differentiation (SCD) foci with transition zones to the cystic zones.
Hematoxylin and eosin stained histologic section of the core biopsy of the left breast lesion demonstrating invasive lobular carcinoma.
Prostate adenocarcinoma: low-power view from left lateral mid prostate biopsy showing Gleason 4 + 4 = 8 pattern.
Histopathologic features of the histiocytic sarcoma show a well-demarcated tumor with high cellularity.

An 81-year-old male with invasive lung adenocarcinoma (Acinar 88.3%, MP 5.6%, Scar 6.1%). Surgical pathology demonstrates a focal micropapillary pattern on the anteromedial side of the tumor with background of an acinar pattern.

Well-differentiated endometrial carcinoma.
Composite image showing cellularity, intact cell morphology, and different architectural patterns of lung adenocarcinoma in cell block preparation, displaying a papillary pattern.

Mantle cell lymphoma involving appendix-lumen filled with monotonous atypical lymphoid infiltrate.
Primary effusion lymphoma, cell block preparation. Large atypical cells with irregular nuclei and visible nucleoli.
Histopathologic section from a patient with diffuse large B-cell non-Hodgkin lymphoma.
Histological features of mixed cellularity classical Hodgkin lymphoma (MCCHL) showing neoplastic cells scattered against a background rich in histiocytes and lymphocytes.
Proximal esophageal biopsy showing a heavy eosinophilic infiltration and microabscess formation.

Fine needle aspiration of the cervical lymph node with myeloid sarcoma revealed groups of atypical immature myeloid cells, mixed with occasional megakaryocytes, and eosinophilic myeloid cells infiltrating the lymph node.
Metastatic well-differentiated papillary thyroid carcinoma in lymph node.
The specimen shows synovial sarcoma composed of spindle cells with a hemangiopericytoma-like vascular pattern.

Hematoxylin and Eosin showing dark stained colloid (classic variant papillary thyroid cancer).

Anal melanoma. Cross-section of the external surface region.
Desmoplastic melanoma with neurotropic features showing malignant spindle-shaped cells tended to invade around nerves using H&E staining. Original magnification: ×200; ×400; ×400.
Esophagus: Subepithelial congestion and lymphocytic infiltrate.

16-year-old male with primary leptomeningeal melanoma. A slide from the resection of the epidural lesion at the base of the spine shows a largely necrotic tumor. The better preserved cells are dyscohesive, with round pyknotic nuclei and moderately abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm. Abundant dark brown patches suggest a melanocytic neoplasm.
5 Foxp3 + T regs /high-power field in a primary melanoma with no MMP-23 expression.
Placenta shows a monotonous population of medium-sized lymphoma cells infiltrating between scattered larger decidual cells.  D  decidual cells,  L  lymphoma cells.

Glioblastoma.

Biopsy of soft tissue located between the second and third tracheal cartilages on the right anterior portion of the trachea revealed histopathologic findings consistent with locally invasive classical papillary thyroid carcinoma.

MEITL H&E (×20): There is a predominantly diffuse, infiltrate of atypical medium-sized cells with scattered mitosis and apoptosis. MEITL, monomorphic epitheliotropic intestinal T-cell lymphoma; H&E, hematoxylin and eosin.

Microscopic image of chondrosarcoma.
Histological findings of parathyroid carcinoma showing vascular invasion.
Pathological finding of intestinal type of lung adenocarcinoma in a female patient with H&E stain.
Histologic features of benign prostate gland, high grade PIN, adenocarcinoma and SCNC. Prostatic adenocarcinoma showing proliferation of small, compact malignant glands (arrow).
14-day coculture of human PBMCs with Ewing's sarcoma-derived fibroblasts in the presence of M-CSF.

Classic histological appearance of spindle cell melanoma (SM) and desmoplastic melanoma (DM). SM is typically composed of amelanotic spindled cells. In desmoplastic melanoma thick strands of fibrous/collagenous tissue separate the neoplastic melanocytes. Note: Despite the spindled configuration of cytoplasmic outlines, the nuclear shape (i.e. circularity) differs between SM and DM.
Histopathological examinations of metastatic myxoid liposarcoma show uniform round-shaped non-lipogenic mesenchymal cells.

Tumor with areas resembling hemangioma and Kaposi's sarcoma.
The types of multinucleated giant cells seen in various thyroid lesions, including multinucleated giant cells in papillary thyroid carcinoma.
Melanoma showing positive (brown) nuclear and cytoplasmic staining.

Cellular smears of lymphoma showing isolated large round cells with scanty cytoplasm. Nucleoli are prominent.
Medullary thyroid carcinoma: histological findings. Two tumor nodules in dense fibrous tissue.
Columnar cell variant of papillary thyroid carcinoma (PTC) with columnar cells resembling secretory-type endometrium and supranuclear cytoplasmic vacuoles.
Tissue histology revealed mucinous adenocarcinoma of the lung with a largely lepidic pattern and smaller foci of acinar growth.
The appearance of the vascular structure conglomerated in the neurofibrillary matrix in the case of glioblastoma.
Needle biopsy specimen of the prostate showing an irregular arrangement of fused glands, indicative of poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma.  Gleason score was 4 + 4 = 8.
Papillary renal carcinoma in the hilar region of the left kidney with characteristic histology, including papillary and tubular structures, hemorrhages, and glazing of the connective tissue stroma.
Photomicrograph of periductal stromal sarcoma showing mitoses in the spindle cell stroma.
Histology types of thyroid cancer identified in this study include the solid variant of papillary thyroid carcinoma (PTC).
Follicular lymphoma with a monotonous population of small lymphocytes.
Healthy cell image, BL and DLBCL.
Some unusual morphological features of papillary renal neoplasm with reverse polarity and perineural invasion.
Histologic feature of malignant melanoma. The cells are medium-to large-sized with irregular nuclear contours, macronucleoli, and numerous mitotic activities (×400).
Psammoma bodies (PBs) in a papillary thyroid carcinoma: visible PBs with purple color in hematoxylin and eosin (HE) staining.
Microscopic appearance of the cyst wall and the prostate adenocarcinoma, with hematoxylin and eosin staining.
The lymphoma cells are squared off. Mitotic figures and apoptotic bodies are evident.

Follicular thyroid carcinoma (FTC) showing vascular invasion.
Barrett’s esophagus with high-grade dysplasia. This biopsy shows proliferation of glands with marked architectural complexity and enlarged and hyperchromatic nuclei. There is no surface maturation.
Adenocarcinoma of the left lung.
Normal esophageal squamous mucosa with a normal basal layer, no intraepithelial inflammatory cells, and no elongation of papillae from the lamina propria.
Histopathological analysis by hematoxylin and eosin (H&E) staining shows adenocarcinoma of the lung with a high intratumoral density of tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes (TILs).
Microscope findings of the esophagus biopsy.
Pathology report shows positive neoplastic lymphoma cells with a high volume of lymphocytes and high nuclear-cytoplasmic ratios.
Overview of colonic mucosa (glands) infiltrated by adenocarcinoma.
Chondrosarcoma section showing areas of less differentiated cartilaginous tissues characterized by spindled cells.

In the first biopsy of 2 years ago, it was revealed as lymphoid hyperplasia with proliferation of lymphocytes but there is no bizarre patterns. In the final biopsy, bizarre nodular infiltration and differentiations of lymphocytes were observed with forming lymphoepithelial lesion. After all, it turned out to be mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue lymphoma.
Osteoid and tumor bone without osteoblastic rimming suggestive of osteoblastic osteosarcoma.
Histopathological appearance of esophageal epithelium with eosinophilic esophagitis and numerous eosinophils.
Microscopic chondroid-type change demonstrating sarcoma differentiation.
Enteric-type adenocarcinoma invading into prostate gland using hematoxylin and eosin stain, similar to that seen in bladder specimen.
Postoperative histopathology report of spinal lesion showing features of necrosis, endothelial proliferation, brisk mitosis, and nuclear atypia suggestive of glioblastoma multiforme.
Primary glioblastoma with extensive microvascular proliferation.
Pleomorphic osteoblasts with minimal osteoid; bizarre mitosis and giant nuclei of osteosarcoma.
Architectural pattern of the cribriform-morular variant papillary thyroid carcinoma with solid zones containing spindle cells arranged in spiral and grooved nuclei.
Papillary renal cell carcinoma (type 2) with papillary structures covered by eosinophilic neoplastic cells with mild nuclear pleomorphism and visible nucleoli.  Haematoxylin and eosin staining.
Tumor pathology slides showing heterologous liposarcomatous differentiation with variably sized, hyperchromatic, atypical adipocytes, numerous lipoblasts, and high mitotic rate.
A tumour with two different entities is shown, with a poorly differentiated thyroid carcinoma (PDTC) and a coexisting follicular thyroid tumour.
Microscopic view of multiple foci of thyroid carcinoma, including medullary carcinoma of the left lobe.
Sclerosing epithelioid fibrosarcoma. Smears showed ovoid epithelioid cells embedded in a collagenous matrix.

Photomicrograph of the initial core needle biopsy depicts features of low grade parosteal osteosarcoma. The neoplastic stroma in between bone trabeculae contained spindle cells with small uniform nuclei. Histology was presented at the Multidisciplinary Sarcoma Tumor Board, and recommendation was made for distal femoral resection.
Section showing respiratory epithelium lined tissue with subepithelium infiltrated by an adenocarcinoma arranged in tubulo-acinar and micropapillary pattern.

Histological presentation of postauricular skin next to the melanoma. Paget cells are located in the epidermis and in the adnexal epithelium in the dermis. Pagetoid distribution of Paget cells in the epidermis.
Osteoblastic variant of osteogenic sarcoma of case 1 showing osteoblasts with cytonuclear pleomorphism and hyperchromatic nuclei surrounding malignant osteoid (X100).

Histologic examination of the curettage reveals sarcomatous, spindle shaped cells with adjacent tumor osteoid production; represented by eosinophilic, amorphous, fibrillary deposits between individual or small aggregates of tumor cells.
H and E stained slide showing pigmented melanoma cells.

Histological examination of the resected kidney tumor shows tumor cells arranged in a solid architectural pattern with indistinct cell borders and clear cytoplasm, consistent with renal clear cell carcinoma.

Microscopic examination of the punch biopsy of the metastatic melanoma on the left parietal scalp shows atypical melanocytes in a nodular configuration in the papillary dermis, extending deeply into the reticular dermis.
pleomorphic liposarcoma showing highly malignant tumour cells supplied with citoplasmic vacuolization consistent with multivacuolated lipoblasts (inset).
Microscopy of neuroendocrine tumor favoring small cell carcinoma of the esophagus.
Histology of the ampulla of Vater shows papilla infiltration by invasive ductal carcinoma of the breast.
Puncture cytology image of follicular epithelium showing variously sized and crowded cells with ground glass-like nuclei, consistent with papillary thyroid carcinoma.
H&E of colon showing invasive adenocarcinoma.

Haematoxylin and eosin stain of the collision tumour of the metastatic Merkel cell tumour within the tumour relapse of the dermatofibrosarcoma protuberans. Note the coexistence of a small cell tumour mass within a storiform, fascicular cell formation.
Type B microinvasive carcinoma of the breast: several small glandular ducts around the middle-grade ductal carcinoma in situ and no lymphocytes around small glandular ducts.
Foci of adenocarcinoma from the right colon demonstrating large amounts of mucin on the serosal surface.

Barrett esophagus-associated dysplasia with high-grade dysplasia.

Variability of expression of ENT1 transporter in normal pancreas and pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma (PDAC). PDAC cells with strong membranous and cytoplasmic staining for ENT1. Lymphoid elements show the same level of positivity, whereas non-neoplastic exocrine pancreas is virtually negative.
Arrow demonstrates adenocarcinoma of the prostate with complex glandular arrangement.

Metastatic melanoma replacing a lymph node with a thin rim of residual lymphocytes.

Representative hematoxylin and eosin section of the cancer sites showing endometrioid adenocarcinoma with extensive squamous differentiation involving the muscularis propria of the rectosigmoid colon site.
Pathologic picture of well-differentiated liposarcoma showing lipoblastic cells.

Primary vitreoretinal lymphoma in a 68-year-old female. Pleomorphic lymphomatous cells lying between the retinal pigment epithelium and the underlying choroid. The choroid has a reactive infiltrate of small non-neoplastic lymphocytes.
Ossification within clear cell chondrosarcoma.
Secondary glioblastoma with abrupt transition between low-grade and high-grade areas. High-grade areas are indicated by a long arrow, and low-grade areas are indicated by a small arrow.
Haematoxylin and eosin stain of the axillary tumour shows the characteristic partial storiform, partial fascicular growth of the dermatofibrosarcoma protuberans.
Histopathologic appearance of the granulocytic sarcoma in the testis with multiple mitotic figures.
Right breast biopsy positive for invasive ductal carcinoma.
Spleen: Nodular hyperplasia (lymphoid follicle) with lymphocytic follicular hyperplasia and no evidence of progression to lymphoma. The other follicles are normal.

Histopathological description of moderately differentiated lung squamous cell carcinoma (LUSC) with intra and extracellular keratinization.

Cervical lymph node biopsy showing effacement of architecture, replaced diffusely by large atypical cells with eosinophilic cytoplasm, ill-defined cell borders, irregular/round vesicular nuclei, and eosinophilic nucleoli; suggesting diffuse large B-cell lymphoma.

Partial resection of the lesion in its intracardiac portion of 4.6 × 2.4 × 1.3 cm. The pathology findings were pleomorphic leiomyosarcoma, arterial type, poorly differentiated. The pathology findings were pleomorphic leiomyosarcoma, arterial type, poorly differentiated and desmin positive in 70%.

Histological findings of splenic angiosarcoma showed proliferation of oval- to spindle-shaped cells having hyperchromatic nuclei arranged in an irregular microtubular pattern, accompanied by massive hemorrhage and necrosis.
Sarcomatoid carcinoma presenting round cells, giant pleomorphic cells, and spindle-shaped anisokaryocytic cells.

Microscopic findings of thyroid cancer showing tumor cells with characteristic nuclear features of papillary carcinoma: large, crowded, oval, optically clear, and grooved nuclei with small distinct nucleoli.

Photomicrograph of the intra-abdominal soft tissue sarcoma showing neoplastic spindle-shaped cells arranged in loose or densely packed interlacing, haphazardly oriented bundles. Tumor cells have small to moderate amounts of eosinophilic fibrillary cytoplasm with indistinct borders, and nuclei are oval with finely stippled chromatin and a nucleolus. Area of tumor myxoid differentiation is also observed.
Bronchial ciliated epithelium with large and small nuclei is observed. Some of these cilia are not seen, and differentiation of these findings from adenocarcinoma is required.
Histopathological examination showed that the tumor was composed of a mixture of well-differentiated lipoblast and pleomorphic liposarcoma with both atypical nuclear and multinuclear spindle cells.
Overview of the pancreatic adenocarcinoma colliding with the liposarcoma using Hematoxylin-Eosin staining.
Histological findings of ascending colon biopsy show adenocarcinoma.

Histologically, the lipoblastomas demonstrated predominantly myxoid stroma containing a rich capillary network, features which may lead to diagnostic confusion with myxoid liposarcoma (Case 7). Haematoxylin and Eosin (H&E) stain, 100x magnification.
Photomicrograph demonstrating lymphoma cells consisting of small to medium lymphocytes and plasmacytoid cells with abundant basophilic cytoplasm and lymphocyte-like nuclei.
Histopathological specimen of pancreatic tissue with well-differentiated ductal adenocarcinoma of pancreatic head.
Epithelioid melanoma cells invasion into lamina propria, which are arranged in sheets and islands, containing large prominent nucleoli and melanin.

Desmoplastic melanoma: atypical spindle cells in a dense fibrous matrix.

Sections of the primordial oesophagus on the 19th day of development showing the formation of the four tunics, the tunica mucosa lined by stratified squamous epithelium, submucosa, tunica muscularis, and tunica adventitia. The primordial oesophageal gland appeared in clusters in the tunica mucosa.
Candidatus Xenohaliotis californiensis inclusions within posterior esophagus epithelia. Arrows indicate classical inclusions and phage-containing variant inclusions.

Well-differentiated (lipoma-like) liposarcoma with sclerosing areas and numerous lipoblasts.

In situ  acral lentiginous melanoma with a lentiginous proliferation of atypical melanocytes along the dermoepidermal junction, with pagetoid spread and scattered nests at the tips of the rete ridges. There is also acanthosis, hypergranulosis, and hyperkeratosis. Tumour cells are hyperchromatic and have a cytoplasmic fixation retraction artefact. The dermis contains a chronic inflammatory cell infiltrate associated with macrophages.
Microphotograph of lung biopsy showing a malignant tumor with an epithelial appearance, consistent with adenocarcinoma or an epitheloid mesothelioma - Hematoxylin and Eosin Stain.

Histopathological examination of the second neoplasm confirmed a poorly to moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, which was not derived from the intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm: A metachronous pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma. Metastatic melanoma with relatively sharp demarcation, except for limited peripheral spread along perivascular spaces. The adjacent white matter appears pale and edematous.
Microphotograph showing Medullary thyroid carcinoma.

Papillary structures are seen projecting into the cystic spaces which contain eosinophilic material. Epithelial cells lining the cysts and papillae have clear cytoplasm. Solid areas of the tumor contain epithelial cells with a tubular growth pattern, clear cytoplasm, and low grade nuclei which are arranged in a 'picket-fence' like configuration, a classic feature for clear cell tubulopapillary renal cell carcinoma.
Carcinome sarcomatoide maxillaire: histologiquement, il s'agit d'une prolifération fusocellulaire.
Microphotograph showing esophageal duplication cyst lined by nonkeratinizing stratified squamous epithelium and double-walled smooth muscle wall.

High power magnification shows malignant large lymphocytes in the lower half with abundant cytoplasm, round nuclei with prominent nucleoli and occasional mitoses. This is consistent with diffuse large B cell lymphoma. Seen in the upper half of the figure are small lymphoid cell with a narrow rim of clear cytoplasm and condense chromatin. This is consistent with MALT lymphoma.

Histopathological aspects of interdigitating dendritic cell sarcoma revealing a growth pattern by hematoxylin and eosin staining. Spindle-shaped cells make up the entire lesion, with small lymphocytes.

A well-circumscribed area of high grade angiosarcoma. The tumor cells are large and polygonal with abundant cytoplasm, which corresponds to the epithelioid variant. The nuclei are very atypical and pleomorphic, with large nucleoli and irregular nuclear outlines; abnormal mitoses are present. The abundant pigment and prominent nucleoli led to the consideration of a melanoma; however, melanoma markers were negative, and the pigment is hemosiderin.

Anaplastic Meningioma, Grade 3, showing sarcoma-like morphology and frequent mitoses.

HE stain showing a sclerosing-variant papillary thyroid carcinoma as a well-defined nodular mass. HE high power field image of tumor cells within the mass.

20× power H&E stain jaw biopsy showing a diffuse infiltrate of medium to large lymphoid cells that are monomorphic against a heavy background of scattered macrophages with a'starry sky' pattern, consistent with Burkitt's lymphoma.

Representative histology of the tumors shows an intimate association of neoplastic disorganized, fairly primitive trabeculae with the tumor cells, which either present as a lace-like pattern or as broad sheets. The arrows indicate mitosis, and the asterisk indicates neoplastic osteoid. Relapsed primary osteosarcoma at the time of diagnosis. The xenograft tumor closely resembles the relapsed primary, including the production of neoplastic bone. Note the abundant mitotic tumor cells.
Oropahryngeal angiosarcoma with ulceration of the mucosae. Vascular proliferation on standard coloration with Hemalun Eosine Safron.
Monocytic sarcoma in the gallbladder.

The histopathologic finding of femur bone shows a bone lesion composed of metastatic adenocarcinoma, similar to the carcinoma component of the uterus cancer. This is quite different from the lung lesion.
Histopathology showing tumor cells of pheochromocytoma.
Encapsulated papillary thyroid carcinoma measuring 6 mm in diameter.

Peritoneal fluid with deciduoid mesothelioma. Enlarged malignant cells with a binucleate form, and glassy cytoplasm. Scattered smaller atypical mesothelial cells are present in the background. [PAP stain, 40X.] (Courtesy of Dr Bernard Naylor.)
A histological examination revealed glioblastoma multiforme without any microorganism identified.
Ulceration showing the absence of intact epidermis overlying primary invasive melanoma, associated with serum crust and fibrinous exudate.

Pathology imaging from right middle lung bronchial biopsy showing lepidic adenocarcinoma with growth along intact alveolar septae. Adenocarcinoma is indicated by a big arrow and free floating tumor cells are indicated by a little arrow.
Pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma with infiltrating atypical tubular and gland structures.
Follicular T-cell lymphoma. Aggregations of intermediate-sized neoplastic cells with round nuclei and pale cytoplasm are recognized inside the follicles.

The sarcoma shows very high cellularity with a sheet-like growth pattern, multinucleated giant cells, and necrosis. On higher magnification, there are high-grade pleomorphic tumor cells and multiple mitotic figures with areas of heterologous osteosarcomatous differentiation. Chemotherapy effect, characterized by cell death and hyalinization, was present in ~ 60% of the tumor.

The sarcoma shows very high cellularity with a sheet-like growth pattern, multinucleated giant cells, and necrosis. On higher magnification, there are high-grade pleomorphic tumor cells and multiple mitotic figures with areas of heterologous osteosarcomatous differentiation. Chemotherapy effect, characterized by cell death and hyalinization, was present in ~ 60% of the tumor.

Peripheral blood smear showing a flower cell, which is a lymphocyte with a petal-shaped nucleus. Flower cells may be seen in the setting of HTLV-1 infection or HTLV-1-associated T cell leukemia/lymphoma.

Combined hepatocellular-cholangiocarcinoma with stem cell features, cholangiocellular subtype. Small hyperchromatic tumor cells with high nuclear to cytoplasmic ratio present within dense fibrous stroma.

This image shows an atypical leiomyoma due to diffuse cytologic atypia of the symplastic type/bizarre atypia. There is no evidence of coagulative necrosis and no increased mitotic activity, and this did not meet the criteria for leiomyosarcoma.

Keratin-positive stromal cells are confined within the elastic lamina of the peritoneal membrane. Adenocarcinoma of the colon invades the peritoneal membrane with uneven fraying of the elastic fibers of the elastic lamina.

Numerous eosinophils are found in the epithelium of this esophageal biopsy. The basal zone is markedly expanded. Lamina propria fibers appear thickened near the epithelium, but not at the deep margin. Eosinophils are also present in the lamina propria.

46-year-old female with spindle-cell sarcoma of the heart. The histological specimens show typical characteristics of a small cell osteosarcoma. The tumor comprises fields of many small purple cells. The cortex is disrupted totally by the atypical cells. The tumor is situated in and around the cortex of the phalanx. The cells infiltrate the surrounding soft tissue, where there is osteoid formation by the tumor cells. This feature defines this tumor as being an osteosarcoma. The osteoid formation was in a lamellar fashion. Within the formed osteoid the same atypical cells are present.

Adenosquamous carcinoma of the pancreas in a resection material. Squamous nests are noted. The glandular counterpart shows typical features of pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma.
Photomicrograph of biopsy taken from scapular swelling showing ovoid shaped dark cells, giving a sarcomatous picture.
Adrenocortical carcinoma (potentially arising from an adenoma), typical necrosis.
Histologic features of the esophageal mass and soft tissue mass show moderately differentiated neoplastic glands with osteoblastic activity, but lacking bone marrow elements.
A case of epithelioid glioblastoma composed of epithelioid discohesive cells with eosinophilic round cytoplasm and nuclei with distinct eccentrically nucleoli.
Pathological features of the local lesions show local recurrence without sarcomatous change using Hematoxylin and eosin stain.

Pleomorphic liposarcoma shows sheets of large pleomorphic tumor cells resembling undifferentiated pleomorphic sarcoma. Higher magnification of pleomorphic liposarcoma shows a large multivacuolated lipoblast; identification of these cells is indispensable for the diagnosis.
Pulmonary adenocarcinoma. HE staining.
Hematoxylin and eosin staining of right breast tissues indicated the presence of invasive lobular carcinoma. Small and round cancer cells infiltrated the breast tissue.
Zone of collision between the gastric stromal tumor and the pancreatic adenocarcinoma.
Chondrosarcoma section showing invasion of bone by chondrocytes.
Histologic features of glioblastoma with PNET-like components.

Follicular dendritic cell sarcoma. The neoplastic cells show admixed spindled to ovoid nuclei with indistinct cytoplasmic borders, mitosis, and mild pleomorphism. Rare small lymphocytes are seen in the background.
Biopsy results demonstrated spindle cell sarcoma with bleeding and necrosis.
Hematoxylin and eosin staining shows a cluster of viable tumor cells in a brain metastasis of lung adenocarcinoma.
Biopsy samples of the rectum show moderately differentiated tubular adenocarcinoma.
B-lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma with absolute eosinophilia, showing increased circulating blasts and mature eosinophils.
A) Cyst involving the esophageal submucosal ducts. B) High power image of the cyst lining epithelium composed of bland cuboidal to columnar cells.
Pulmonary adenocarcinoma in fibrotic lung parenchyma.
Hematoxylin and eosin-stained histologic sections showing the intimate association of the lymphoma cells with the individual striated muscle fibers in the gluteal muscle biopsy.
Part of chondrosarcoma stained with hematoxylin and eosin.
Pathological findings of hepatocellular carcinoma cells by hepatic resection.
High-power view of the cells shows nuclei with features of papillary thyroid carcinoma.
63-year-old man with angiosarcoma of the scalp shows pleomorphic endothelial cells.
Histological findings. Epithelioid features of round-to-polygonal or rhabdoid cells with cellular atypia resembling malignant melanoma (hematoxylin-eosin, ×400).

Histology of the resected nodule in the right lower lobe showing poorly differentiated squamous cell carcinoma. Cancer cells developed and replaced the honeycomb lungs. Polygonal cells, with an oval to irregular heterozygous nucleus, formed solid vesicular nests.
Representative tumor sections from the patient show geographic necrosis, confirming the diagnosis of glioblastoma.
Extensive perineural invasion of well differentiated pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma.

A 64-year-old woman with lung adenocarcinoma, who had new metastases on pleural and evaluated as PMD according to PERCIST after two doses sintilimab treatment. Pleural biopsy confirmed this patient had metastases on pleural.
Renal clear cell carcinoma, Fuhrman's grade I-II.

This image depicts numerous mitotic figures at a rate of 7–12/high power fields, moderate cytologic atypia, and some atypical mitotic figures, diagnostic of vaginal leiomyosarcoma of low to intermediate nuclear grade. The vaginal material shows greater hypercellularity compared to the prior and a high mitotic rate but no coagulative necrosis.
Sparse and isolated groups of lymphocytes are present between melanoma cells.
Solid nests of metastatic medullary thyroid cancer in a lymph node.
Secondary malignant GCTB developed in a 38-year-old male after 14 years of irradiation of primary tumour, showing overt sarcomatous atypia.

56-year-old male with ‘wet’ appearance of epithelioid peritoneal mesothelioma. Photomicrograph demonstrates pleomorphic sheets of epithelioid cells with large nuclei, prominent nucleoli, and eosinophilic cytoplasm. A few psammoma bodies are visible.
A low-grade chondrosarcoma in the upper right is juxtaposed with a high-grade spindle cell sarcoma in the lower left consistent with a dedifferentiated chondrosarcoma.
Light Microscopic Appearance of Ewing’s Sarcoma demonstrating areas with large nuclei and many prominent mitotic figures.
Meningothelial-like whorls and metaplastic bone formation in a retroperitoneal dedifferentiated liposarcoma.
Histologic sections of the tumor showing presence of rhabdomyoblasts, confirming the diagnosis of rhabdomyosarcoma.
Diffuse large B cell lymphoma of the elderly.
Histology slide demonstrating well-differentiated liposarcoma.
Histologic features of the chondrosarcomatous and pleomorphic cell components.
Histomorphological features of the Kaposi sarcoma. This tumor is also composed of spindle cell-forming slit-like spaces filled with erythrocytes. Tumor cells have slight atypia and no pleomorphism.
Hematoxylin and eosin stain of gastroesophageal junction showing a thickened muscularis propria.
Paired cytological sample and surgical sample of pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma (PDAC) with Hematoxylin and Eosin stain in surgical sample.
Barrett esophagus-associated dysplasia, indefinite for dysplasia.
Liver: high power view of hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) with a distinct granular cytoplasmic staining.

Histological features of carcinosarcoma in the enterectomy specimen. Tumor involving the enteric serosa and focally invading the outer muscle layer of the intestinal wall. Here the tumor consists predominantly of the mesenchymal component (undifferentiated sarcoma).
HE stains of the specimen demonstrating nodules of lymphocytes surrounded by fibrous bands, typical of classical Hodgkin lymphoma, nodular sclerosis variant.
100x angiosarcoma H&E demonstrating tumor with high cellularity and prominent vascular network.

Microscopic view of the tumor in the seminal vesicle: The tumor cells were arranged in trabecular and solid nests, which was compatible with the original small bowel adenocarcinoma. 100 × magnification.
A representative sample of human glioblastoma showing the characteristic, irregularly shaped microvascular proliferation.
Right testicular mixed germ cell tumor associated with a left testicular seminoma.
Malignant CD10+ cells present, consistent with known diffuse large B-cell lymphoma (left: thin prep slide, right: cell block)
The microscopic examination of radical prostatectomy showed moderately to poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma of the prostatic acinar type, Gleason score 9, Grade 5.
The morphological features of one case of high-grade B-cell lymphoma, not otherwise specified (HGBL, NOS).
Specimen of IM in distal esophagus with high density of goblet cells, stroma shows inflammatory infiltration and extravasation.
Pleural biopsy specimen showing polygonal and spindle-shaped cells with hyperchromatic nuclei and osteoid formation along with mitotic figures, suggestive of metastatic osteogenic sarcoma.
Nests and islands of malignant squamous cells admixed with sarcomatous component
Adenocarcinoma stomach showing glands lined by cells having pleomorphic vesicular nuclei with prominent nucleoli.
