Photomicrograph of esophageal mucosal biopsy demonstrated sloughing in the mucosa.
Microscopy of the lateral neck mass showing cells with enlarged nuclei, intranuclear cytoplasmic inclusions, nuclear grooves, and powdery chromatin, diagnostic for papillary thyroid carcinoma.
The tumor was composed of a Sertoli-Leydig cell and rhabdomyosarcomatous component.

Histopathological appearance of polypoid, moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma taken from the surgically resected transverse colon on hematoxylin and eosin staining. Tumor cells invading the muscularis propria.
Tumor cell at dermo–epidermal junction and organized in nests in the superficial dermis. The tumor is not ulcerated. Cutaneous superficial spreading melanoma.
Histological findings typical of cholangiocarcinoma.
Parathyroid carcinoma. Negative parafibromin staining of neoplastic cells. Arrow indicates parafibromin-positive vascular endothelial cells that serve as an internal positive control.

Photomicrographs showing pleomorphism in leiomyosarcoma. Cells exhibiting extreme degree of pleomorphism and occasional multinucleation resembling pleomorphic undifferentiated sarcoma/ malignant fibrous histiocytoma (H&E stain).

Myxofibrosarcoma revealing elongated, curvilinear, thin-walled blood
vessel.
Intermediate power view of the tumour reflecting the spindled, sarcomatoid component.
Extraskeletal myxoid chondrosarcoma shows a lace-like architecture due to the myxoid matrix. There are monomorphic epitheloid and spindle cells with an obvious eosinophilic cytoplasm.
Photomicrograph of lung lesion showing pulmonary squamous cell carcinoma.
Histopathologic findings of acral lentiginous melanoma show invading mixed cell types of heavily pigmented epithelioid and spindle cells.

b ) The tumor is indicative of glioblastoma by the presence of necrosis and microvascular proliferation.  c,  d ) Tumor cells are positive for IDH-1 (H09), R132H-mutant, and retained expression of ATRX.
Histological evaluation of pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma using H&E staining.
Intraosseous fibrosarcoma, left tarso-metatarsal bone, composed of spindle-shaped neoplastic cells embedded in abundant amounts of collagen fibers.
Hodgkin’s lymphoma with atypical mononuclear cells and bi-nucleate cells.
Photomicrograph demonstrating a mixed-type diffuse mesothelioma with poorly differentiated epithelial and spindle cells.
Lymphomatoid granulomatosis showing angiocentric proliferation of atypical lymphoid cells associated with Epstein-Barr virus.
Transverse section of esophagus showing lamina propria, submucosa, blood vessel, inner circular muscle, and outer longitudinal muscle. Arrows indicate tubular glands.
Moderately differentiated pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma.
The histological examination confirmed the diagnosis of pituitary lymphoma. Figures show infiltrative large-sized lymphocytes with occasional mitotic activity.
Microscopic image of the DLBCL showing the tumor cells between the crypts in the lamina propria. Hematoxylin and eosin (H&E) staining was used on the tissue.
Biopsied section of the gastric tumor stained with hematoxylin–eosin (HE), which was pathologically diagnosed as poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma.
Photomicrographs of inflammatory myofibroblastic tumour with sarcomatous transformation. Spindle cells display moderate hyperchromasia and pleomorphism in initial biopsy.
Papillary thyroid carcinoma (PTC) showing nuclear features.
Subsequent wide excision with satellite/in transit metastasis of plasmacytoid melanoma.
H and E section of EUS-guided pancreatic biopsy showing invasive adenocarcinoma, moderately differentiated, associated with desmoplastic stroma and tumor necrosis.
Photomicrograph of fine needle aspiration cytology of the right lung lesion showing adenocarcinoma.
Nodular Kaposi sarcoma showing a peripheral component reminiscent of a cavernous hemangioma.
Histological findings (H&E stain) in poorly differentiated thyroid cancer showing extensive necrosis.
Scalp angiosarcoma. Pleomorphic malignant cells forming inter-anastomosing vascular channels beneath the epidermis (hematoxylin and eosin; original magnification ×200)
Primary cardiac undifferentiated pleomorphic sarcoma with a hypocellular lesion in a myxoid background.
Malignant small round cell tumor (Ewing's sarcoma). Imprint smear showing sheets of small round to oval tumor cells showing moderate atypia. Cytoplasm is vacuolated (H&E, X400).
Illustration of the histological pictures of renal cell carcinomas in our series, showing a classical picture of clear cell carcinoma, with mostly clear cell tumour cells.
Photomicrograph of parosteal osteosarcoma showing mature-appearing bone without osteoblastic rimming, surrounded by a hypercellular fibroblastic stroma with moderate cytologic atypia.

Microscopic view of the lymph node reveals a small number of metastatic papillary thyroid carcinomas present at the periphery of chronic granulomatous inflammation with caseous necrosis. Lymph node structures around metastatic papillary thyroid carcinoma with psammoma bodies are preserved.
Non-small cell lung carcinomas favor adenocarcinoma: Morphology not discernible but tumor cells are strongly and diffusely positive for thyroid transcription factor-1.

The bone marrow biopsy shows normocellular marrow with diffuse infiltration of neoplastic lymphoid cells and an increase of histiocytes with occasional hemophagocytosis, indicating the presence of B-cell lymphoma associated with hemophagocytic histiocytosis.
The pathologic image of Case 1 shows papillary thyroid carcinoma (PTC) stained with hematoxylin and eosin.
Primary lung adenocarcinoma is indicated by red arrow, as compared with the normal alveolar epithelium (seen in black arrow).
Biopsy of the tumor showed a typical histology of myxofibrosarcoma. The histological grade was determined as grade 1.
Pathological images of the lesion showing gliosarcoma with a biphasic tissue pattern displaying gliomatous and mesenchymal differentiation.
Ductal adenocarcinoma of the prostate with pseudoendometrioid growth pattern, focally reminiscent of secreting endometrium.
Histological studies before initiating esomeprazole treatment showed eosinophilic infiltration in the stratified squamous layer of the mid esophagus.
Pathology of the parathyroid carcinoma.

Fatal Measles pneumonia (Hecht pneumonia) in a child under treatment for non-Hodgkin lymphoma. The arrows show multinucleated giant cells (Warthin-Finkeldey cells), with nuclear and cytoplasmic eosinophilic inclusions.

Photomicrograph of post-treatment tumor on H&E stain shows differentiated rhabdomyomatous cells with abundant cytoplasm and frequent apoptotic (non-viable) forms in an abundant largely acellular fibroblastic matrix. No undifferentiated or poorly differentiated rhabdomyosarcoma cells were identified throughout the tissue sections.

Hepatocellular carcinoma cells characterized by large anaplastic carcinoma cells with eosinophilic cytoplasm, large hyperchromatic nuclei, and prominent nucleoli. The normal trabecular structure of the liver is distorted.
Bone marrow involvement by T-cell lymphoma with paratrabecular and interstitial lymphoid aggregates.
H and E stain of primary colon tumor showing poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma of the colon.
Histological findings of the surgical specimen of the left breast tumor show invasive lobular carcinoma.

Photomicrograph of a transverse section through the esophagus showing keratinized epithelium, mucosa, muscularis mucosa, submucosa, lymphocyte infiltration, tunica muscularis, inner circular layer, and outer longitudinal layer.

Superficial spreading melanoma on the abdomen of an 82-year-old man. The presence of a heavy lymphohistiocytic infiltrate with melanophages and acanthosis of the epidermis and heavily pigmented atypical nests and melanocytes in the epidermis are responsible for the structureless blue pigmentation.
H&E section of the 4.5 cm left renal mass showing a papillary renal cell carcinoma with fibrovascular cores filling a cystic space and composed of eosinophilic cytoplasm.

Histology appearance of parathyroid carcinoma in transition with papillary thyroid carcinoma removed from the left thyroid lobe. The neoplastic cells are represented by the monomorphic cellular proliferation with discrete atypia and mitosis.

An increased number of M2 macrophages was independently associated with lymph node metastasis (LNM) development in patients with concomitant Hashimoto thyroiditis. A high number of M2 macrophages in papillary thyroid carcinoma with LNM.
Cytological smear from lung tumor showing dysplastic cells in an inflammatory background suggestive of squamous cell carcinoma.
Case of grade 1 hepatocellular carcinoma with a thick capsule and adjacent reactive hepatic tissue.
Muqueuse laryngée infiltrée par un processus lymphomateux.
Breast histology: invasive ductal carcinoma.
Adrenocortical carcinosarcoma histological appearance showing a sarcomatous component composed of uniform spindle cells arranged in a fascicular pattern.
Measurement of width of ulceration (mm) in cutaneous melanoma.
Microscopic section of the prostate revealing adenocarcinoma with Gleason score 4 + 5 on the diagnostic biopsy on hematoxylin‐eosin staining.

Histologic appearance of lentigo maligna (LM) compared to non-lentigo maligna melanoma in situ. The peripheral edge of LM is poorly defined histologically, making complete histologic excision difficult.
Photomicrograph showing dense infiltration of melanoma cells with pigment at places. Atypical cells have descended deep into the reticular dermis.

Haematoxylin and Eosin stained sections of rare type colorectal carcinomas showing serrated adenocarcinoma with epithelial serrations or tufts, abundant eosinophilic or clear cytoplasm, vesicular basal nuclei with preserved polarity.
Pleural biopsy with Video assisted thoracic surgery revealing non-small cell adenocarcinoma of lung.
Cystic Warthin's tumor epithelium surrounded by lymphoma next to normal salivary gland tissue.
Papillary thyroid carcinoma with characteristic nuclear features (nuclear crowding, overlapping, clearing, membrane irregularities, and inclusions).
8 prostate adenocarcinoma in pathological examination of the first TUR-P material.

Histopathological findings of the endoscopic submucosal dissection-resected specimen show gastric adenocarcinoma of fundic gland type (GA-FG) partially invading the submucosa layer up to 450 μm, mainly located in the deep layer of the lamina propria mucosae. Enlarged ducts of the heterotopic gastric glands are observed just under the submucosal lesion of the GA-FG. The submucosal lesion has a poor stromal reaction.

Imprint smear of Ewing's sarcoma shows scattered population of malignant round tumor cells with larger cells having pale stained nuclei and smaller cells having darkly stained nuclei. The cytoplasm is vacuolated. MGG stain, ×400.
Rhabdomyosarcomatous differentiation.
Section of the rectal mass showing tumor cells floating in pools of mucin consistent with mucinous adenocarcinoma.
Pathological finding of metastatic lesion by hematoxylin and eosin staining: poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma originating from the stomach infiltrated the submucosa of the small intestine.

Rectal mass biopsy showing superficial mucosal tissue lined by highly atypical dysplastic/neoplastic glandular epithelial cells with nuclear pleomorphism, prominent nucleoli, and frequent mitotic figures. This is consistent with at least intramucosal adenocarcinoma. Invasive growth cannot be excluded.

Histopathological findings showing the feature of glioblastoma composed of poorly differentiated pleomorphic tumor cells with marked nuclear atypia and brisk mitotic activity and focal necrosis with pseudopalisading.
Histopathologic examination shows small foci of residual and scant melanoma cells.
Histology of chronic pancreatitis, pancreatic adenocarcinoma, and normal pancreas. Mild chronic pancreatitis.
Medullary thyroid carcinoma showing a tumor capsule. The neoplastic cells are demarcated from the normal thyroid parenchyma by a fibrous capsule.
Stained sample of bone metastasis of lung adenocarcinoma.
Hematoxylin and eosin staining of a glioblastoma multiforme shows the interface between tumor cells and the area of necrosis. The necrotic area shows greatly reduced nuclear staining.
Arterial leiomyosarcoma originating from the superior mesenteric artery; notice the nuclear pleomorphism, mitotic figures, and necrotic areas typical of a leiomyosarcoma.

Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma (DLBCL) in the pleural cavity with aggregates of large atypical lymphocytes having irregular nuclei with uneven chromatin and small to large nucleoli. Some cells show multilobulated nuclei. Mitosis and apoptotic bodies are conspicuous.
Histological finding of the tumor shows pheochromocytes.
The colon mass adenocarcinoma focus showed confluent cribiform glands with minor mucinous differentiation.
Malignant Melanoma with Pagetoid Distribution of Melanoma Cells and Consumption of Epidermis in Right Side of the Field (H&E, magnification × 20)

Histology of the primary endometrial cancer and the ileum recurrence shows endometrioid adenocarcinoma metastasizing to the ileum. The tumor invades the bowel mucosa and the subserous connective adipose tissue using hematoxylin–eosin staining.
Adenocarcinoma colon showing malignant cells with neutral mucins using periodic acid Schiff (PAS).
Histology types of thyroid cancer identified in this study, including follicular variant PTC.
Mastectomy specimen with invasive ductal carcinoma. Duct-like structures and nests are seen invading the breast stroma and fat.
Diffuse cellular swelling and presence of intrahepatocytic pigment deposits with melanomacrophage centres (MMC).
Multiple histopathological grades can be seen in the same glioblastoma tumor, with the upper fragments representing lower grade and the bottom part depicting a fully developed GBM.
Colon hepatic flexure tumor biopsy showing moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma.
A case of pulmonary adenocarcinoma, solid type.
The histopathological figure of RCC with sarcomatoid differentiation, showing chRCC together with fibrosarcomatoid cells using H&E stain.
Squamous cell carcinoma of the hypopharynx showing increased mitotic figures and nuclear atypia.
Photomicrograph showing B-cell lymphoma cells in the intestinal mucosa & submucosa.
Radiation-induced glioblastoma multiforme demonstrating increased cellularity with marked nuclear atypia, necrosis, and vascular endothelialization.
Histopathologic features of cutaneous melanoma. Nodular melanoma reveals deep nodular vertical growth of melanoma cells in the dermis without radial growth phase.

Typical morphological features of mesenchymal chondrosarcomas showing a biphasic pattern of cartilage islands distributed among spindle cells, mainly located in the periphery. Chondrocytes showed moderate nuclear atypia, while spindle cells exhibited nuclear hyperchromatism and pleomorphism.
Low-grade endometrial carcinoma with well-preserved glandular architecture.
Pigment granules are observed in the smooth muscles of the artery in the adventitia of the esophagus.
Endometrial carcinoma in liquid-based cytology preparation.
Histomorphological patterns in colorectal adenocarcinomas with conspicuous psammomatous calcification in cases of papillary serous cyst adenocarcinomas of the ovary.
Hematoxylin & eosin stain showing lymphoma infiltration of the bone marrow and hemophagocytosis.
Hematoxylin and eosin stain showing endobronchial invasion of mucoepidermoid carcinoma.
Primary adenocarcinoma of the lung.

Histologic features of primary tumor showing a mixed cell morphology with anaplastic epithelioid and spindle malignant melanoma cells invading the ciliary body. Choroidal and iris involvement were also present.
Histological findings of the surgical lung resection specimens show three different components: keratinizing squamous cell carcinoma.

Hematoxylin and eosin (H&E) staining showed a packed round cell pattern with a striking uniformity. The individual cells had a small round to ovoid nucleus with fine powdery chromatin and few mitotic nucleoli. The cytoplasm was ill-defined and scanty. The histological diagnosis was Ewing’s sarcoma.
Microscopic finding shows a bizarre, large nucleus suggesting liposarcoma rather than lipoma.
Representative area of the mucinous colon adenocarcinoma, depicting malignant epithelium within pools of extracellular mucin (hematoxylin and eosin counterstain, magnification ×100) .
Muscle specimen of the upper part of the esophagus showing dystrophic and necrobiotic changes with focal myocytolysis of muscle fibers.
Hematoxylin and eosin stain of pancreatic duct adenocarcinoma (PDAC) tumor tissues.
Follicles in a trabecular pattern are visible. There are no nuclear features of papillary thyroid carcinoma, squamous metaplasia, or psammoma bodies.
Proximal-type epithelioid sarcoma of perineum. Sheets of large cells with occasional intracytoplasmic inclusions and little intervening stroma.
Histopathologic feature of Burkitt lymphoma.
Burkitt lymphoma, ascitic fluid; monomorphous population of medium-sized cells with prominent cytoplasmic vacuolization. Note the mitoses.
Laryngeal squamous carcinoma was diagnosed from a small biopsy that revealed well-differentiated epithelial tumour with slight atypia and invasive growth into the fibrous stroma.
Myxofibrosarcoma with a myxoid stroma containing spindle or stellate-shaped cells with mildly atypical, hyperchromatic nuclei.
Image showing the pelvic tumor with sarcomatous-component spindled cells.
Invasive lobular carcinoma of the breast with extra cellular mucin shows the classic pattern of lobular carcinoma with single cell infiltration and discohesive pattern.
Histological findings of resected testis showed an adenocarcinoma with moderate differentiation, identical to the primary colon cancer.

Fine needle biopsy specimen obtained from a pancreatic head mass. This lesion was sampled using standard fine needle aspiration technique twice prior to referral to our hospital with insufficient cytology. Rare malignant cells seen infiltrating the fibrous stroma. This was assigned a score of 1 on the cell block. The final diagnosis was pancreatic adenocarcinoma (Hematoxylin and eosin, ×100).
Dysplastic nevus and melanoma in situ.

A, Low-power overview of a monomorphic appearing epithelial proliferation expanding but confined within mammary ducts, with large areas of central necrosis and microcalcifications. There is no invasive carcinoma seen. B, Low-power overview of unremarkable breast parenchyma, where there is no expansion of the terminal duct lobular units and no epithelial proliferation. Also seen is usual ductal hyperplasia, where the terminal duct lobular units are expanded by a benign proliferation containing peripherally located and irregular shaped fenestrated spaces.
Haematoxylin and eosin (H&E) stained slide of pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma exhibiting widespread tumour necrosis.
Type A spindle cell melanoma.

a  In situ adenocarcinoma in video-assisted thoracoscopic lung biopsy (hematoxylin-phloxine-saffron stain, Xobj 4).  Inset , higher magnification highlights malignant nuclei (Xobj 40).  b  Invasive lung adenocarcinoma in a CT-guided biopsy (Hematoxylin-phloxine-saffron stain, Xobj 40).
Photomicrograph of esophageal mucosal biopsy demonstrated lymphocyte aggregation.
H&E-stained sections demonstrating invasive melanoma with a Breslow thickness of 1 mm.
Pathology of the parathyroid carcinoma.

A lesion whose diagnosis was upgraded from gastric low-grade dysplasia to early gastric cancer after endoscopic resection. Histologic features of the resected specimen show moderately differentiated tubular adenocarcinoma arising from a tubular adenoma. The tumor was 0.5 × 0.4 cm in size.

Microscopic appearance of the retroperitoneal follicular dendritic cell sarcoma. The histopathological appearance indicates that the tumor is composed of spindle cells arranged in a storiform pattern and that these spindle cells are admixed with lymphocytes.
Esophageal squamous mucosa with acute and chronic inflammation. No eosinophils are visualized. Neutrophils and lymphocytes are present.
Anatomic pathological examination of the esophagus showing ulceration with presence of multinucleated cells with overlapping nuclei and ground-glass aspect, consistent with herpetic infection.
Pulmonary biopsy of malign neoplasm, which shows a trabecular pattern with the morphologic features of adenocarcinoma.
Microscopic image of the 4th pedicle biopsy showing hyphae and yeast-like cells suggesting Pheohyphomycosis.  Gram-positive hyphae/pseudohyphae can be appreciated.
Gastric metastasis of ovarian serous cystadenocarcinoma.
Morphological descriptions of Kaposi’s sarcoma and Kaposi’s sarcoma-like cases. Microscopic identification by hematoxylin and eosin staining shows patchy areas.
Primary tumor of the resected stomach is composed of well-differentiated adenocarcinoma invading to the muscularis propria.
Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma (DLBCL): the tumor composed of diffuse infiltration of large lymphoid cells in all wall layers of the affected terminal ileum.

4 μm-thick H&E stained section from the cell-block shows a highly cellular sample, with a typical papillary architecture; thyrocytes show irregular, large and clear nuclei. A diagnosis of Papillary Thyroid Carcinoma was formulated.
Stomach biopsy revealed signet ring cells consistent with primary gastric adenocarcinoma.
Pathological features of non‐small cell lung cancer. HE staining of adenocarcinoma.
Biopsied lymph node showing squamous cell carcinoma metastasis from the hypopharynx. The sample is stained with hematoxylin and eosin.
Pathology specimen of cardiac tissue demonstrating lymphocytes infiltrating the cardiac muscle, consistent with cardiac lymphoma.
CK-7 stain of lung adenocarcinoma
Poorly differentiated with signet ring colon adenocarcinoma with extracellular mucin.
Leiomyosarcoma – microscopic image presenting abundant, myxomatous stroma with high level of cellularity and fields of dedifferentiation.
Form and structure that eliminates the normal pattern of lymph node in follicular lymphoma.
Autopsy and pathological results of the patient showed colon adenocarcinoma.
Histological images of sarcoma using hematoxylin and eosin stain show myxoid areas with spindle cells.
Representative images of subtype of lung adenosquamous carcinoma (ASC).

Photomicrographs of pathological hematoxylin and eosin staining of the tissue sections of the resected primary vertebral leiomyosarcoma show a large number of hyperplastic collagen fibers and heteromorphic cells, supporting a diagnosis of polymorphic undifferentiated sarcoma.
Occasional nuclei stain with myogenin, a pattern seen with embryonal rhabdomyosarcoma.
A close-up of the melanoma metastasis in the inguinal lymph node showing both components.
Intestinal fibrosarcoma, dense spindle cells proliferation occurring in the submucosa and extending to the whole intestinal wall.
Capsular invasion and thick fibrous bands in parathyroid carcinoma. Parathyroid carcinoma exhibiting vascular invasion.
The histologic features of well-differentiated liposarcoma (WDL) showing variation in adipocyte size, with the presence of bizarre, hyperchromatic stromal cells. Hematoxylin and eosin staining (H&E).
Photomicrograph of the esophagus showing acute inflammatory infiltration and thrombosed capillary within the granulation tissue.
Histopathology demonstrating pleomorphic glial cells, nuclear atypia, palisading necrosis, mitoses, and vascular proliferation consistent with a diagnosis of glioblastoma.
H&E stained FFPE Undifferentiated pleomorphic sarcoma tissue. The region highlighted by the black circle represents the area from which 1mm cores of tumour tissue were harvested for DNA extraction.
Angiosarcoma lesions exhibited a significantly lower apoptosis index than those of hemangioma.
Invasive ductal carcinoma of the breast showing a mitotic figure.  H&E staining.

Histiocytic sarcoma of spindle cell type. The neoplasm consists of spindle-shaped to angular cells arranged in interlacing bundles. Neoplastic cells have indistinct cell borders and small amounts of eosinophilic cytoplasm. Nuclei are variable in size and oval to elongated in shape. Multinucleated giant cells are often observed.
Epithelioid mesothelioma cells with prominent nucleoli.
Histopathological picture of a well-differentiated liposarcoma.

H&E stained section of affected parathyroid gland (x100).  A parathyroid gland is shown, invaded from a follicular thyroid carcinoma. Malignant cells are large, composed of eosinophilic cytoplasm and round nuclei. These tumor cells form groups or scant follicles with parathyroid cells and lipocytes among them. At the periphery of this picture the parathyroid capsule is shown.
The HRS cells in EBV‐positive mixed cellularity classic Hodgkin lymphoma (CHL) are EBER‐positive (×400).
Microscopic appearance shows neoplastic cells arranged in solid nests, cytologic atypia, and hyperchromatic nuclei suggestive of mesothelioma.
Histopathologic findings of esophageal cryotherapy show necrosis and inflammatory reaction involving the submucosa and extension to the muscularis propria.

Hyperplastic and neoplastic transformations of ectopic endometrial foci. Moderately differentiated G2 endometrioid carcinoma area, coexisting with underlying areas of endometriosis, some with hyperplasia with and without atypia.  Classic histological staining HE. HE: Hematoxylin-Eosin.
Nodular melanoma. Nests and plaques of tumor cells can be observed.
Hematoxylin and eosin staining of the gastric mass showed mixed mucinous and tubular adenocarcinomas.

10.1371/journal.pone.0104983.g003 Figure 3 Immediately immersed smear into 95% ethyl-alcohol fixative. Staining qualities are optimal, with good contrast between nuclear and cytoplasmic elements in pulmonary adenocarcinoma.
The tumor cells lack conventional papillary thyroid carcinoma nuclei and nested or papillary growth pattern.
1 case showed scattered larger lymphocytes, which were not considered sufficient for a diagnosis of high-grade lymphoma.

Pathological findings of the resected SMT show gastric glands extending into the submucosal layer, consistent with GCP. Well-differentiated adenocarcinoma is partially seen within the GCP. There is no involvement of the lateral and deep margins, lymphatic invasion, vascular invasion, or perineural invasion.
Representative hematoxylin and eosin (H&E)-stained sections of post-transplant plasmablastic lymphomas showing numerous tingible body macrophages that impart a 'starry sky' appearance.
Spindle cell rhabdomyosarcoma. Some tumors like this spindle cell lesion contain spindle cells with easily recognizable rhabdomyoblasts with eosinophilic cytoplasm.
Tumor cells consistent with acinar adenocarcinoma, narrowed peripheral airways, and distended subpleural alveolar spaces.
Histological examination revealed diffuse infiltration of the pericardium by epithelioid cells due to the primary malignant pericardial mesothelioma.
Metastatic melanoma to the right buttock. The tumor cells, invading the fat connective tissue, are round with eosinophilic cytoplasm and hyperchromatic nuclei.

The high-grade dedifferentiated component shows mitoses and atypia. The lesion is composed of spindle cells arranged in a fascicular growth pattern, resembling a high-grade undifferentiated pleomorphic sarcoma.
Microscopic sections show metastatic glands of colon adenocarcinoma, infiltrating between thyroid follicles.
Hematoxylin and eosin stain of the lesion revealed neoplastic lymphocytes surrounding and invading myofibrils, which was consistent with non-Hodgkin's lymphoma of skeletal muscles.

Intraoperative SRH images from a 49-year-old male patient, who underwent surgery for a recurrent left frontal glioblastoma. The length of the scale bar in the lower right corner represents 100 μm. d The SRH image of contrast-enhancing cyst wall of the previous resection cavity. e A SRH image of the contrast-enhancing solid tumor nodulus. Infiltration zone was also imaged.
Pancreas adenocarcinoma, moderately differentiated ductal adenocarcinoma.
Biopsy of corpus cavernosum demonstrating poorly differentiated prostatic adenocarcinoma.
Postoperative histopathology of esophageal squamous-cell carcinoma lesion.
Histological appearance of Dermatofibrosarcoma Protuberans. The tumour is located in the dermis and composed of fascicles of spindle tumour cells forming a protruding mass.
Esophageal leiomyoma arising from the muscularis mucosa.
Histopathology of prostatic adenocarcinoma.
Posterior stomach wall tissue with well- and moderate-differentiated ductal adenocarcinoma. Identical morphology with a primary pancreatic tumor. No signs of primary gastric adenocarcinoma.
Histological image of myxosarcoma showing hyperchromatic cells, atypia, and mitosis.
Focus of non-Hodgkin lymphoma showing effacement of the parenchyma by diffuse monotonous lymphoid infiltrate.
Histology of parathyroid adenoma, papillary thyroid carcinoma, and thyroid adenoma. Parathyroid adenoma with hematoxylin and eosin (H&E) staining.
Sclerosing epitheloid fibrosarcoma, demonstrated by cords of bland looking epitheloid cells in a sclerotic stroma. Note pseudoangiomatous shrinkage artefacts.
Left axillary lymph node biopsy showed large atypical B-cells, consistent with involvement by diffuse large B-cell lymphoma.
Showing fascicles of spindle cells with necrosis, marked nuclear pleomorphism, and increased mitoses, features of leiomyosarcoma.

4 μm-thick H&E stained section from the cell-block shows a highly cellular sample, with a typical papillary architecture; thyrocytes show irregular, large and clear nuclei. A diagnosis of Papillary Thyroid Carcinoma was formulated.

Photomicrographs of pathological hematoxylin and eosin staining of the tissue sections of the resected primary vertebral leiomyosarcoma show a large number of hyperplastic collagen fibers and heteromorphic cells, supporting a diagnosis of polymorphic undifferentiated sarcoma.
Cholangiocarcinoma with glandular clusters of cuboidal cells.

Fine-needle aspiration cytology is consistent with B-cell lymphoma. The cells are discohesive, and the chromatin is fine. Many nuclei appear to have little or no cytoplasm. A few lymphoglandular bodies are in the background.
Lymphoma. Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma with large atypical discohesive cells and distinct nucleoli.
Squamous epithelial lining of esophagus with medium-to-large sized neoplastic cells infiltrated beneath the epithelium.
Examples of ductal adenocarcinoma of the prostate.

Cytology of the pre-scapular lymph node in the lymphoma patient shows a monomorphic population of lymphoblasts with round to slightly irregular nuclei in a scant amount of circumferential basophilic cytoplasm. The nuclei contain large nucleoli. Lymphoglandular bodies are present in the background.
Sarcomatous appearance of cells adjoining bony trabeculae noticed in the peripheral aspect of the lesion.
Microphotograph of a mucoepidermoid carcinoma of the lung.  To view the virtual slide for this image, please see here:  http://eu-demo-dih.slidepath.com/dih/webViewer.php?snapshotId=1294305419.
Histopathology of the rectal mass showed well-differentiated adenocarcinoma.
Angiosarcoma. Large polygonal cells are dispersed as single forms and in a large 3-dimensional cluster. No vasoformative features are present which is often the case for this sarcoma.

Histology slide showing a region of more traditional glioblastoma in the upper left aspect exhibiting greater hypercellularity and epithelioid cytology. This region shows a relatively abrupt transition to a more paucicellular spindle cell proliferation in the lower right, consistent with gliosarcoma.
45-year-old man with pathologically proven myxoid/round cell liposarcoma. Photomicrograph demonstrates undifferentiated round cell morphology with myxoid component.
Hematoxylin- and eosin-stained section of tissue from the initial surgical excision shows a high-grade spindle-cell sarcoma with nuclear pleomorphism.
Photomicrograph of the esophagus showing invasive Candida spp. from mucosal ulcer and submucosa.
Angiosarcoma undifferentiated. Note the presence of anarchic vascular elements not very differentiated with mitoses.
Histological finding of the surgical specimen shows large neoplastic cells with vacuolated cytoplasm mixed with squamous and sarcomatoid differentiation.

Histopathology features of the thyroid tumor show papillae lined with columnar epithelium with round to oval nuclei and relatively clear chromatins, indicating conventional-type papillary thyroid carcinoma.
Metastatic malignant mesothelioma to lymph node. The tumor cells are large and polygonal with eosinophilic cytoplasm. They have prominent nucleoli and display numerous mitoses (H&E, 40×).
Numerous lipoblasts are rarely observed in well-differentiated liposarcoma, and they can be completely absent.
Image showing the diffuse infiltrate of large lymphoma cells with admixed histiocytes, mitosis, and karyorrhexis debris.
Type 2 endometrial carcinoma: clear cell carcinoma of the endometrium. Tumor with tubuloglandular architecture lined by clear cells with intraluminal secretions.

Histologic features of the esophageal mass and soft tissue mass showed a well-circumscribed mass of neoplastic glands closely associated with osteoblastic activity within skeletal muscle and fibrosis.
Medullary thyroid carcinoma featuring groups of cells with polygonal to elongated cytoplasms and round-to-oval nuclei with indistinct nucleoli. Note the amyloid deposition in the stroma.
The pelvic resection specimen of dedifferentiated chondrosarcoma demonstrated low-grade component abruptly juxtaposed to high-grade dedifferentiated component.
Histologic features of benign prostate gland, high grade PIN, adenocarcinoma and SCNC. High grade PIN showing malignant luminal cells without invasion of the stroma.
Typical pathological images of papillary thyroid carcinoma revealing calcifications and fibrosis separated by cancer tissues.

Light microscopic examination of recurrent tumor shows centrocyte-like cells and plasmacytoid differentiation in the recurrent MALT lymphoma. Plasmacytoid differentiation was more prevalent in the recurrent tumor than in the primary tumor.
Histology of the esophagus before treatment shows greater than 80 eosinophils per high-power field in the proximal esophagus, indicated by blue arrows.
Interface between areas of classical clear-cell carcinoma and its sarcomatoid component.
Sarcomatoid differentiation.

Photomicrograph of the undifferentiated cardiac intimal sarcoma showing areas of coagulative necrosis without any organoid pattern. The high power view shows tumor cells with oval to spindle shaped, hyperchromatic or vesicular nuclei and frequent mitoses.
Conventional osteosarcoma within a preexisting histological confirmed giant cell tumour, suggesting primary malignant transformation.
Histopathological features of papillary thyroid carcinoma with spindle cell metaplasia. Entrapped tumour cells within the nodule exhibiting features consistent with classical PTC are also observed.

Mature teratoma adjacent to papillary thyroid carcinoma arising in a struma ovarii. The major bulk of the papillary thyroid carcinoma can be seen on the right side. The benign teratomatous tissue shows dense stroma with multiple, relatively well-circumscribed sebaceous glands and overlying stratified epithelium. Benign-looking thyroid follicular tissue with eosinophilic colloid and flattened epithelial lining can also be seen.
Primary mediastinal large B-cell lymphoma.
Pheochromocytoma—cells with moderate nuclear pleomorphism, prominent nucleoli, and abundant granular cytoplasm that form irregular nests.
Pancreatic adenocarcinoma.
Colon tumor. Microscopically, the tumor is an adenocarcinoma with papillary and glandular architectures.

Medullary thyroid carcinoma showing highly vascularized tumor with trabecular pattern of growth and deposition of amyloid.

Histopathologic study of stomach biopsy specimen showing irregular tubular structures, pluristratification, multiple lumens, and reduced stroma of intestinal-type adenocarcinoma.

Lung adenocarcinoma infiltrating the transverse colon.
Deep penetrating nevus–like melanoma showing a compound, asymmetric melanocytic proliferation.

Light-microscopic images of liver from the early HBV-related HCC groups depicting details of the liver microstructure, including growth patterns of hepatocellular carcinoma with HBV infection, trabecular pattern with pseudoglandular growth pattern, and giant cell formation.

Midesophageal biopsies revealing significant eosinophilia of the midesophagus, with 80 eosinophils per high-power field and associated parakeratosis consistent with eosinophilic esophagitis.

Pathological findings of resected tumor show a mixed tumor consisting of rhabdomyosarcoma.

Invasive melanoma.

Carcinosarcoma shows an association of malignant epithelial and mesenchymal components. The latter is composed of large, abnormal cells with numerous mitoses (arrows) (H&E, objective 40x).

Esophageal mucosa with intestinal metaplasia. Columnar epithelium-forming glands with interspersed goblet cells are present. A chronic inflammatory infiltrate is present in the lamina propria. Histopathology slides showing moderate-to-poorly differentiated gastric adenocarcinoma with gastric mucosa and ulceration, and cells arranged in a glandular pattern, signet ring cells, and pools of mucin.

Histopathological analysis of the mediastinal lymphadenopathy revealed a moderately to poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma. The tumor cells with round nuclei, eosinophilic cytoplasm, and distinct cell borders are arranged in sheets and show alveolar or solid growth pattern with some glandular cavity. A large number of tumor cells have mucinous cytoplasm. The histologic examination of the primary lesion, diagnosed as a well-differentiated adenocarcinoma, is inconsistent with the recurrent lesion. However, inconsistent histological analysis between metastatic and primary tumors often occurs. The primary lesion also contains a sheet-like structure, so there is some consistency in diagnosis of this lesion as a recurrence.
Histopathology of ovarian low-grade and high-grade serous carcinoma shows uniform nuclei and infrequent mitotic figures, with low nuclear atypia of well-differentiated tumors.
Photomicrographs of the hepatic tumor show neoplastic cells in nested structures mimicking a hepatocellular carcinoma using Hematoxylin & Eosin staining.
Fat overlying the tumour demonstrating papillary renal cell carcinoma seeding along the previous percutaneous biopsy tract.

Leiomyoma shows a spindle cell proliferation. The lesion is hypocellular. Leiomyosarcoma is composed of epithelioid cells with high nuclear-cytoplasmic ratio. Compared to leiomyoma, it is highly cellular with frequent mitosis.

43-year-old female, abdomen–Spitz melanoma; asymmetric melanocytic proliferation composed of enlarged, nodular or sheet-like aggregates of melanocytes and diminished maturation; spindle and epithelioid melanocytes show nuclear enlargement, pleomorphism, thickening and irregularity of nuclear membranes, and prominent nucleoli.

Pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma. The ducts show features of malignancy including cytologic atypia and incomplete gland formation with loss of lobular architecture, in a prominent desmoplastic stroma (hematoxylin & eosin, 130 ×, scale 250 μm).

Hemithyroidectomy specimen grossly revealed a totally encapsulated 3 cm sized round nodule in the right lobe and histologically demonstrated invasive encapsulated follicular variant papillary thyroid carcinoma with definite capsular invasion.
Tumor cell migration in a mucinous adenocarcinoma, with larger-cell complexes along the alveolar walls, still using the supply by the alveolar septa.

Histological examination of a lung biopsy specimen showing pleomorphic giant tumor cells with poor cohesiveness. No apparent differentiation toward adenocarcinoma, squamous cell carcinoma, or neuroendocrine carcinoma was seen.
Metastatic follicular thyroid carcinoma (FTC) in the femur.
Infiltration of esophageal epithelium from a high grade/poorly cohesive-poorly differentiated large-cell carcinoma.
Nodular melanoma.
Colonic adenocarcinoma colliding with granulosa cell tumor showing microfollicular pattern.
Burkitt lymphoma, ascitic fluid; monomorphous population of medium-sized cells with prominent cytoplasmic vacuolization.

Lymph node metastases of papillary serous renal cell carcinoma.
Struma ovarii with papillary thyroid carcinoma.

Histologic appearance of acute esophageal necrosis or black esophagus: hematoxylin and eosin (H&E) staining showing necrotic debris, absence of epithelium, granulation tissue, and robust leukocyte infiltrates.
Poorly differentiated lung adenocarcinoma (LUAD) with focal areas of glandular formation and focal necrosis.

Papillary thyroid carcinoma H&E stain showing characteristic papillary architecture, characteristic nuclear features with ground class chromatin, nuclear grooving, nuclear crowding, nuclear overlapping, and intranuclear cytoplasmic pseudo-inclusions.
Photomicrograph showing well-differentiated liposarcomas composed of fat cells of a variety of sizes and shapes.
A section of the uterine fundus showing a small endometrial carcinoma of elevated type arising from the tubal recess (cornu) with associated endometrial complex hyperplasia adjacent to the cancer.

Pathological examination of the transbronchial lung cryobiopsy specimen stained with hematoxylin and eosin shows atypical cells with anisonucleosis in a micropapillary pattern consistent with adenocarcinoma.
Moderately differentiated colonic adenocarcinoma with hematoxylin-eosin staining.
Secondary glioblastoma with the presence of oligodendroglial component with honey comb appearance.

Metastatic M5-T1 tumor tissue presents a high mitotic index. Histological aspects of a representative example of metastatic mesothelioma tissue invading the parietal peritoneum. On the parietal side, the interface between the tumor and the invaded peritoneum is characterized by extended areas of fibrosis.
Pathological images show the morphology of a micropapillary pattern in lung adenocarcinoma cells, which cluster and bulge into the alveolar space.
Section of the rectal specimen showing metastatic gastric adenocarcinoma.

Pleomorphic adenoma with a malignant component of myoepithelial carcinoma (right inset). Notes:  Peripherally, there is infiltration by chronic lymphocytic leukemia/small lymphocytic lymphoma (left inset).
Pathology image of low-grade mucoepidermoid carcinoma showing nests of tumour cells in the bronchial lumen.

Microscopic findings in an adult female bare-faced curassow (Crax fasciolata) with polyostotic osteosarcoma. Cytologic features of malignancy characterized by a high nucleus:cytoplasm ratio, coarse aspect chromatin with evidence of nucleoli, being possible to observe binucleated cells. HE, 400X.
Malignant poorly formed epithelial glands with surrounding malignant spindle cell sarcoma (H&E ×10 objective).
Microscopic photograph showing positive staining of the melanocytic marker in human melanoma.
Phyllodes tumour with malignant chondrosarcoma.

Histopathological appearance of polypoid, moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma taken from the surgically resected transverse colon on hematoxylin and eosin staining. Adenomatous features showing multiple tubular glands suggestive of tumor arising in the background of a tubular adenoma.
Lymphoma cells with a starry sky appearance.
Showing osteosarcoma components.
Histomorphological patterns in colorectal adenocarcinomas showing intraluminal bridging with necrotic debris in cases of endometrioid type of primary ovarian adenocarcinoma.
Pathological biopsy result revealed lymphoma or plasmacytoma.
Hematoxylin and eosin stain demonstrates a highly cellular, pleomorphic, and spindle shaped leiomyosarcoma with few mitotic figures.
Chondrosarcoma growth is strongly linked to the bone tissue with infiltration of chondrosarcoma cells into the bone tissue.
Histopathologic appearance of desmoplastic melanoma with bland-looking tumor cells and minimal pleomorphism or atypia.
Tall cell variant of papillary thyroid carcinoma invading the nerve, in contact with nerve fibers.

The left inguinal sentinel lymph node with focus of a 6 mm deposit of metastatic melanoma demonstrating intracytoplasmic melanin. Consistent with melanoma is the key features of melanocytes associated with blood vessels and large infiltrate of cells with abnormal patterning.
Papillary thyroid carcinoma with no central lymph node metastasis.

Frozen section showing only coagulative necrosis of glioblastoma multiforme with no malignant cells, which was misinterpreted as tuberculoma. Hematoxylin and eosin staining with original magnification, ×200.
Isolates neoplastic cells (gastric adenocarcinoma) in ascitic fluid.
Aspiration cytology smear of a case of plasmablastic lymphoma of the chest wall shows abundant plasma cells along with occasional lymphoid cells.

Small round cell sarcomas, type not determined, with neuroendocrine differentiation. The tumor was composed of mixed round and oval cells with low mitotic activity and relative monomorphic cytomorphology.
Ovarian metastases mimicking MBT originating from metastatic pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma.
Sarcomatoid carcinoma within the tumor. High-grade transformation to sarcomatoid carcinoma. The sarcomatoid component is designated by an 'X' in images.  H&E, 200x total magnification.
Microscopic appearance of the resected stomach showing adenocarcinoma cells in the muscularis propria.

28-year-old female with malignant peritoneal mesothelioma. Hematoxylin and eosin staining of the frozen section shows a highly cellular tumor consisting of spindle-out cells arranged in interlacing bundles and sheets. The cells have hyperchromatic nuclei with mild anisocytosis.
Representative pathology slides from the primary excision of the exophytic clitoral mass demonstrating melanoma. Invasive melanoma with spindled cell morphology and an overlying in-situ component.

Histopathology of mass post-resection shows a background'starry sky' appearance with tingible body macrophages. Cells have large vesicular nuclei with 2–3 chromocentres and show prominent mitotic activity, findings specific for lymphoma.
Pathology of combined hepatocellular carcinoma-cholangiocarcinoma showing both liver (sinusoidal pattern) and bile duct epithelium (glandular formation).

Postoperative histological results showing prominent mixed inflammatory infiltrate, macrophages, Touton-type giant cells, and myxoid matrix, indicating a diagnosis of myxoinflammatory fibroblastic sarcoma.

Analysis of a cellblock obtained via brushing revealing an exon 19 deletion in a 63‐year‐old male patient with left lower lobe lung adenocarcinoma whose transbronchial needle aspiration cellblock was positive for malignancy but inadequate for analysis. Hematoxylin and eosin staining.
Microphotographs showing the appearance of anaplastic large cell lymphoma in the capsule surrounding an implant. Most cases are of a B-cell phenotype.

Classic papillary thyroid carcinoma (PTC) within the nerve sheath, in contact with nerve fibers.

Histopathological examination: fibrous tissue with nests of cartilaginous proliferation with hypercellularity and variation in cellular size and shape, in a focally myxoid matrix. Final diagnosis was G2 peripheral conventional chondrosarcoma. Radiologic features were not consistent with the presence of dedifferentiated areas thus supporting the final diagnosis of a conventional chondrosarcoma.
Hematoxylin/eosin staining for ccRCC without sarcomatoid features.
Histology of the esophagus before treatment shows greater than 60 eosinophils per high-power field in the distal esophagus.
The bronchoalveolar lavage fluid showed many adenocarcinoma cells.
Representative aspect of CNS lymphoma sections stained with hematoxylin-Eosin. Perivascular cuffing and diffuse proliferation of microblasts typical of lymphomas is seen.

Histologic features of αβ T-cell lymphoma involving the spinal cord. Atypical lymphoid cells showed clear to eosinophilic cytoplasm with distinct cell borders and hyperchromatic nuclei with small indistinct nucleoli.
Langerhans cell sarcoma with nuclear pleomorphism and variable inflammatory infiltrate surrounding neoplastic tumor cells.
Endometrial carcinoma with lymphovascular invasion by a poorly differentiated component.
Cytology of a Papillary Thyroid carcinoma showing the fibrovascular core and an intranuclear inclusion.

Dedifferentiated liposarcoma with ill-defined foci of moderately cellular tumoral osteoid, containing mildly atypical osteocytes, and with mineralization. This is in keeping with heterologous osteosarcomatous differentiation.
Microscopic examination disclosed bony structures (osteoid) within the tumour with no other mesenchyme structures present, pointing to osteosarcoma.
Rectal adenocarcinoma microscopic sections show areas of moderately differentiated rectal adenocarcinoma.

Histologic section of the monophasic synovial sarcoma shows the tumor is mainly composed of spindled component characterized by elongated cells with ovoid pale-staining nuclei, inconspicuous nucleoli, and scanty cytoplasm.

Specific histomorphological patterns of diffuse invasion, so-called “secondary structures of Scherer” in glioblastoma. As a rule, glioma cells migrate along existing brain structures such as brain parenchyma, blood vessels, white matter tracts, and subpial spaces. The secondary structures of Scherer are referred to four criteria as perivascular satellitosis.

H&E stain showing granulation tissue with an ulcer of the esophageal wall.
Medullary thyroid carcinoma, mostly composed of spindle cells forming closely packed solid nests with amorphous eosinophilic deposits in the stroma.
Histological image of transbronchial lung biopsy specimen revealing an adenocarcinoma within the small vessels and surrounding tissue.
Hematoxylin and eosin slide from esophageal biopsy shows large numbers of intraepithelial eosinophils as well as multiple degranulated eosinophils.
Osteoid and atypical spindled cells from osteosarcoma were found in a distant lymph node.
Lympho-epithelioid variant (so-called Lennert’s lymphoma) of PTCL_NOS.
Photomicrographs of non-metastatic pheochromocytoma cases displaying focal tumor cell spindling with elongated nuclei. The patient is alive without metastatic disease after 20 years of follow-up.
Esophageal biopsy shows extravascular eosinophilic infiltration.
Prostatic ductal adenocarcinoma tumor made of back-to-back glands, which have a bridge-like structure within the glands. The glandular cavity is fissure type.
Jejunum showing diffuse large cell lymphomatous infiltration of all layers.
Pancreatobiliary type adenocarcinoma of the hepatopancreatic ampulla with a focal micropapillary pattern and cytological atypia.
Microphotograph of esophagus showing dilated blood vessels in lamina propria.
Pseudoliposarcomatous plasma cells in bone marrow cytology.
Histological findings of the resected gastric cancer show a poorly differentiated tubular adenocarcinoma near the lymphoid follicle in the mucosa.
The pictures show typical papillary growth pattern of glandular epithelial cells, which is usually seen in papillary thyroid carcinoma.
Evidence of fibrosis in the esophageal specimen.
High-power view of the fibrotic lesion shows several embedded small tubules and the cell nuclei possess the features of papillary thyroid carcinoma.
Histological features of combined hepatocellular cholangiocarcinoma. Passage area between cholangiocarcinoma features and HCC component.
Representative leiomyosarcoma with tumor cells exhibiting diffuse positive staining.
Follicular variant papillary thyroid carcinoma. Follicles are of varying size and contain hyper-eosinophilic colloid. The nuclear morphology is clear and enlarged, with nuclear grooves.
Microscopic pathology photographs of primary right atrial angiosarcoma demonstrate typical features of angiosarcoma.

Low-resolution image depicting a focus of PTC in a struma ovarii PTC: papillary thyroid carcinoma Multiple complex and branched papillae with central fibrovascular cores are seen, with presumably dystrophic calcification (psammoma body) in one papilla. The identification of psammoma bodies in a thyroid-type papillary neoplasm is highly supportive of malignancy. However, they are better visualized on a higher resolution
Lymphoma cells with vesicular chromatin and prominent cytoplasmic vacuolization. Background shows lymphoglandular bodies.
Histopathological evaluation revealing a poorly differentiated serous papillary adenocarcinoma of the right ovary, infiltrating the colon.
Histological presentation of enteropathy-associated T cell lymphoma in the jejunum. Hematoxylin and eosin staining showing large anaplastic tumor cells.

Microphotographs of the resected specimens’ histopathology sections show the mandibular lesion, compatible with osteosarcoma, composed mostly of neoplastic mineralized bone in a fibrous tissue stroma with a paucity of tumor cells, representing the effect of presurgical oncologic treatments.
Biopsy of the endobronchial lesion reveals low-grade mucoepidermoid carcinoma.
Positive membrane staining for PD-L1 in MSI-H endometrial carcinomas.
Representative image patches from diffuse large B-cell lymphoma are shown.
The S area shows how the squamous cells that line the esophagus appear under the microscope, whereas the B area shows Barrett’s metaplasia with goblet cells characteristic of Barrett’s metaplasia.
Resection specimen of colon with adenocarcinoma. Arrow indicates adjacent normal colonic mucosa. The adenocarcinoma is moderately differentiated.
Pathology of the cervical lymph node showing the presence of metastatic papillary thyroid carcinoma tumor.
The oesophagus showed groups and cords of carcinoma cells.
Highly cellular undifferentiated sarcoma in a fascicular pattern with increased mitotic activity.
A cluster of melanin pigment containing melanoma cells is observed.
Microscopic view of angiosarcoma with hemorrhagic areas and vascular channels lined by endothelial atypical cells.
Photomicrographs of the lesion after 6 months of treatment showing no evidence of residual melanoma.
Translocation renal cell carcinoma composed of clear cells with voluminous cytoplasm and distinct cell borders showing typical papillary architecture and hyalinised fibrovascular cords.
Histological findings of resected duodenum show papillary-like growth of adenocarcinoma in the vicinity of heterotopic pancreas tissue.
Complete destructive replacement of the myocardial wall by a diffuse large B cell lymphoma that demonstrated plasmacytoid differentiation and blasts.
Typical fibrocaseous granulomas in black rectangular box and lymphoma area in red oval.
Rectal adenocarcinoma cells invade nerves and grow within the perineural space.
The histopathological figure of RCC with sarcomatoid differentiation. ChRCC together with malignant fibrous histiocytoma-like cells using H&E stain.
Hematoxylin and eosin stain showing endometrial carcinoma invading the duodenal mucosa.
H&E staining of a moderate differentiated tubular gastric adenocarcinoma. The histology of this case was intestinal-type carcinoma according to the Lauren classification.
Image showing the pelvic tumor with sarcomatous-bizarre cells.
Rhabdomyosarcomatous differentiation.
Histology of amputated specimen shows sarcoma with storiform pattern and mitotic figures.

The lesion of Hashimoto thyroiditis shows diffused lymphoplasmacytic infiltration and parenchymal atrophy in the pathology.  HT = Hashimoto thyroiditis, PB = psammoma body, PTC = papillary thyroid carcinoma.
Clear cell sarcoma. Smears showed large polygonal cells with abundant wispy cytoplasm, round to oval nuclei, and prominent nucleoli.
Histopathology of neurolymphomatosis showing neuroganglion tissue diffusely infiltrated by abnormal lymphoid cells.
A nodule shows a nerve surrounded by melanoma with tumour cells arranged in a fasciculated growth pattern, similar to the nerve next to it.
Angiosarcomatous component exhibiting irregular vascular channels with mitotic figures.
Histology of parathyroid adenoma, papillary thyroid carcinoma, and thyroid adenoma. Papillary thyroid carcinoma with H&E staining.
Papillary thyroid carcinoma from the right lobe of the thyroid.
Photomicrograph of Ewing sarcoma showing scant and eosinophilic cytoplasm with sheets of small cells with high nuclear to cytoplasmic ratio.
Synovial sarcoma, biphasic, with an epithelial component exhibiting a glandular configuration.

Right retropharyngeal lymph node consistent with extensive metastasis by a well-differentiated squamous cell carcinoma. The sample is characterized microscopically by replacement of the paracortex and medulla and 50% of the cortex by epithelial cords, and cystic structures containing luminal keratin and necrotic debris and surrounded by a desmoplastic response. Neoplastic epithelial cells in cords and lining cysts have variable nuclear/cytoplasmic ratios, moderate amounts of light-to-glassy, intensely eosinophilic cytoplasm, and occasionally polarised nuclei.
Histology types of thyroid cancer identified in this study include classical type papillary thyroid carcinoma (PTC).
Histomorphological features of pleomorphic liposarcoma displaying more pronounced pleomorphic lipoblasts.
The histopathological examination of the excised mass combined with the pathology expert group discussion considered lung adenocarcinoma.
Histological specimen from the oesophagus showing marked oedema and numerous intraepithelial eosinophils in the oesophageal squamous mucosa.
Some unusual morphological features of papillary renal neoplasm with reverse polarity. Tumor components focally invade into renal parenchyma.
Pathological findings: pancreatic mucinous adenocarcinoma.
Bone marrow revealing hypercellularity mainly due to interstitial infiltration by Burkitt lymphoma.
Histopathology images of cardiac intimal sarcoma showing cells arranged in spindles with high mitotic activity and negative tumor margins.

Histopathological examination of the tumor shows a dense infiltration of round cells admixed with cells with large eosinophilic cytoplasm and vesicular nucleus with prominent nucleolus, consistent with non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.

Oesophageal ulcer biopsy: Focal ulceration surrounded by neutrophil-rich inflammatory infiltrate. Dyscohesive squamous cells are seen. Some of them are enlarged with nucleomegaly and many bi- and multinucleated cells. These show dense eosinophilic intranuclear inclusions.
Photomicrograph of liver pathology showing hepatocellular carcinoma with an irregular and invasive border.
Different morphological appearances of lung invasive adenocarcinoma. Mucus-out-of-cell adenocarcinoma (tumor cells with abundant extracellular mucus admixed with invasive adenocarcinoma patterns).
Photomicrographs of inflammatory myofibroblastic tumour with sarcomatous transformation showing marked atypia with hyperchromasia and mitosis.
Atypical lipogenic cells were found in neoplastic cells, constituting a component of pleomorphic liposarcoma.

Pathological samples of the focal liver lesions show liver metastatic tumors from colorectal adenocarcinoma with fat accumulation in normal liver tissue outside of hepatic metastases after neoadjuvant chemotherapy.
Histological examination of the resected pulmonary nodule revealed metastatic rectal adenocarcinoma in a background of normal lung parenchyma.
Type I papillary renal cell carcinoma: basophilic cuboidal or columnar cells with clear cytoplasm, small hyperchromatic, round or oval nuclei, and inconspicuous nucleoli.

The neoplasm is composed of discohesive oval-to-round neoplastic cells with abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm and eccentric nuclei, showing pleomorphism. These features partly resemble plasma cells, lymphoma cells, and rhabdoid cells.

Tubulopapillary structures composed of uniform cuboidal cells with unsuspicious round nuclei, without atypia and foamy macrophages in the papillary cores. Histologically consistent with primary papillary renal cell carcinoma type 1 in renal biopsy.
Spindle cell pattern in Fibrosarcoma.
Adenocarcinoma in the duodenum mainly located in the extra-mucosal layer, and combined with ectopic pancreas, which is consistent with carcinoma derived from ectopic pancreas.
Glial cells with round nuclei associated with Grade 3 oligodendroglioma in a sample of the original intracranial mass.
Hematoxylin and eosin staining for specimens obtained by CT-guided PCNB for lung squamous cell carcinoma (SQC) subtype diagnoses showing nonkeratinizing pattern.
Non-Hodgkin lymphoma, small cell morphology.

Fibroblastic sarcoma that developed in the radiation field. The tumor cells have large, irregular nuclei and are intimately related to the collagenous stroma, which also contains scattered chronic inflammatory cells.

Hematoxylin and eosin stain showing extra-nodal marginal zone (MALT) lymphoma characterized by diffuse infiltration by atypical lymphocytes including small cells with irregular nuclei and larger cells with relatively abundant cytoplasm. Inset demonstrates rare Dutcher bodies. MALT: mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue.
Histopathology of the most common malignant renal neoplasms. Papillary type 2.
Microscopic examination demonstrating glioblastoma with neovascularization. The glioblastoma extensively infiltrates and replaces the entire cortical band.
Hürthle cell carcinoma and Classic type of papillary thyroid carcinoma separated by a thick capsule.
H&E histological slide of the patient's papillary renal cell carcinoma, Fuhrman grade III. Occasional papillary structures demonstrate typical foamy histiocytes in fibrovascular cores.

Microscopic view of the bone metastasis in a tissue sample taken during the primary surgery. Folicular structures which contain the colloid proliferate invasively via destruction of the trabeculae, indicating a diagnosis of metastatic thyroid carcinoma.

Specific histomorphological patterns of diffuse invasion, so-called “secondary structures of Scherer” in glioblastoma. As a rule, glioma cells migrate along existing brain structures such as brain parenchyma, blood vessels, white matter tracts, and subpial spaces. The secondary structures of Scherer are referred to four criteria as invasion along the white matter tracts.
Area of phyllodes tumor with stromal/sarcomatous overgrowth demonstrating nuclear atypia and increased mitotic activity.
Histology types of thyroid cancer identified in this study, including tall cell variant PTC.
Burkitt lymphoma, ascitic fluid; monomorphous population of medium-sized cells with prominent cytoplasmic vacuolization.
Representation of malignant primary tumors of the liver in FCM scans. Hepatocellular carcinoma (grade 2) in FCM.
Hematoxylin–Eosin staining of a PDAC biopsy obtained through EUS–FNB.  EUS–FNB: Endoscopic ultrasound–fine-needle biopsy; PDAC: Pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma.
Histopathology of adrenocortical carcinoma shows pleomorphic tumour cells forming patternless sheets of cells.
Histopathologic examination of thyroid mass is consistent with papillary thyroid carcinoma.
A histopathological exam confirms papillary renal cell carcinoma.
Sampling pattern with FNAB as obvious in cell-blocks with the predominance of diagnostic tumor cells without stroma using Cell-block section of EUS-FNAB needle rise of pancreatic adenocarcinoma.

Core biopsy of prostate shows extensive infiltration by adenocarcinoma. The majority of the tumour is composed of poorly formed glands, contrasting with occasional larger, well-formed, benign glands.

Hematoxylin and eosin stain shows the coexistence of normal lymphoid follicles with well-defined mantels and hyperplastic germinal centers, and low-grade follicular lymphoma with irregularly shaped and confluent neoplastic follicles.
Ductal adenocarcinoma with papillary patterns in the prostatic ducts.
Rectal adenocarcinoma cells with solid differentiation and some microscopic microabscesses. Rectal adenocarcinoma grade 3.

The glioblastoma component of the left frontal lobe tumour showing neoplastic astrocytes with pleomorphic nuclei and fibrillary cytoplasm. There was frequent mitotic activity, microvascular proliferation, and pseudopalisading necrosis. The oligodendroglial component of the left frontal lobe tumour.
Representative tissue histology of PSC tumors showing carcinosarcoma.

H & E-stained ascending colon polyp index lesion revealing a well-differentiated invasive colonic adenocarcinoma arising from an adenoma with focal invasion of the carcinoma into the submucosa involving the inked margin.
The malignant melanoma is characterized by compacted fascicular and sheet like growth of highly atypical and mitotically active melanocytes. (H&E, original magnification × 200).

Representative H&E stained brain tissue sections of the same individual diagnosed as mixed anaplastic oligoastrocytoma (AOA).  ( A ) Before laser microdissection and ( B ) after laser microdissection.
Adenocarcinoma of the prostate Gleason 9 (4+5).
Histology types of thyroid cancer identified in this study include the follicular variant of papillary thyroid carcinoma (PTC).

The renal oncocytoma component is in the central area and is composed of large eosinophilic cells with a cyst of variable size. The oncocytoma component is on the left and the papillary renal cell carcinoma component is on the right.
The superficial and deep reticular dermis are filled with melanophages, and residual melanoma is absent.
Sarcoma; biphasic glandular structures are formed amid a spindle cell background.
Hematoxylin and eosin-stained section of the left ovary showing low-grade serous carcinoma with invasive focus.
A ductal adenocarcinoma of the pancreas surrounding and invading an islet in the background of chronic pancreatitis. The islet has regular contours despite an invasion.
Lymphangioma-like Kaposi sarcoma with the promontory sign well demonstrated.

High-grade lobulated sclerosing liposarcoma with focal loss of differentiation. Fatty tissue is present in the upper left area, which contains lipoblasts. In the lower right area, there are areas of dedifferentiation with leiomyosarcoma features.
Well-differentiated adenocarcinoma of the rectum.
Histopathologic examination of the esophagus showing acute inflammation and ulceration with the presence of multinucleated cells consistent with herpetic infection.
Biopsy of bladder neck mass demonstrating poorly differentiated prostatic adenocarcinoma.

Photomicrograph of the histological specimen showing conventional osteosarcoma composed of sarcomatous tumor cells that produced both osteoid and immature bone, and chondroid matrices. Insert showing a high power view of severely atypical cells of the lesion.
Endometrial curetting prior to therapy, irregular cribriform glands, and mild atypia: well-differentiated endometrioid carcinoma.
Pathologic picture of well-differentiated liposarcoma showing atypical stromal cells and collagen ropey bands.
Photomicrography of the retroocular mass showing neoplastic cells with the same pattern as the esophageal lesion.
Photomicrograph showing focal dysplasia at the esophageal cut margin.

A detailed examination revealed preservation of erythrocytes and no signs of lysis or loss of staining of eosinophils in a GAF-fixed colorectal adenocarcinoma. An area enriched with eosinophils is captured at a higher magnification.

A detailed examination revealed preservation of erythrocytes and no signs of lysis or loss of staining of eosinophils in a GAF-fixed colorectal adenocarcinoma. An area enriched with eosinophils is captured at a higher magnification.
The open biopsy shows pleomorphic spindle cell sarcoma.
Melanoma. Invasive malignant melanoma, spindle cell type, low power.

Representative histology of papillary thyroid carcinoma (PTC) subtypes. High-magnification image of PTC with poorly differentiated components. The tumor cells of the poorly differentiated components showed no distinct nuclear features of PTC.
Typical growth characteristics of glioblastoma multiforme; neovascularity necrosis and palisade type arrangement of tumor cells are presented.
Histopathology of ovarian low-grade and high-grade serous carcinoma shows uniform nuclei and infrequent mitotic figures, with low nuclear atypia of well-differentiated tumors. 40× magnification.
Representative micrograph of pulmonary adenocarcinoma stained with hematoxylin and eosin. Neoplastic cells show a large hyperchromatic basophilic nucleus.
Histological response to the treatment: biopsy of a high-grade, undifferentiated spindle cell and focally pleomorphic sarcoma with brisk mitotic activity.
Representative histologic images of follicular lymphoma showing lymphoid follicular formations with small-to-medium-sized centrocyte-like cells and a few centroblast-like cells.
Representative image of HE staining for TBB with adenocarcinoma.  HE: hematoxylin and eosin; TBB: transbronchial biopsy.

Pathological findings of the resected SMT show gastric glands extending into the submucosal layer, consistent with GCP. Well-differentiated adenocarcinoma is partially seen within the GCP. There is no involvement of the lateral and deep margins, lymphatic invasion, vascular invasion, or perineural invasion.
Malignant breast invasive ductal carcinoma glandular structures (hematoxylin and eosin ×200). Fig. 5

Histologic differences between benign giant cell tumor of bone (GCTB), giant cell-rich osteosarcoma, and malignant GCTB. Malignant GCTB consists of a GC tumor component with mononuclear cells with typical nuclei, side by side with a pleomorphic malignant spindle cell component (T).
Histopathological image of malignant melanoma.
Photomicrographs of colon tissues stained with H&E show Grade 3 poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma.
Histopathology figure of osteosarcoma.
Well circumscribed nodule composed of papillary thyroid carcinoma with solid, follicular, and papillary architecture surrounded by fibrosis.
Angiosarcoma demonstrating tumor consisting of anastomosing vascular channels and hobnailing nuclei.
This oncocytic type papillary cholangiocarcinoma shows a columnar lining with abundant oxyphilic granular cytoplasm and intraepithelial lumina, giving rise to a cribriform pattern of growth.
The histological examination confirmed the diagnosis of pituitary lymphoma. Figures show infiltrative large-sized lymphocytes with occasional mitotic activity.
LSD1 expression in positive control. A lung adenocarcinomas that overexpression of LSD1 was used as positive control.
Pathological features of choroidal melanoma, epithelioid type.
Colonic type appendiceal adenocarcinoma arising in a villous adenoma.

Examples of expression of tumour-infiltrating lymphocytes (TILs) in haematoxylin and eosin-stained sections (magnification ×100) of oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinoma (OPSCC). Predominant TILs infiltrate in OPSCC where almost the whole stroma is occupied by TILs.
Histologic findings of tumor mass from rib show pleomorphic astrocytic tumor cells with mitosis and nuclear atypia compatible with glioblastoma.
Bone marrow biopsy showed diffuse involvement by lymphoma.
Esophageal biopsies show granulomatous changes.
Histopathological image of ulcerated nodular melanoma, left mid-back.

H&E staining of an architecturally disturbed germinal center in a supposed case of follicular hyperplasia (FH) of a patient, who developed in follow-up a splenic diffuse red pulp small B cell lymphoma.
Pathologic findings of the biopsied gastric tissue show adenocarcinoma with fused glands intermingled with inflammatory exudates and normal mucosal glands.
Histological image of esophageal tumor showing infiltration nests with keratinization.
Microscopic cross-section of the normal portion of the recurrent laryngeal nerve resected due to invasion by thyroid cancer, showing the true nerve component surrounded by thick peri-neural tissue.

Greenfinch, esophagus with predominantly superficial heterophilic inflammation, mucosal ulceration and bacterial growth. H&E staining, bar = 160. Insert shows fibrin formation, infiltration of heterophils, intralesional and superficial coccoid bacteria; H&E staining, bar = 40 μm).
Microscopic findings of low grade fibromyxoid sarcoma. Hematoxylin-eosin staining.
Histologic findings of tumor mass from spine show pleomorphic astrocytic tumor cells with mitosis and nuclear atypia compatible with glioblastoma.
Tumor budding in an EMR specimen of T1 esophageal cancer, indicated by arrows.
Trucut biopsy from the mass showing large round tumor cells with extensive ischemic necrosis suggestive of non-Hodgkin’s lymphoma (diffuse large B cell type).
Microscopic features of retroperitoneal leiomyosarcoma showing intersecting fascicles.
High power view showing intraepithelial infiltrate by lymphomatous cells.
Examples of uveal melanoma cells showing intense nuclear staining in about half of tumoral cells.
Nevoid melanoma showing deep area of the tumor with lack of maturation. Enlarged, atypical tumoral cells are observed, presenting prominent nucleoli. Mitoses are highlighted.
Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma (DLBCL) with pleomorphic nuclei and numerous mitotic figures.
Primary invasive ductal carcinoma (left breast lesion, core needle biopsy). Hematoxylin & Eosin (H & E) stain.
Histopathological findings showed atypical cell infiltration into the esophagus.
Biopsy with hematoxylin and eosin staining showing microabscess formation in Barrett's esophagus.
Histologic findings of adrenocortical carcinoma show sheets and nests of hypercellular tumor cells with thick fibrous septation.
Histologically, Ewing sarcoma is composed of small cells with round hyperchromatic nuclei.

Histology of the biopsy samples. Neuroendoscopic biopsy specimen of the tumor in the pineal region revealing adenocarcinoma with a papillotubular pattern. Transbronchial biopsy specimen in the lung tumor revealing adenocarcinoma similar to the pineal region tumor.
Pathological findings of periosteal osteosarcoma cells.
Photomicrographs of the tumor showing cellular arrangements in bundles with occasional 'fishbone' arrangement, fibrosarcoma-like, with the presence of mitoses.

Histologic appearance of the clear cell adenocarcinoma of the colon shows focal chronic histiocytic intervillositis in the center of the picture. Compared to Panel 1, the changes seem a bit more pronounced.
A low-power view of the lymphoma, involving the intestinal wall and ulcerating the mucosa.
Tissue sections showing a glioblastoma multiforme with bone invasion.
Undifferentiated sarcoma. Hematoxylin-eosin staining.
Microscopic pathologic examination showing histopathological features of spindle cell sarcoma.
Photomicrograph image showing micropapillary/solid histologic subtypes of lung adenocarcinoma in PTNB specimens.
