Pathological aspects of anaplastic thyroid carcinoma in the left thyroid lobe, with hypercellularity, discohesive tumor cells, marked pleomorphism, and multinucleated giant cells.

Malignant melanoma. Numerous single cells are seen on a smear. The cells contain round to oval nuclei with moderate amount of cytoplasm. Occasionally cells contain melanin pigment, as observed at ×200 magnification using Diff‐Quik staining.

Surgical section of medullary thyroid cancer (MTC) with polygonal or spindle cells in nests or follicle formation. Tumor cells displayed granular cytoplasm with oval nuclei. The stroma contained amyloid deposits.

Lymph node involvement by nodular lymphocyte-predominant Hodgkin lymphoma (NLPHL)
showing prominent nodular growth pattern (hematoxylin and eosin, 100× magnification).
Inset is a high-magnification (400×) view of the characteristic cell of NLPHL, the
lymphocyte-predominant (LP) or “popcorn” cell. Note the polylobulated nucleus and small,
peripherally located nucleoli.
Pathological examination of the lung tumor orienting toward a poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma. Hematoxylin and eosin stain.
Microscopic review of dual pathologies shows meningioma containing foci of large B-cell lymphoma, characterized by dense aggregates of cells with marked nuclear enlargement and hyperchromasia.

1. Medium power field of acral junctional nevus. Most cells are in solitary units, but they form groups at the base of the rete ridges. 2. Acral lentiginous melanoma. Single melanocytes proliferate along the dermo-epidermal junction.
Pheochromocytoma cells stained with hematoxylin and eosin. The tumor cells had small nuclei and abundant finely granular amphophilic cytoplasm and were arranged in solid nests and organoid patterns.

Transrectal biopsy produced a diagnosis of poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma with small cell neuroendocrine carcinoma. HE staining produced an initial diagnosis of Gleason pattern 5b poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma.
Routine histology, stained using hematoxylin-eosin, shows gastric adenocarcinoma.
Histology shows moderately differentiated squamous cell carcinoma of the lung.
Cellular morphological details in YWHAE-NUTM2 sarcoma.
Paratrabecular infiltrate in follicular lymphoma.
Photomicrograph showing B-cell lymphoma cells in the intestinal mucosa.

Thyroid section showing mixed medullary and papillary thyroid carcinoma. A, Cells with characteristics of papillary thyroid carcinoma (irregular nuclear membrane, nuclear overlap, and clarified chromatin), sometimes with follicle formation. B, Interspersed with salt and pepper chromatin cells. Histological type (WHO): Mixed carcinoma composed of a component of medullary carcinoma and another of follicular cells with characteristics of papillary carcinoma in the left lobe; In the right lobe, a 1 mm papillary microcarcinoma is observed. Multifocality/intrathyroid spread: observed, with sizes from 1 to 23 mm. Vascular and lymphatic invasion: observed. Infiltrative pattern. Invasion of the gland capsule: observed. Extra-thyroid extension: observed; limited, however, without involvement of striated muscle tissue. Margins: not involved by neoplasia. Lymph nodes: metastases (from the medullary and papillary components) are observed in 12 of the 38 lymph nodes isolated on the left and 8 of the 10 in the central region; size of the largest metastasis: 20 mm—T2N1BM0.
Photomicrograph of malignant melanoma. Tumor cells arranged in nests and cords. Hematoxylin and eosin (H and E), × 100.

Microscopic pathology showed well-differentiated, invasive, mucinous, adenocarcinoma diffusely involving the appendix, sigmoid, and cecum through the serosa. Low power photomicrograph shows junction of mucinous appendiceal adenocarcinoma with serrated glands on the right, contiguous with normal sigmoid mucosa with normal glands, on the left.
A Crohn’s disease-associated small bowel adenocarcinoma (SBA) observed with hematoxylin and eosin.
Well-differentiated liposarcoma with adipocytes intermixed with diaphragmatic skeletal muscle fibers, demonstrating that the liposarcoma originated from the diaphragm.
Pathology of tumor tissues from the right lung revealed poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma.
Vaginal melanoma. Vaginal squamous epithelium with areas of ulceration. In lamina propria one can observe tumoral cells organized in nests.
Biopsy showing a classic 'starry sky' appearance consistent with Burkitt's lymphoma.
Barrett’s esophagus with features suspicious for carcinoma. This biopsy shows features of high-grade dysplasia (HGD). In addition, there are a few glands with eosinophilic luminal debris.
Histopathology findings suggestive of Diffuse Large B cell Non-Hodgkin’s Lymphoma.
Histology revealed that the rectal tumor is a mucinous adenocarcinoma.

Microscopic images demonstrating the replacement of the spleen tissue by large atypical lymphoid cells, with scattered large polygonal cells characterized by bizarre pleomorphic nuclei resembling the cells of anaplastic large cell lymphoma, and fewer cells with large atypical nuclei resembling Reed-Sternberg cells.
VEGF expression by melanoma cells (40x).
Photomicrograph of a surgically resected infantile esophageal duplication cyst showing an internal layer with pseudostratified ciliated epithelium.

The biopsy shows low-grade myxofibrosarcoma characterized by a spindle cell neoplasm in a fibromyxoid stroma with prominent, arching, interconnecting, curvilinear blood vessels and a perivascular condensation of tumor cells.

Sarcoma forming cellular fascicles is seen in the stroma of the tongue, focally invading the intrinsic muscle. The surface squamous epithelium shows no dysplastic field change or connection with sarcoma.
Appendiceal adenocarcinoma. Microscopically, the cecum biopsy shows a neoplastic glandular proliferation.
The endometrioid carcinoma component was characterized by a proliferation of back-to-back atypical endometrial-like glands.

Histopathological characteristics of the recurring tumor depict features of malignant sarcoma with areas of myxoid stroma that contain elongated, thin‐walled blood vessels, resembling the morphology of myxofibrosarcoma

83-year-old male with elevated prostate-specific antigen (PSA) was diagnosed with prostate cancer. An area of dysheasive neoplastic cells demonstrates esophageal adenocarcinoma of signet ring cell morphology. Signet ring morphology is described as abundant in cytoplasm with the nucleus pushed to one side.
H&E stain of the colon segment demonstrating adenocarcinoma with presence of signet cells.

Diffuse involvement of spleen by malignant melanoma cells showing fascicular and trabecular pattern (Hematoxylin and Eosin stain, scale bar = 100 μm). Inset shows rhabdoid type tumor cells (Hematoxylin and Eosin stain, scale bar = 50 μm).

Diffuse involvement of spleen by malignant melanoma cells showing fascicular and trabecular pattern (Hematoxylin and Eosin stain, scale bar = 100 μm). Inset shows rhabdoid type tumor cells (Hematoxylin and Eosin stain, scale bar = 50 μm).
Histopathology of the tumor shows anaplasticity, nuclear atypia, and cellular pleomorphism, confirming the diagnosis of glioblastoma.
Histopathological picture of high-grade osteosarcoma of the right distal femur.
Phyllodes tumor with liposarcomatous differentiation. Other features (stromal atypia, mitotic activity) in this tumor supported the designation as malignant phyllodes tumor.

Fine-needle aspiration cytology of the anterior abdominal wall lump revealed hypercellular smear showing markedly pleomorphic sarcomatous cells including giant cells amidst stroma consistent with osteogenic sarcoma. A large sarcomatous cell with a pleomorphic nucleus and moderate cytoplasm is also observed.
Cranial mediastinal hemangiosarcoma. The cells are tightly packed with minimal amphophilic cytoplasm and hyperchromatic plump oblong nuclei with coarsely stippled chromatin and a single nucleolus.
The invasive ductal carcinoma in the right breast was mainly composed of micropapillary components. The tumor cells were suspended in a clear space.
Metastatic adenocarcinoma from the lung diagnosed by EUSFNB. Tumor cells with variable nuclear size and salt and pepper chromatin.

Histopathologic image of the specimen from a lesion on the left lateral neck (H&E, × 200), showing neutrophilic perivascular infiltration throughout the whole field, with the absence of squamous cell carcinoma or other malignancy.
Superficial spreading melanoma of the ear and metastasis infiltrating striated muscle fibers.
The pathology of the esophagus indicated moderate to severe squamous epithelial dysplasia.
Colonoscopy and histologic findings in colon. Rectal adenocarcinoma.
Pathologic specimen from multi-focal breast cancer recurrence in 2008; invasive ductal carcinoma.
Microscopic findings in low grade chondrosarcoma show host bone permeation, a hallmark of chondrosarcoma.
Dermoscopy-guided incisional biopsy revealing a 0.37 mm-thick melanoma.
Lymph node showing features of pediatric-type follicular lymphoma.

The light microscopic features of monophasic fibrous-type and biphasic-type synovial sarcoma (SS). Monophasic fibrous SS typically appears with fascicles and sheets of uniform small oval neoplastic cells. Biphasic SS has spindle cell mesenchymal components and glandular elements.
Histological features of nodular lymphocyte-predominant Hodgkin’s lymphoma (NLPHL). Hematoxylin and eosin stain at low magnification (×100) shows the vaguely nodular architecture of NLPHL (arrows).
8 (4 + 4, Grade Group 4) prostate adenocarcinoma with strong membrane staining.
Esophageal squamous mucosa showing separation and detachment of superficial squamous epithelial cells in the absence of any mucosal inflammatory process.

Histological examination shows a resected part of the stomach with foci of moderately differentiated tubular adenocarcinoma in fibrous stroma, located in submucosa and subserosa through muscle layers of the stomach.  a  ·20.  b  ·100.
Detail of tumor melanoma cells with atypical nuclei.
Ascitic fluid in a known case of lung carcinoma showing features of papillary adenocarcinoma with H&E stain.
Microscopic examination of the cholangiocarcinoma of the distal bile duct shows pancreatic tissue in the upper left quadrant and infiltration into the papillary region by an adenocarcinoma.
Photomicrograph showing the two components in the gliosarcoma: cytologically atypical nests of glial cells are intimately admixed with spindled sarcomatous tumor.

Right tonsil, squamous cell carcinoma. There is a partially exophytic, mostly infiltrating mass expanding the majority of the tonsil. The residual tonsillar parenchyma is indicated by white asterisks.

Right tonsil, squamous cell carcinoma. There is a partially exophytic, mostly infiltrating mass expanding the majority of the tonsil. The residual tonsillar parenchyma is indicated by white asterisks.
Microscopically, two types of adenocarcinoma cells with dissimilar differentiation types were observed on the serosal surface of the rectum using Hematoxylin and Eosin staining.
Biphasic neoplasm showing both benign epithelial component and sarcomatous mesenchymal component.
Lymphocytes diffusely interposed between melanoma cells in the entire vertical growth phase.
Adenocarcinoma of the rectum.
Sarcomatous areas with spindle and rare bizarre cells.
Malignant serous carcinoma of ovary.

A hematoxylin and eosin–stained tissue section from the surgical resection shows enlarged, pleomorphic tumor cells invading into fat. The increased cellularity and histologic features indicate an undifferentiated pleomorphic sarcoma. Scattered inflammatory cells with small hyperchromatic nuclei were noted in the background. 200×.
Extranodal NK/T-cell lymphoma, nasal type. The lymphoma cells are small to medium-sized and are angioinvasive.
Histological examination of the transbronchial biopsy specimen revealed squamous cell carcinoma.
Lymph vascular invasion of pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma.
Histopathologic image of the tumor exhibiting moderate pleomorphism and moderate mitotic activity with no undifferentiated areas—consistent with a grade II chondrosarcoma.
Hematoxylin-and-eosin-stained primary melanoma specimen showing an absent lymphocytic infiltrate.
Low-grade fibromyxoid sarcoma with fibrous parts (including hints of collagenous rosettes) on the upper left and myxoid parts opposite.
Biopsy of the transverse colon mass showing adenocarcinoma.
Histological findings of mediastinal tumour resembled those of primary ovarian serous carcinoma.
Histologic features of small biopsy samples of mesothelioma showing tumor cells invading fat.
Microscopical features of extraskeletal myxoid chondrosarcoma: Myxoid tumor nodules separated by fibrous septae, containing neoplastic cells.
Esophagus: Focal inflammatory cell infiltration in the lamina propria with focal lymphoplasmacytic infiltration.

Example of imaging and pathologic features of pseudoprogression in a glioblastoma patient 4 months after completing chemoradiation. Gliosis, and a small amount of residual tumor which was not mitotically active.

The epithelial layer of the esophageal squamous mucosa is flat. Squamous cells in the basal layer of mucosa proliferate and become crowded. These cells have uniform shape and size, with thickened nuclear chromatin.
H&E-stained sections demonstrating melanoma in situ with regression.
Primary effusion lymphoma presenting as a solid tumour.
Microscopic findings of cholangiocarcinoma with perineural invasion.
Esophageal histology shows an evident eosinophilic cellular infiltrate in the esophageal epithelium, with intercellular oedema and basal zone hyperplasia.
Adenocarcinoma of human lung was stained by hematoxylin and eosin.
Gastric mixed adenocarcinoma with 70% mucinous adenocarcinoma and 30% papillary adenocarcinoma.
Bone tissue invaded by lung adenocarcinoma cells.
Histology with H&E staining showing spindle cells suggestive of monophasic variant of synovial sarcoma.
Histology of the primary dermal melanoma.
Sarcomatous component is consisted with pleomorphic cells and atypical spindle cells.
Histologic appearance of the clear cell adenocarcinoma of the colon showing focal chronic histiocytic intervillositis in the center of the picture.
Histopathological slide of the esophageal biopsy revealing acute on chronic inflammation with reactive epithelial changes.
Pleomorphic mantle cell lymphoma demonstrated in the histopathology of a pretherapy bone marrow sample.

MEITL H&E (×10): There is a predominantly diffuse, infiltrate of atypical medium-sized cells with scattered mitosis and apoptosis. MEITL, monomorphic epitheliotropic intestinal T-cell lymphoma; H&E, hematoxylin and eosin.
Adrenocortical carcinosarcoma histological appearance showing carcinomatous component with epithelioid cells and clear to eosinophilic cytoplasm arranged in a nested pattern.
A melanoma satellite in the subcutaneous tissue.
Bone marrow biopsy from posterosuperior iliac spine showing intertrabecular spaces replaced by osteosarcoma.

Photomicrograph of pre-treatment tumor on hematoxylin and eosin (H&E) stain shows dense and loose areas of cellularity, characteristic of embryonal rhabdomyosarcoma. Occasional scattered cells with'strap' cell morphology, ovoid nuclei with abundant polarized cytoplasm with blunted ends, indicative of skeletal muscle differentiation, were present amid numerous poorly differentiated tumor cells with scant cytoplasm.  Fig. 2.
Dedifferentiated sarcomatoid morphology demonstrating marked nuclear atypia, pleomorphism, and mitotic activity.
Histopathological examination of mixed-type liposarcoma tissue shows an undifferentiated component.
Adenocarcinoma is present at the esophagogastric junction.
Well differentiated, grade 1 hepatocellular carcinoma and early hepatocellular carcinoma with diffuse fatty change. White arrows indicate the interface between HCC and background liver.
Representative histopathological images of high-grade myxofibrosarcoma showing myxoid stroma, pleomorphic cells, and curvilinear vessels.
Gastric hyperplastic polyp with adenocarcinoma using H&E staining.
Typical histology of pancreatic ITPN with an associated invasive adenocarcinoma.  Infiltrative component of the ITPN.
Gastric mucosa with metastatic adenocarcinoma.
Hematoxylin-eosin (HE) staining of resected spindle cell sarcoma specimen shows tumor cells with small spindle-shaped cytoplasm.
Histopathological appearance of well-differentiated adenocarcinoma of the colon with arrows marking the area of serosal invasion.
Histiocytic sarcoma. Diffuse proliferation of large round to oval cells with pleomorphic vesicular nuclei, prominent nucleoli and abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm. A mitosis is seen.

Microscopic view of the tumor in the seminal vesicle: The tumor cells were arranged in trabecular and solid nests, which was compatible with the original small bowel adenocarcinoma. 400 × magnification.

Histological features of mucinous colon adenocarcinoma and gastric carcinoma – intestinal type. Gastric cancer, intestinal type. Tumor is composed of confluent tubular structures consisting of atypical cells with hyperchromatic nuclei similar to intestinal adenocarcinoma, which invade the submucosal gastric area. In the upper part is antral mucosa with reactive mucinous foveolar hyperplasia.
Esophageal tumor—sheets of large cells with plasmacytoid features.
A photograph of the microscopic examination of the well-differentiated chondrosarcoma.
Stromal p16 overexpression in malignant endometrial lesions: Endometrioid carcinoma (EC). White arrows indicate the periglandular stroma.
Histopathology of biopsy specimen shows adenocarcinoma of gastric-type mucosa.

Microscopic image of diffuse large B-cell lymphoma showing a diffuse growth pattern with large cells having amphophilic cytoplasm, eccentric nuclei, and a central nucleoli. Centroblasts with basophilic cytoplasm, vesicular chromatin, and prominent nucleoli close to the nuclear membrane are also observed.
Histopathology of left eye: conjunctival melanoma with free margins and evident melanocytes with nuclear pleomorphism.

Infiltrating moderately differentiated hepatocellular carcinoma of the liver.
Microscopic identification of Kaposi's sarcoma (KS) and KS-like using H and E staining; plaque: plaque stage KS with bizarre vessels; there is erythrocyte extravasation and hemosiderin pigmentation.
Section from lung showing a moderately differentiated invasive squamous cell carcinoma.

Brain surgical specimen showing high-grade glioma with foci of necrosis and microvascular proliferation consistent with glioblastoma multiforme (WHO Grade IV).

Biopsy of this lesion confirmed an EBV positive B-cell lymphoma.

Hematoxylin and eosin stain shows pancreatic carcinosarcoma with poorly differentiated ductal adenocarcinoma and spindle cell component. Well to moderately differentiated ductal structures with transition to poorly formed ducts and to small sheets of epithelioid cells with no apparent structure.
Entrapped glomeruli in sarcomatoid tumor cells.
Histopathological aspect of pigmented melanoma.
Histopathological findings show a biphasic pattern with benign odontogenic epithelium surrounded by sarcomatous component with intense cellular and nuclear pleomorphism and mitotic figures.

Histopathology shows peripheral T-cell lymphoma with diffuse infiltrates of medium-sized lymphoid cells with irregular nuclei.

Histologically, hematoxylin and eosin staining of metastatic malignant melanoma in a lymph node.

Pathology of case 6 with pulmonary enteric adenocarcinoma using HE staining.

Histological presentation of pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma in hematoxylin and eosin staining: irregular glandular mucinous aggregates (both large and small), immersed in a fibrous stroma, with basal-nucleus polarized cells and sporadic interposed goblet cells.

Epithelioid mesothelioma presenting as metastatic lymph node of the mediastinum.
Acinar adenocarcinoma of prostate.
Histopathological examination view of the abdominal pheochromocytoma.
Pathological finding of intestinal type of lung adenocarcinoma in female patient: positivity of CDX-2.
Thyroid gland with classic papillary thyroid carcinoma.

Histologic features of primary penile desmoplastic melanoma. Low-power photomicrograph of the penile glans depicts haphazardly arranged spindle tumor cells permeating in between collagen bundles and deeply infiltrating the dermis and corpus spongiosum within. In intimate association with the spindle tumor cells are focal atypical intraepidermal melanocytic proliferation and pseudoepitheliomatous hyperplasia in the overlying epidermis.
A photomicrograph of the tumor shows small proliferating spindle cells and lipoblasts in the myxoid stroma, findings consistent with myxoid liposarcoma. Hematoxylin and eosin stain.
Histopathology images of chondrosarcoma showing hyaline cartilage matrix and chondrocytes in lacunae.
Cell block of Ewing's sarcoma (H and E)
The tumor cells strongly reacted with human melanoma black-45 monoclonal antibody.
Tumor budding in an EMR specimen of T1 esophageal cancer. Tumor budding foci are indicated by arrows.
Histologic findings of the resected rhabomyosarcoma show a characteristic eccentric nucleus with eosinophilic cytoplasm.

Invasive cancer cells are floating in the mucous lake. Lymphoplasmacytic infiltration of the tumor tissue was observed, but it was not as prominent as the inflammatory features in Lynch syndrome-associated colon adenocarcinoma.
Classic histopathologic appearance of a pheochromocytoma with large polygonal cells arranged in small nests (so-called Zellballen), which are separated by capillaries filled with erythrocytes.
Lung lesion showing squamous cell carcinoma with lymphatic invasion.
Adenocarcinoma of cervical esophagus arising from a patch of gastric-type mucosa with intestinal-type goblet cells.

A case of tubular breast carcinoma composed of well-differentiated rounded to angulated tubular structures organized haphazardly. A case of invasive ductal carcinoma not otherwise specified (NOS), grade 1, demonstrating tumor cells arranged in clusters.
Gliosarcoma. Mixed neoplastic population of two different and intermingled cell types. A distinct neoplastic cell population characterized by astrocytic-like cells.
Esophagus with severe transmural heterophilic inflammation and necrosis. High-grade diffuse infiltration with heterophils.
Low power view of Hodgkin lymphoma at the right side and Langerhans cell histiocytosis at the left side.
Cell-block section of a well differentiated papillary mesothelioma showing numerous small clusters of mesothelial cells with knobby borders.

Mixed histological type of gastric cancer in WHO classification. High differentiated tubular adenocarcinoma mixed with signet ring cell carcinoma and mucinous adenocarcinoma.
Adenocarcinoma cells in a specimen obtained by transbronchial biopsy.

Histopathological picture of a spindle cell sarcoma showing extensive necrosis in the upper part of the image with several foci containing microspheres. The bottom part of the image shows remaining neoplastic tissue with moderate lymphoplasmacytic inflammation. Hematoxylin and eosin stain.
Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma, activated subtype.

Photomicrographs of the surgically removed breast tissue show residual and viable invasive ductal carcinoma of no special type accompanied by fibrotic and inflammatory granulation tissue, along with a large number of arteries embolized with spherical particles.
Extrathyroidal invasion and intranuclear features of thyroid cancer cells with nuclear grooves.
5B14 mAb showed focal positivity in three out of eleven Burkitt's lymphoma specimens.

Prostate biopsy showing prostate acinar adenocarcinoma (Gleason score 3 + 4 = 7, grade group 2; percentage of Gleason pattern 4 equal to 40%; Gleason pattern 4 architecture fused glands). The tumor has spread to the periprostatic soft tissue composed of adipose and fibrous tissue and nerves. Fibrosis basically replaced the adipose tissue when infiltrated by cancer, i.e., stromal reaction. 10× magnification.
Representative photomicrographs of an tonsillar squamous cell carcinoma stained with human papillomavirus (HPV)  in situ  hybridization. All of staining results are interpreted as positive.
Malignant epithelial tumors. Endometrioid carcinoma. Glands are lined by columnar tumor cells with atypia resembling endometrioid carcinoma of uterus (H and E, ×40).
Biopsy of the liver lesion showed well-differentiated hepatocellular carcinoma.

Hematoxylin and eosin stains show a sarcomatous proliferation characterized by fascicles of medium/large size spindle cells with abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm and well-defined cell borders. The nuclei are spindle or oval with mild to marked atypia. Both typical and atypical mitotic activity is easily found, along with a mild lymphocytic infiltrate without necrosis.
A lymph node showing double hit follicular lymphoma with a follicular pattern of growth. B lymph node showing double hit follicular lymphoma.
100x, Hematoxylin and eosin (H&E) stain showing hyper-cellular glial neoplasm with marked nuclear atypia, geographic necrosis, and microvascular proliferation; consistent with glioblastoma.
Histological aspect of papillary thyroid carcinoma.
Dysplasia lesions of esophagus showing mild dysplasia.
Microscopic photography of pelvic lymph node metastasis showing the lymph node infiltrated with prostate adenocarcinoma.
Closer view of the atypical melanocytes along the dermal-epidermal junction in a lentigo maligna melanoma biopsy.
Tumor cells of histiocytic sarcoma.
Histological presentation of postauricular skin next to the melanoma.

Marked spongiosis with numerous eosinophils, consistent with allergic contact dermatitis, but no evidence of melanoma.
Collision tumour rectal GIST/prostatic adenocarcinoma. HE (50x).
Histological patterns of splenic marginal zone lymphoma (SMZL). Atrophic pattern, with an atrophic white pulp and few infiltrating cells in the red pulp.
Rhabdomyosarcoma.

Microscopic images demonstrating the replacement of the spleen tissue by large atypical lymphoid cells, with scattered large polygonal cells characterized by bizarre pleomorphic nuclei resembling the cells of anaplastic large cell lymphoma, and fewer cells with large atypical nuclei resembling Reed-Sternberg cells.
A moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma is present at the esophagogastric junction.

Adenomatous low-grade dysplasia in a columnar-lined esophagus with lack of surface maturation. Most of the glands are simple, round or angulated, with few dilated glands. Nuclear stratification and enlarged nucleo-cytoplasmic ratio are obvious. Nuclei are penicillated, located in the basal half of the cells, with readily identified mitoses.
Biopsy from a Barrett esophagus and eGCT showing overlying epithelium with goblet cell metaplasia.
The pathological report of the resected sample reveals a pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma.
Composite image showing cellularity, intact cell morphology, and different architectural patterns of lung adenocarcinoma in cell block preparation, with an acinar pattern.

Histologic section of a colonic adenoma containing invasive carcinoma. High grade mucosal neoplasia is strictly confined above the muscularis mucosae, whereas well differentiated adenocarcinoma extensively invades the submucosa.
Pathological findings of resected tumor in case 2 show glioblastoma.
Histopathologic Feature of Osteosarcoma and Cellular Cannibalism. Show malignant mesenchymal cells intermixed with disorganized bone and a number of cannibalistic cells (H&E stain).
Peritoneal mesothelioma: an epithelioid component with eosinophilic cytoplasm.
Nevoid melanoma: massive dermal invasion by a pigmented clonal proliferation with the destruction of hair follicles. The grenz zone is obscured, and the epidermis is elevated.
An example of renal cell carcinoma with papillary architecture.
Papillary thyroid carcinoma, tall cell variant. The tumour invades the parathyroid widely, by an infiltrative growth.
Well-differentiated leiomyosarcoma consisting of spindle cells arranged in intersecting fascicles.
NK/T cell lymphoma in bone marrow is not suspected by H&E stain.
Brown or basophilic granules are remarkably observed in the smooth muscles of the vein in the adventitia of the esophagus.
The lesion demonstrates papillary renal cell carcinoma.
The image shows lung adenocarcinoma, a round array of tumor cells with peripheral nuclear polarization.
Microscopic examination of periductal stromal sarcoma revealed nodules and coalesced nodules, which are separated by fibro-fatty tissue.
Needle biopsy specimen of the prostate showing an irregular arrangement of fused glands, indicative of poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma.  Gleason score = 8.
Parathyroid carcinoma shows mushrooming invasion through the capsule into the surrounding fat.
Smears showing clustered spindle and pleomorphic sarcomatous cells associated with pinkish/orange osteoid.
A case of endometrial carcinoma.
Loosely arranged cluster of pleomorphic sarcomatoid cells.
Round uniform nuclei, nucleoli, and perinuclear halos are observed, suggestive of a typical oligodendroglioma. The tumor cells are infiltrating into brain parenchyma.
Hematoxylin and eosin staining revealed a myxoid variant of a high-grade undifferentiated pleomorphic sarcoma with moderate inflammatory infiltration.
Expression of transducin (β)-like receptor 1 (TBLR1) in the nuclei of cells of primary diffuse large B-cell non-Hodgkin lymphoma (DLBCL). Low nuclear expression of TBLR1 in DLBCL; stage II × 400.
Well-differentiated adenocarcinoma of the colon composed of irregularly shaped glands and branching cords of tumor cells. The neoplastic glands are lined by tall columnar to cuboidal epithelium.
Synovial sarcoma with a population of monomorphic spindle cells and occasional gland-like spaces containing eosinophilic material.
Hepatocellular carcinoma composed of atypical hepatocytes arranged in a solid or trabecular growth pattern with normal hepatic parenchyma present.
Features of penile intraepithelial neoplasia in the glans of a patient with leiomyosarcoma, showing dysplastic epithelial cells in all squamous layers.
Histopathological findings of lung adenocarcinoma metastasis.

Photomicrograph of the edge of the dominant nodule, showing irregularly dilated follicles with pale colloid and subtle infoldings of the follicular epithelium. The follicular cells are uniform and evenly spaced, without features of papillary thyroid carcinoma (H&E, 100x).

Mantle cell lymphoma involving mucosa and submucosa. Malignant cells have the appearance of small atypical lymphocytes. The tumor was composed of small to medium-sized lymphoid cells with irregular nuclear contours, most closely resembling centrocytes. The nuclei had moderately dispersed chromatin but inconspicuous nucleoli. H and E, ×200.
Vascular spaces are lined by enlarged and hyperchromatic endothelial cells. Specimen is absent of necrotic or mitotic cells, which is consistent with low-grade angiosarcoma.
Histopathology showing H&E stain of a follicular lymphoma.
Histologic image of an esophageal biopsy revealing a dense lymphoplasmocytic infiltrate.
Hematoxylin and eosin stain showing primary pulmonary adenocarcinoma.
Histological section of the removed implant capsule at explantation shows benign pseudosynovial metaplasia and foreign body reaction to silicone material. No lymphoma is seen.
Representative results of VM in non-small cell lung cancer and control group. VM in moderately differentiated squamous cell carcinoma (red arrow is vessel, black arrow is VM) (grade 2).
Hematoxylin and eosin (H&E) staining showed poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma in the gastric tumor tissue.
Type 2 papillary renal cell carcinoma showing pseudostratified layers of cells with eosinophilic cytoplasm, atypical nuclei, and hemorrhage with transition to micropapillary areas.
Microscopic view of papillary thyroid cancer with intact thyroid capsule.
Epithelioid inflammatory myofibroblastic sarcoma showing epithelioid tumor cells with vesicular nuclei and prominent nucleoli admixed with numerous neutrophils.
Prostate adenocarcinoma, original tumor.
Representative biopsy from the oesophageal mucosa presenting with ulcerated surface and granulation tissue, but without granulomas or morphological signs of fungi or viral infection.

Photomicrograph showing (a) malignant cells with marked nuclear pleomorphism (#) and the presence of a multinucleated tumor giant cell (*) and (b) sarcomatoid areas with spindled cells in a myxomatous background.
Hematoxylin and eosin view of a bronchoscopic transbronchial pulmonary sample showing primary lung adenocarcinoma with lepidic non mucinous and acinar patterns.
Metastasis of colorectal adenocarcinoma in lymph node with epithelial neoplastic proliferation, cribiform pattern, and comedonecrosis.
Lacunar resorption pits formed on a dentine slice in a 21-day coculture of human PBMCs with Ewing's sarcoma-derived fibroblasts.

Pathological specimen showing low-grade chondrosarcoma with unclear margins and invasion of the surrounding soft tissue. The nuclei of the tumor varied in size, had a disordered arrangement, and obvious atypia.
Histologic evaluation of the biopsy core demonstrating Gleason score 9 (4 + 5) adenocarcinoma of the prostate gland.
Histopathology of intramedullary metastasis from lung adenocarcinoma using hematoxylin and eosin staining.
Pathological diagrams of endometrium showing poorly differentiated endometrial carcinoma with increased lymphocytes infiltrating the cervical endometrium.
Post-operative histological examination showing fibrosarcoma. Hematoxylin and eosin staining.

Chondrosarcoma section showing large and well-differentiated basophilic cells with large nuclei distributed individually in lacunae and surrounded by a hyaline ground substance, with multiple chondrocytes per lacuna.

Normal esophageal mucosa with stratified squamous epithelium and no inflammatory cells present.

Histopathology images of cardiac intimal sarcoma showing cells arranged in spindles with high mitotic activity and extensive necrosis.

Paired cytological sample and surgical sample of pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma (PDAC) showing PDAC cells with Hematoxylin and Eosin stain in cell block.

Core biopsy of the prostate: Hematoxylin and eosin stain revealed small cell carcinoma cells forming diffuse solid sheets with infiltration of prostatic muscle fibers and narrow cords with some areas of necrosis. Tumor cells demonstrated mild to moderate pleomorphism with high nuclear to cytoplasmic ratio, crowded round to irregular nuclei containing chromatin. There was no acinus formation or any component of adenocarcinoma, urothelial carcinoma, squamous cell carcinoma, or sarcomatoid carcinoma. Core biopsy of the left and right seminal vesicles demonstrated identical findings.
Histology of cervical angiosarcoma, showing anastomosing vascular channels with nuclear atypia.  Fig. 1.
Biopsy of the upper lobe of the left lung indicated infiltration of lung adenocarcinoma. HE staining.
Endometrioid carcinoma. The tumor mass destructed the ovarium. The endometrial cyst wall was found.
Angiomatoid fibrous histiocytoma (AFH) with high-grade transformation to round blue cell sarcoma. Interface between classic and high-grade areas. 4x magnification.
Malignant Melanoma treated with CNT/Ag NPs. Histopathologic evaluation shows extensive necrosis (about 70% necrosis) with isolated tumor remnant islands (×100) H&E.

Esophageal biopsy showing iron deposition in the lamina propria covered by an intact epithelium.
Microphotographs showing the appearance of anaplastic large cell lymphoma in the capsule surrounding an implant. Most cases are of a B-cell phenotype.
Tissue preparation within which tumor proliferation nests or cords may be observed, immediately below the esophageal epithelium showing signs of hyperplasia with acanthosis and papillomatosis.
Morphology of extranodal NK/T cell lymphoma, nasal type (ENKTL). Medium-sized tumor cells with apoptotic bodies.
